post_caption:
#BalloInSingapore Day 7
There are few hours in life more agreeable than the hour dedicated to the ceremony known as afternoon tea.
Emily had Mindy and Ballo has- Pinky Pinky Sharma who suggested we go for high tea similar to Duchess of Bedford  Anna (year 1840) who made the tradition of sipping tea and nibbling sandwiches in middle of afternoon fashionable .
But we are crazy (not so rich) Asians , we will enjoy the British tradition in Singapore . 
It was so much fun to meet women with pink hats all together to raise awareness about breast cancer by meeting and donating at high tea event .
When was the last time you went for high tea asks Ballo.

Revisited Punggol Waterway to Coney Island on bike couple of weeks back. Was a nice, chill way to spend a morning on a weekday, with only a couple of old uncles hanging out amongst the Casuarina groves on Coney Island. Varied terrain from well-paved paths to unpaved dirt. Avoided the beach areas because the last time I was there, the sandflies were vicious! Sad that I dropped the cam which now has scratched lens (hence what looks like a permanent water droplet in middle of video 😩) Best were the yummy chicken wings at WingZone Punggol end of the ride. It was a bright day (sunburn liao) and I followed @photographyholic, @vincentphotogram and @ongwill to Kampung Lorong Buangkok - a neighborhood dearly loved by many Singaporeans as we wish we could have chicken running around in our backyard and a mango tree beside the house with the mango hanging outside the window.

Uncle Sng was very friendly and it was a good long chat with Saiful too, which shared the vantage point to shoot his house like a drone without a drone 😬

Believe it or not, it was my first time coming here, and I think next time I would sit for a kopi and pisang goreng. Anyone wants to join?

All pictures from #Pixel3 cos I brought #NikonZ6 with big fat lens and yet forgot to put the XQD card inside, and yes no one else shoots that that card. 😅

PS. If you go there for some shots, please be respectful. The aunty at the yellow house is quite old and she needs her nap in the afternoon, please be quiet. Keep in mind you are in private property although there is no fence for some of the houses. This is not a zoo and these people are not a display for your camera. This is their home, their life. If you have a few minutes to say hi and chat, you will leave with a lot of stories like I did today.

-Culture-

Built in 1900, this colorful house used to be the house of Tan Teng Niah, a businessman that owned sweet-making factories! It is situated in Little India, an area that I have only explored a few times during school trips or as a “tour guide” for my foreign friends!

What I truly miss about traveling is the freedom to roam the streets randomly and learning about the heritage and the way of life of the locals. While travel is still on hold, I am bringing this wanderlust to rediscover Singapore as I explore a different part of the country weekly, and I am not disappointed at all!

Anyone else wanna explore other parts of Singapore together?
Life is tough but so are you

An illustration of Victoria Theatre and concert hall, one of Singapore’s oldest performing art centre with its classic European architectural style.

I had made an effort to drop by one of the day to look at this historic landmark to gather details, perspective and depth of the building.

It has been a challenge for me as this illustration take me lots of focus. It has in another way help push my skill forward, enable me to have a deeper knowledge and understanding of art and illustration.

I am happy to share this illustration with @munping23 of @theartshouse. Thanks for the support you give. 

這是我畫的新加坡維多利亞劇院插圖， 新加坡市中心其中一個頂尖表演藝術中心。
畫這經典地標對我來說是個挑戰，不過它也把我的技能推向另一個程度讓我對美術有更深層次的認識和理解。

This pretty shop selling Arabic-style lights looks like a typical shop in Turkey but it is actually located in Kampong Glam right here in Singapore!

Kampong Glam is an eclectic blend of history, culture and a trendy lifestyle scene. Traditional stores selling textile and handicrafts, such as the one seen here, exist happily alongside hipster cafes and designer labels.

Do you know that #KampongGlam was once designated for the Malay royalty? 😏

TEAGIF FRIDAY SERIES

In this edition of our TeaGIF live stream, we are going to visit @killineysg, one of Singapore’s oldest coffee shops and has its Killiney Road outlet being recognised in Singapore Book of Records 2008 as the ‘Oldest Existing Hainanese Coffeshop’. We will bring you behind the scenes at Killiney Lor Telok outlet, and its instant coffee/tea mix factory at Chin Bee, where their instant coffee is proudly Made-in-Singapore!

Highlights: Speak to coffee masters, learn the 'secrets' of Killiney's coffee and kaya, access to Killiney's instant coffee factory to understand how instant coffee is produced

🎥 Killiney Kopitiam
— From Coffee shop to Factory 🎥
Date: Fri 16 October
Time: 1030hrs-1115hrs (GMT+8)

Bussiness goes on. . . Earning a living after the circuit breaker. The last of Singapore’s streetside barber start his busssiness during the phase one.

Undying dedication to his trade and a master of the art, the one old-school barber. Streetside barbers used to be a thriving industry back then. Haircuts, and shave has been his passion for the last 56 years. A "A+" classic... .
.
Mr Lee is located behind Moosehead along Telok Ayer Street and he usually opens from 10.30am-4pm from Mon-Fri and 10.30am-3pm on Sat. To make an appointment, call him at 97712146. I am so wanting to try nostril hair trim 😄

There's more to this city than meets the eye. In between our concrete skyscrapers and towering metal cranes, there are plenty of Insta-worthy urban street arts that simply take your breath away. From the graffiti (approved by local authority) that’s hidden in plain sight to pieces that lurk away in the backstreets, each street art tells a different story and their heritage.
.

I love old neighbourhood where you find old gem like this! Although it has been closed for many years but one can imagine how it was like in its heydays back in the 70s where it’s considered as a high class barber and beauty salon!

This shop is like a time capsule where time stood still. Can you guess when they cease operation based on these photos?

#ShotOniPhone #iPhone11ProMax

Rojak Flower / Torch Ginger Flower / Bunga Kantan. Delighted to see it again. It used to grow in our garden and mom would simply add it to a dinner salad. Finely julienned, a whisper of it  adds a distinct floral note to our local hawker favourite Rojak. If the Rojak man didn't display it in his store window, Auntie F would refuse to order it. It's also used in Penang Assam Laksa, which if you're lucky enough to have the real thing, is one of the most umami loaded seafood briny noodle soup we know of. 
.

Minds are like flowers; they open only when the time is right. – Stephen Richards

I saw the blooming sidewalks just outside Bishan MRT from the bus on my way for my checkup. I decided to stroll down to the next stop after to enjoy this little butterfly garden just beside a busy road 💚❤️💙 

I hope it gives you pleasure just as it did me 🙏 Taking time just to experience is so #therapeutic! 

1. Arundina graminifolia; Common Name: Bamboo Orchid, Bird Orchid, Kinta Weed, Phanyar, 竹兰, 竹叶兰
2. Kopsia
3. Cuphea hyssopifolia, the false heather, Mexican heather, Hawaiian heather or elfin herb

Discovered this majestic instagram-worthy #wallmural (Titled Medley Alley) with @photographyholic at one of the small side laneways of lively Katong. According to what I read online, this eclectic mural that united the two walls in #MedleyAlley form wings made of colourful Peranakan tiles, and the wall art represent the metamorphosis between generations. 

Also found out that this piece of art was one of the many that were painted for the #KatongJooChiatArtCircuit, in hope to revitalise Katong and JooChiat area. Next time when you are around the area, try and see if you are able to find them for pictures and #ootd.

New Listing on Tropika Club: Enso Hair Studio (Raffles Place)

There's a new premium salon on the block. Enso Hair Studio is the go-to salon in the heart of Singapore's CBD. They're aiming for the stars, carving a place in Singapore's hair industry underneath the towers of Raffles City. The hair artists are skilled at providing hair solutions such as hair styling, hair colouring, blowouts, hair texturing, as well as hair and scalp care. Need a proper perm? This artisan salon also provides root perms, fringe perms, and hair rebonding services. Heading out for the evening? Get an Evening Upstyle at this hair salon before you conquer the night.

Exploring the Culture & Heritage side of Singapore.

Sultan Mosque or Masjid Sultan is a mosque located at Muscat Street and North Bridge Road within the Kampong Glam precinct of the district of Rochor in Singapore. It was named after Sultan Hussain Shah. In 1975, it was designated a national monument. Source: Wikipedia

Five international dance troupes will be celebrating this Mid-Autumn Festival "together" by putting up an online Chinese dance performance on 30 September 2020 (Eve of the Mid-Autumn Festival). 

The concert will feature dances from Atlanta Chinese Dance Company (USA), 一般社団法人 中国舞踊サロン Chinese Dance Salon - CDS (Tokyo, Japan), 澳門英姿舞園 Macau Ieng Chi Dance Association (Macau SAR), 新加坡华族舞蹈剧场 Singapore Chinese Dance Theatre (Singapore), and Shadow Danceland 影子舞团 (Mauritius).

Do join us at our respective Facebook page on 30 September 2020 at SGT 8pm (GMT +8) to watch the “live” stream. Don’t miss it!

Since we posted about our trip to River Safari yesterday, here are more pictures of pandas because we simply love 🐼🐼! We only saw a sleeping Kai Kai the panda when we were there, so here are photos of us having panda buns at Mama Panda kitchen and cuddling a cute panda plushie at the store just outside the panda enclosure. 

Mummy says ok to having panda buns because we can all eat it and it's yummy. She also ordered a panda cappuccino for herself. 😆 We almost bought the panda plushie but we put it back since there are too many plushies waiting for us at home. 

The Mini Kays' mantra ➡️ food over plushies. 😄😁

The zebra dove (Geopelia striata) also known as barred ground dove, is a bird of the dove family, Columbidae, native to Southeast Asia. They are small birds with a long tail, predominantly brownish-grey in colour with black-and-white barring. They are known for their pleasant soft, staccato cooing calls. ~ Wikipedia

I used to dread that the house is facing the rising sun as it can get real hot in the daytime. But ever since I have learnt to enjoy watching the sunrise, I feel so blessed to get such scenic view from the start of the day in the comfort of my house.  So learn to accept things as they are! 

William

<358> “Teleported Colonial Building!”

At first glance, it looked as if a colonial house from more than a hundred years ago has been teleported to the present times!

The truth is this pair of Edwardian era (1901-1910) semi-detached houses known as Winsland House II at Penang Road (near Dhoby Ghaut)has existed since the  1910s. While its surroundings had completely transformed, it has stood the test of time.

William

You’re never too young to pick up printmaking! These young makers are the living testaments as they joined us in our last holiday programme.⁣
⁣
The younger kids eagerly created their imprints using print foam & various blunt tools while the older ones carved their designs with soft lino blocks.⁣
⁣
At the end of the session everyone got to tote back their own designed & printed bag! Hope you all had a fantastic printmaking adventure & can’t wait for another one soon!⁣

GRATITUDE FROM THE HEART 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Lloyd's Inn Singapore: To all guests (past, present, future), thank you for your support. We are proud to say that during the last few months, trying as they may be, we neither cut wages nor let go of staff. This is because of the support from the local staycation market. In fact, we are hiring additional members to the team. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Every booking made supports consumption in the domestic tourism industry. Every staycation supports the livelihood of our team. Although business is not as optimal as pre-Covid times, we endeavour to preserve the staycation spirit for as best as we can. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In our in-room guide, we have curated local experiences one can enjoy and explore. On social media, we will continue sharing our own travel experiences within Singapore via #lloydsinnexplores. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We do encourage all locals to visit the attractions and experiences around Singapore. With the $100 #SingapoRediscovers incentive given by the government, spending it either on Staycations or exploring new sights, it is a cause we support for the local tourism industry. A little spending from each person goes a long way in supporting someone else's livelihood.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We champion for an inclusive nation with mutual support and hope to offer other tourism businesses support as well. Thank you all for your support, and see you really soon at Lloyd's Inn or around Singapore! More on stories today on our team behind-the-scenes >>>
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] - Traditional Popiah

Rediscovery is about walking and finding unique place.  

As I rediscovered Joo Chiat, I came across Kway Guan Huat Joo Chiat - a traditional  Popiah maker since 1938 I was intrigued by the skill of those making the traditional popiah skin from dough. Great to see Chinese Fujian food culture still active and alive for over 80 years. It is also interesting to note that it coexisted for so many years next to the Malay enclave ( Geylang Serai) - Another reminder of our unique racial harmonious culture of Singapore.

I submitted this entry of a photo I took in May 2018, shortly before these iconic and colorful Rochor Centre buildings were demolished, for #shapesofhome and titled this as “Home At The End Of A Rainbow” because this is what I think people should aspire to find instead of that highly touted pot of gold. Also the cheery and colorful sight of these buildings, that mark the district area of Bugis, now long gone, are bound to evoke a sense of #nostalgia for those in the know. And nostalgia is great because it means that we remember and are emotional about #heritage. These buildings also set the tone for future HDB flats by creating a splashing impact and timeless appreciation for them.

“Like many Singaporeans, I’m a great fan of Mustafa Centre. This place started its journey as a makeshift shop set up by Mohamed Mustafa and his son to sell ready-made garments on Campbell Lane. Over the years, Mustafa Centre was gradually built up from one shop to two large buildings along Syed Alwi Road. It was only in 2003 that Mustafa Centre became a 24-hour shopping centre, now with some adjustments to its operating hours. Not to worry – you can still buy almost anything there!”
 
Captured by @darrensohphoto as part of #SingapoRediscovers – comment below to share your favourite part of Mustafa Centre!

post_caption:
【Sengkang #2 - Egg Tart & Siew Pau】
Occupying 24,000 square metres, the “Arts in the Park” is a sculpture garden specially-designed for the residents of Sengkang. Look out for the “Waves” sculptures which reminds us of Sengkang past as a fishing village and harbour. Many colourful textured ball sculptures are also designed to allow park users to simply sit back and laze on them. Put Sengkang Sculpture Park on the top of your to-do list when you visit Sengkang.

Our featured dimsum pastries are a satisfying snack for any time of the day. Traditionally a Cantonese cuisine, it was said that the origin of the egg tart was inspired by the English custard tart and Portuguese egg tarts. And instead of featuring the usual steamed Char Siew Pau, we’ve selected the ‘baked’ version where juicy BBQ pork is wrapped in crispy and buttery pastry. 

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop, and keep a lookout for these savoury yummies in the window display. Best paired with a steaming glass of fragrant Kopi-O-Gao! Shiok!

Chinatown⁠
⁠
Long before the arrival of Raffles in 1819, a small immigrant Chinese population had already settled in Singapore, cultivating gambier and pepper. When Singapore’s free port was established, more Chinese and other immigrants flocked to its shores. For easy administration, Raffles grouped various immigrant communities into ethnic quarters. In his 4 November 1822 letter to the Town Committee the area from the “Boat Quay southwest bank of the Singapore River” was designated a Chinese Kampong. This self-contained kampong or community settlement became the home of many Chinese immigrants, and a transit point for coolies (unskilled labourers) going to Malaya. That kampong and Chinese centre grew, eventually becoming Chinatown.⁠
⁠
The original kampong was divided into zones, a sector for each Chinese community of the same provincial origin and dialect group.⁠
⁠
Different trades were confined to specific areas, so each street took on its own identity. From delicacies to death-houses, there were businessmen, traders, craftsmen, hawkers and peddlers to provide all of the peoples’ needs. ⁠
⁠
Chinatown has become Singapore’s largest Historic District. Its four sub-districts – Bukit Pasoh, Kreta Ayer, Telok Ayer and Tanjong Pagar – were given conservation status in the late 1980s. Much of the town has changed, but fortunately, remnants of its colourful past are still present and old traditions have endured. During festivals such as the Lunar New Year, and the Mid-autumn Festival, there are celebrations and festive shopping. Always dressed for the occasion, Chinatown would be colourful, lit up and abuzz with activity, attracting not just the Chinese but other locals as well as tourists.⁠
⁠.⁠
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg⁠

Mini Bath Tubs
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 °C (160 °F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

HDB Kim Tian Green
Kim Tian Road, Singapore

Little India is filled with vibrant colours that represent its rich culture and heritage. Besides Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple on Serangoon Road, one of the oldest temples in Singapore that was built in 1881, you can also explore Shree Lakshminarayan Temple, Singapore’s first dedicated place of worship for Northern Indian Hindus.
 
Some other buildings that caught my eye over the years are two historical churches – Kampong Kapor Methodist Church and Church of the True Light. Not forgetting the Abdul Gafoor Mosque and the eclectic exterior of Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple. All these buildings add unexpectedly to the vibrant facade of Little India.
 
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your own pictures with #SingapoRediscovers.

Family Wefie
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

Scenes from Sago Street

Singapore’s Chinatown precinct has been one of my favorite places to photograph since moving to this country about 18 months ago. It’s a bustling area where new and old traditions blend together, and there’s always something interesting to point the camera at. It’s a place full of life, but starting around the 1920s, Chinatown’s Sago Street and Sago Lane were also a place full of death.

In that time, the area was home to many lower class Chinese immigrants. Superstition dictated that it was bad luck to die within one’s own home, and proper funerals were costly. Out of that sad reality came a pragmatic solution: death houses. For a small fee, the sick and elderly could live out their remaining days on the second floor of a death house. The first floor was reserved for funeral services.

Due to the poor conditions in death houses, the practice was eventually banned in 1961. Nowadays, all traces of the death houses have vanished, and the area between Sago Street and Sago Lane is the site of the well-known Buddha Tooth Relic Temple.

Indian Heritage Centre
Campbell Lane
Singapore

Sony ILCE-9M2
FE 16-35mm F2.8 GM
1/160, sec, f/2.8, ISO 3200

Did you know that the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India?

This is the first time I’ve actually explored Little India and glad that I’ve taken some photos of this unique place as a souvenir. 

There was even a friendly man telling me where I should take my photos and led me to a flock of pigeons which I’ve failed to capture the scene nicely because I didn’t have the right lens setup at that time.

I would say this is the most fruitful photography session I’ve done in Singapore. I am also glad to have my first shoot this year (though tired of clocking 12k steps in that few hours) as the pandemic has kept us at home for the most part of the year.
.
.

Shooting the Masjid Sultan - or Sultan Mosque - and Bussorah Street as they should be experienced: a pair 🕌 #SeteMilKmEmSingapura ⠀
⠀
This neighbourhood has been here for 200 years and is Singapore's Arab Quarter, but the truth is you can find touches of soooo many cultures in Kampong Glam! The area offers a unique mix of Malay, Chinese, European, Indonesian and Islamic architecture, cuisine and art - I love how walking around Singapore feels like visiting several different countries at once ❤️⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Foto da Masjid Sultan - ou Mesquita do Sultão - e da Rua Bussorah, que ficam ainda mais lindas juntas! 🕌 ⠀
⠀
Essa área é habitada há 200 anos e é conhecida como o bairro muçulmano de Singapura, mas a verdade é que você vai encontrar toques de muuuuitas culturas em Kampong Glam! O bairro tem uma mistura única de arquitetura, culinária e arte malaia, chinesa, européia, indonésia e muçulmana - AMO como os passeios em Singapura parecem uma viagem por vários países! ❤️⠀

Stack it up! Designed by Paul Rudolph, The Concourse is an iconic 41-storey office with retail space along Singapore’s famed ‘Golden Mile’ strip.

Boasting a beautiful post-modern geometric façade and stunning atrium lobby, the building was designed with a ‘tropical skyscraper’ concept. Its unique octagonal shape is also inspired by the number 8, associated with prosperity in Chinese culture.

Lately, I've been going around the touristy/non-touristy places to take photos. This has made me to discover and learn quite a number of things along the way.

Most importantly, it forces me to think out of the box, and create new perspective of the common scenes in Singapore, so as to make my photos more interesting to look at (hopefully). 

The walks have also reminded me that Singapore is a very interesting country. Like our hawker centre where you can find food from all over the world, Singapore has places that resembles all over the world too. So no more excuses to tell myself that Singapore is a "boring" place for photography because it is definitely not one!

A tip for those who wants to try doing this. Imagine you are a visitor from overseas paying $1k on air ticket to visit Singapore. How would you have made the trip worth it?

Me the local tourist returned to childhood. 

This place reminds me of the kopithiam (not the brand: kopithiam that ruined the traditional image) that my grandfather brought me to when I was a kiddo. I was forced to drink milo off the saucer while he enjoyed his coffee with a piece of gu you in it! WHY CAN I HAVE GU YOU IN MY MILO? 

I can’t remember when is the last time I have gu you in my coffee and my bet was more than a decade, or two. 

I wish I had seated closer to the uncle and mesmerise his act of this traditional trade. 

I want to go back again, and again, and again. 

Who else wanna join me?

The Japanese Cemetery was a place I really wanted to visit post circuit breaker, and I’m glad I did. Build not only to commemorate various renowned Japanese figures who made an impact on Singapore, the place offers a gorgeous space that many can revel in whilst paying respects to the fallen.  I even got chance to interact with the janitor, who says he cleans the cemetery without fail everyday. Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It’s an opportunity to re-live our nation’s history while tuning into modern narratives of “hidden” spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

We took the kids to Mega Bounce @megaadventuresingapore @sentosa_island on Saturday. It was their first time trying bungee trampolines and turned out to be a pretty fun experience for them. Took a little getting used to initially but they were soon happily bouncing on the trampolines (can't do flips and turns yet though 😆).
.
The activity is only for 5 minutes ($15 usual price or ten tokens from the Sentosa fun pass), so we bought for 10 minutes each with our Sentosa fun passes. It really just cost us $10 each child as we bought the Mastercard 1-for-1 fun pass promo which gives us 2 fun passes with 60 tokens each at $60.
.
Turned out ten minutes were just enough for them as it was pretty hot (you can jump with your nose uncovered under your mask but my girls were OK covered up) and they said their harnesses were starting to feel a lil uncomfortable near the end. But they would definitely like to return for it another time!
.
We were all pretty beat by the end of the day because of the hot weather 😅 How was your weekend? 😊

my whole heart❤️💛💙 

(Pc: @weishuenn)

Pretty thrilled to be able to take out the shoes, feel the sands, brisk walking along the beach early in the morning.

. 
.
. 
1. Marina South Pier to St. John's Island (9.00am), then take the shuttle ferry from St. John's to Sisters' Island (10.00am)
2. Sisters' Island to Kusu Island (11.20am)
3. Kusu Island to St. John's Island (1.00pm/2.30pm)
4. Explore St. John's Island, 15-20min walk to Lazarus Island
5. St. John's Island back to Marina South Pier (4.00pm/6.00pm)
.
*Note: Our shuttle ferry is available on weekends/ph schedule only

This Mid-Autumn Festival, @gardensbythebay is offering a brand-new festival experience - with a mixture of both online and offline programmes.

Take a stroll through the gorgeous Apricot Grove or watch the Royal Family's Walk display, which was first displayed at the Seoul Lantern Festival last year.

Another highlight of the festival is the Colonnade of Lights display which showcases 1,500 paper lanterns thoughtfully painted by the community and Gardens by the Bay's senior workers.

Besides these displays, they also offer hands-on activities such as learning how to make a snowskin mooncake or a DIY Good-Luck knot. If you're unable to make it down, you can still participate through the virtual space where exciting performances await you!

The festival and virtual programmes will be launched on 18 Sep and lasts till 4 Oct so mark your calendars now!

Entry is free so share this post with your friends and jio them for a Mid-Autumn outing!

🏡The Residence of Tan Teng Niah
.
A brightly colored landmark that stands along the arts belt in Little India. It is the last remaining Chinese villa in the history of Little India, Singapore.
Tan Teng Niah, a successful businessman who owned a confectionary business and various other smaller businesses, built the villa in 1900 for his wife. The Residence of Tan Teng Niah won the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention Award in 1991.
Was it always this colourful? The Residence of Tan Teng Niah villa was originally whitewashed. The colors were added fairly recently.
Found along Kerbau Road, it is probably one of the most photographed buildings in Little India.
.

295/365
Takumar 50mm F1.4
Sony a7RIII
Today, I didn’t feel like I was getting “the shot.” When I am in that mental state, I start blaming the weather conditions, locations, lack of interesting subjects, etc. And everything I shoot start to look like they are bad. But @sixstreetunder said in his Skillshare class that you have to know that “the moment” may not come that day. Maybe something that you expected may not happen. You need to always adjust yourself to the changing moment. It’s what street photography is about. 
So, I decided to read an art book of Monet’s paintings to broaden my perspective. It said “Don’t see objects before you such as houses, clouds, statues, as what they are but see them as geometric shapes with colors.” The perspective made sense when I went outside. I was just thinking too much about the subjects. I’ll let go of the stress and just try to enjoy the moment.
.
.
.
.
.

I’ve been taking this online course by @jordhammond about travel photography. It cleared out questions I had about how to do travel photography. 
.
It’s been great experience, but most of the successful examples I see in his videos are way different from my current style and I’m not sure to what extent I should stick to “my style” and how much I should skew my style to more appealing look while keeping my personality.
I know my look isn’t appealing to majority of people, but I don’t want to sell my soul just to gain popularity...nor do I want to stay where I am and not be successful.
It’s a struggle. Hmmm 🤔

“One thing I really love about Little India is its rich culture and history that also live within unassuming hotel buildings.
 
Many of the smaller hotels in Little India such as The Daulat and Perak Hotel started off as shophouses, and what’s not known to many is that Hotel 81 Rochor was first built just before the Second World War. The Great Madras also takes up a building that has been proudly perched on Madras Street since the 1940s.”
 
Captured by @darrensohphoto as part of #SingapoRediscovers – capture your own hidden gem in Little India and hashtag us too! 
 
#PassionMadePossible

<341> “Running From A Hill To Another”

Can you imagine running from a hill to another via a bridge? 

As a young boy who grew up in Telok Blangah, I always had to chose between Mount Faber or Telok Blangah Hill for hiking. It’s too much a hassle to go up and down two hills at one go. 

The two neighbouring hills, which were then separated by a road, is now connected by a stylish wave-shaped bridge. The bridge’s shape creates shell-like sheltered spaces where visitors can rest and enjoy the scenery. But these resting areas have been closed by the authorities to avoid gathering of crowds.

Since there is no place to take a breather, I ran across the beautiful bridge as fast as I could like the man in front of me! 

William

Covid in Singapore update: daily cases keep doing down (some days there are 0 new cases!! 😍) and last night it was announced phase 3 of the reopening could start before the end of the year! #SeteMilKmEmSingapura⠀
⠀
We've been on phase 2 since June, with most businesses open and groups of 5 people allowed to gather. On phase 3 bigger crowds could enter venues (up to 50 people) and groups would increase from 5 to 8 people - I don't even think I know 8 people here yet so no changes for me 😂⠀
⠀
The news *everyone* is waiting for is when the borders will open again. We are technically allowed to leave, but even residents returning to Singapore need to quarantine in a hotel for 14 days, so travel is basically out of the question 💸 Tourists from New Zealand, Brunei, Vietnam and Australia are allowed entry without quarantine, but we can't travel there... Hopefully our first "travel bubble" - no quarantine both ways! - will happen soon! 🤞⠀
⠀
📸 Shot with the help of @blondiewanderlust ⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Update covid em Singapura: os casos continuam diminuindo (em alguns dias temos 0 novos casos!! 😍) e anunciaram que a fase 3 de reabertura pode começar antes do fim do ano.⠀
⠀
Estamos na fase 2 desde junho, com a maioria dos estabelecimentos abertos e grupos de até 5 pessoas liberados. Na fase 3 grupos maiores vão poder participar de eventos (no máximo 50 pessoas) e seria liberado juntar 8 pessoas - o que não vai mudar nada na minha vida, acho que ainda nem conheço 8 pessoas aqui em Singapura 😂⠀
⠀
Mas a notícia que *todo mundo* tá esperando ansiosamente é quando as fronteiras vão reabrir. Tecnicamente a gente pode viajar, mas até residentes voltando pra Singapura precisam pagar por uma quarentena de 14 dias num hotel, então na prática não rola 💸 Turistas da Nova Zelândia, Brunei, Vietnã e Austrália podem vir pra cá sem quarentena, mas a gente não pode entrar lá... Torcendo pra nossa primeira "bolha de viagem" - sem quarentena na ida e na volta! - ser confirmada logo! 🤞

Nothing beats having hightea with your friend and thinking of what to eat for dinner next 😂👍🏻

Fort Gate, entrance to the British fort completed in 1860. Fort Canning was named after then-Governor-General of India, Lord Charles John Canning. It was built to protect Singapore from seaborne attacks. Fort Gate, the main entrance, faced the beach. A second purpose of the Fort was to be a refuge for the European population in the event of local unrest. #rediscoversg #singaporediscovers #whatmakessg #mysingapore

When I accidentally dress like my surroundings (part 2).

Chanced upon this row Peranakan shophouses just next to the bustling East Coast Road. This area - Joo Chiat/Katong - is fast becoming my favourite place to explore. Having been here thrice in the last month, especially when I live at the other end of Singapore, should be a testament to Joo Chiat/Katong’s allure.

Aside from photographing these well-preserved Peranakan houses, this area has a plethora of good food! There’s famous shops selling almost every dish that’s representative of Singapore, with my favourite being “Delicious Boneless Chicken Rice” at Katong Shopping Centre.

While it’s debatable whether chicken rice is a national dish, there’s definitely no debate that eating is our national past time. Couple that with a stroll within this historic precinct will make anyone’s experience a truly local one!

| Into the dark
• Sony a6000 + SEL55210 •

While I love bright bold colours that daytime photography can give me, it's quite tough to catch much sunlight after office hours.  So instead, I'm learning to embrace and enjoy night photography. Thankfully, Singapore has so much to offer at night. Bright LED lights from skyscrapers in the CBD area and bustling roads filled with cars almost 24/7. I'm never disappointed when I head out into the night after work is over.

For this set of photos, I chose 3 iconic brands with logos that stand out in the midst of the darkness.

Dreaming of another staycation at the @mo_singapore ✨ Lately I’ve found myself watching back my IGTV with snippets from our stay and wishing I could go back in time... ⠀
⠀
Now that travel is off the table, I’ll try to spend a couple of days enjoying a staycation in Singapore every so often to take a mental break from 2020. Some people might find it silly to pay for a hotel in the city you live in, but a little change of scenery and routine helps so much! I can’t wait to do it again 😍⠀
⠀
📸 Shot with the help of @blondiewanderlust ❤⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Sonhando com outra staycation no Mandarin Oriental ✨ Esses dias me peguei assistindo o IGTV que postei com uns pedacinhos das nossas ~mini férias~ e deu uma saudade... Agora que viajar parece algo que a gente fazia em outra vida, quero tentar passar uns 2 dias num hotel de vez em quando pra pelo menos lembrar como era a sensação de acordar em outro lugar.⠀
⠀
Pode parecer besteira (e um desperdício) pagar por um hotel na sua própria cidade, mas num ano em que todos os meses se misturam numa coisa só, uma mudança de cenário e rotina ajuda a renovar as energias. Já estou pensando quando vai ser a próxima 😍 #SeteMilKmEmSingapura⠀
⠀
⚠ P.S. Estou falando da realidade de Singapura, onde os casos estão sob controle, as medidas sanitárias, de rastreamento/isolamento são exemplares, tem multas pra pessoas e estabelecimentos que não cumprem as regras etc. Mesmo com a vida por aqui entrando num "novo normal" (como odeio esse termo! 😂), só postei 6 fotos nos últimos 6 meses porque a última coisa que quero é incentivar alguém a se arriscar. ⠀
⠀
Mas países e cidades diferentes têm realidades diferentes e infelizmente vai ser assim por muito tempo... Posso fazer um post detalhando as medidas que estão nos ajudando a viver de uma forma mais tranquila por aqui, me digam se interessa a alguém ou se só a nerd aqui acha isso interessante? 😆

post_caption:
<361> “Do you know where to look for eagles?”

Do you know there is a place to watch eagles 🦅 flying in the skies? 

I was searching high up for eagles through an circular structure situated at the end of the boardwalk. The blue sky was unbelievably beautiful filled with thin layers of clouds, but there was no sight of any eagle.

Surely there must be eagles in this place known as the Eagle Point at Sungei Buloh Wetland Reserve. So I set my sights further and lower.  There, an eagle was swooping down close to the sea as if it was hunting for fish.  But it was too far for my phone camera to capture a close-up. Perhaps, I should really get myself a better camera one day. 

Still, I was delighted to catch a glimpse of an eagle!

William

MID-AUTUMN FESTIVAL 2020 returns at @gardensbythebay 
Till 4 October, 7pm to 10pm (lantern sets’ light-up)
.
We are always amazed by the Garden’s mid-autumn displays!
.
This year, we all love the “Apricot Grove” filled with colourful garden-themed walking isle, and of course the “Water Song” exhibit that reminds us to cherish precious moments with our loved ones.
.
Check out the Colonnade of Lights and Illumination of Joy where some 1,500 colourful lantern sets lined up the corridor.
.
What about online? Watch Chinese dance duet by Li Ruimin and Zheng Long, a performance on 26 Sep, 8.00pm, on Gardens by the Bay's Facebook Page.
.
Make a family trip to The Gardens! There are officers around to ensure safe distancing measures and make sure all wear masks 😷
.
Happy Mid-Autumn!
.

Located at south bridge road the heart of Chinatown, this beautiful old Hindu temple is the oldest Hindu temple in Singapore. 
When you get a chance to stand in front of this temple, You will appreciate and enjoy looking at the structures of this beautiful temple, Sri Mariamman Temple, founded by Mr Naraina Pillai a pioneer social entrepreneur and businessman. 
Built in 1827, the temple is dedicated to Goddess Mariamman, known for her power in curing epidemic illinesses and diseases. 
Be blessed, Stay safe & healthy. 🤗🤗🤗

【Sengkang #3 - Herbal Soup】
Well known for its calmness and tranquility, Sengkang Riverside Park offers an array of activities for nature lovers. Designed with a “fruity” theme, this wetland is about the size of a football field which helps to collect rainwater naturally through its aquatic plants. Wow!

As health foods go, herbal soup has been always been the favourite among many Singaporeans. Fragrant rice is cooked and served with a flavourful herbal chicken soup, believed to have benefits from detoxification to healing and strengthening the body. Each restaurant boasts its own closely-guarded secret herbal recipe of up to 20 different ingredients.

Make a trip to the nearest coffee shop and let us know where you get your healthy nutritious broth. A perfect pairing will be a glass of warm barley water! Burp!

Do you know of any hawkers that sell such herbal soup? Comment below to tell us where to find these delicious pastries. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

Created an illustration of the famous Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a historical temple located in the district of Chinatown. The architecture of the temple is inspired by Buddhist temples during the Tang Dynasty.

Rebecca pays a visit to the temple wearing a Mulan inspired red outfit. I wanted to inject a sense of liveliness in her clothes by painting it bold red.

She wanted to know more about Chinese culture and hope that through Singapore rediscovering temple trips, it will enable her to gain more insights about Buddhism history and culture.

畫了新加坡佛牙寺的插圖， 一間歷史悠久座落在牛車水區的寺廟。建築的靈感來自唐代寺廟的建築結構。

我希望給Rebecca 的服飾注入一種活潑感， 於是采有了大膽的鮮紅色。

Rebecca 希望透過新加坡重新探索之旅來了解更多關於佛教的歷史和文化。

Discover more of Singapore attractions @visit_singapore and @stb_sg.

On the way to the meet the best people in the world.

It’s been an annual tradition for us, every year our family will spend some time together at Chinatown for a good meal. Who says family reunion only happens during new year? Mid Autumn is the time for our “annual” family reviews of which mooncake is the best, which bakwa is good this year, and after the meal we will go home with so many bags of calories. This is what I really love about this time of the year, it’s the gathering of the sweet-tooth family!..

Chinatown Mid-Autumn Festival 2020.
@chinatown_festivals
Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. The lanterns display will depict traditional Chinese motifs and characters such as Chang’e, Goddess of the Moon in Chinese mythology, it will also illustrate this year’s theme – “family”, as a core element in getting Singaporean unite together as one big family to overcome the challenges ahead and emerge stronger.
Date: 17 September – 16 October 2020
Time: 7pm – 12mn (Daily)
Venue: Along New Bridge Road, Eu Tong Sen Street and South Bridge Road

Set in the heart of the city, the art-centric Ritz-Carlton Millenia Singapore surrounds you with visual beauty. Admire the sweeping view of the Marina Bay cityscape from the 32nd floor, or the 4,200 masterpieces by world-renowned artists like Frank Stella, Dale Chihuly and Andy Warhol, housed within this luxurious 5-star establishment. 

Families with young children can indulge in The Ritz Kids Night Safari, an adventurous in-room camping experience. Little ones will be delighted to discover a sleeping tent pitched in the room and amenities that’ll keep them occupied with hours of imaginative fun. 🤩

Treat your eyes to a feast during your stay with five culinary presentations daily, or a trip to the nearby Gardens By The Bay with the complimentary limousine drop-off service. 

Enjoy all these exclusive perks and a third night’s stay for free when you reserve a weekend stay with us. Read more through the link in our bio.

What’s your favourite way to pass time in the city? Let us know in the comments below.

These flats along #Bishan Road, which I snapped from where Bishan Circle Line station is, set themselves apart from those in neighbouring #ToaPayoh and Ang Mo Kio.

With the much vibrant colours and facades, the design of these #HDB blocks differs from those in the latter mentioned two.

The development of Bishan as a housing estate begun in 1980s and prior to that, this area was known for Kwong Wai Siew Peck San Theng, a cemetery that mainly served the Cantonese and Hakka communities of Singapore, according to Wikipedia.

Almost 8 years ago i told myself that i would only want a child when i am ready.. ⁣
⁣
Oh well to be honest no matter how prepared you are, you’ll be left unprepared still, there are so many new things to learn and so many things to deal with physically and mentally.. ⁣
I could totally get it when someone said they do not want a child, it’s personal choice.. ⁣
⁣
But don’t get me wrong.. At one point i really want a child.. and till now never ever regretting to have one on my own.. ⁣
Even though, life is getting more tough and harder now.. I feel life more fulfilling and purposeful.. Motherhood is the greatest thing and the hardest thing.. At the end of the day, i am going to raise a human being..⁣
⁣
To all struggling mommies, let’s think in this postive way: if today was rough and i feel that i am not good enough, i’ll try again tomorrow.. 💪🏻

Often some of our participants had reservations in trying their hands on linocut printing citing that they don’t think they can do it or they’re unable to draw.⁣
⁣
We always assure them to give it a shot and before long some even find the lino plate carving to be therapeutic! ⁣
⁣
Like this group of ex classmates that joined the private session, they’re game enough despite being in their silver age. We’re truly blessed to witness their cheerful bonding and how they found joy through printmaking!⁣
⁣
Why not get acquainted with linocut printing & sign up for our next printmaking workshop!⁣

The flowers are Mexican creepers. Such a vibrant happy pink! 💗 The last 2 photos were taken from one of my favourite vantage points; night photos I'd posted previously.

Wikipedia:  Antigonon leptopus, commonly known as coral vine, Coralita, bee bush (in many Caribbean islands) or San Miguelito vine, is a species of flowering plant in the buckwheat family, Polygonaceae. It is a perennial that is native to Mexico. It is a vine with pink or white flowers (Antigonon leptopus 'alba' ).

A timely reminder to all in this COVID-19 Pandemic; Singapore's Ok! sculpture Park was built after Singapore successfully won the SARS outbreak in 2003. 

Each finger represent a message:
1) Eat healthy, exercise regularly 
2) Wash hand with soap frequently
3) Do not litter. Bag your rubbish and place in bin
4) See doctor, avoid crowded places if unwell. Spit, cough and sneeze into tissue
5) Keep public toilet clean. Keep places clean and free of pests.

This is an amazing place. Very huge natural setting. The data coverage is not great. Relive only captured 22min walk😅
Very glad to have spent time talking to Mr David Li who is an NParks volunteer here at this one of 4 awesome nature parks in Singapore. Learnt alot.

Do note that there are CROCODILES here. Near enough to get you worried (see video). The authorities (with expert assessment) have repeatedly declared that it is totally safe. Crocodiles here have enough to eat in the mangrove water eg fish (no need to go down and let them have more), and also crocs by nature actually shy away from people (see video). Reports of regular croc attacks around the world may not be applicable here at this reserve.

BUT - like the many monkeys and wild boars everywhere, you stay AWAY from them. Do NOT go near their territory. If they do ever come UP to cross the roads, they are just sharing space with us. Slowly move away from them. Do not go near to take Insta worthy shots. It might go viral 😅

So yes it's safe but know that you're in a nature reserve. Respect their space. Do volunteer too, to help NPark❤️ Give back to nature, and be rewarded with joy. 

Bring your loved ones. Or take a lovely stroll yourselves. I was gonna say, sit by the waters and read a book but hmmm maybe not here 😊

Have fun!!!

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

𝗪𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐚 𝐭𝐢𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐛𝐮𝐭 𝐬𝐮𝐩𝐞𝐫 𝐟𝐮𝐥𝐟𝐢𝐥𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐰𝐞𝐞𝐤𝐞𝐧𝐝! 🙆🏻‍♀️⁣
⁣
Saturday:⁣
- meatball went with me to the mkt ⁣
- took a 🚇🚎 to his fave Berries lesson⁣
- came home, hang out at the playground & then drove to marina square for his 💇🏻‍♂️⁣
- swimming is now changed to sat at 6pm so off he goes for some water fun! ⁣
- happy dinner at itacho city square mall, where meatball did his 2nd art & craft to complete his paw patrol collection. signed off the artwork with his “k”.⁣
⁣
Sunday:⁣
- booked the 830am slot for the singapore zoo weeks ago. glad we went ahead despite seeing the drizzle and dark clouds, which went away when we reached there! lucky us! kimmy counted and said he saw 37 types of animals (dinosaur was one of it thou 😅).⁣
- went to vivocity for lunch and while fam knocked out for a 1.5 hours nap! ⁣
- woke up & was craving for crabs, so took the 🚇 to try Holy Crab at tan quee lan st. thou a little pricey, the crab was really good and loved the vibe of the place too! ⁣
- after a full tummy, we 🚊 from bugis to bayfront mrt to visit gardens by the bay! saw pm lee doing his jalan jalan too! the mid autumn lantern display was dull this year, but we still had fun navigating around the much less crowded gardens. ⁣
⁣
Always treasure all the family bonding time, and taking public transport meant we exercise together. being on foot also meant we saw so much more things we could have missed if we drove. And with covid, it also taught us that with some planning, it can feel like a vacation anytime, anywhere. 👨‍👩‍👦⁣
⁣
another two places of interests added to kimmy’s sg passport! ✅⁣
⁣

View from HDB City Vue @ Henderson

At City Vue @ Henderson, you will discover plenty of recreational options that cater to the residents of all ages. Children will enjoy playing at the children’s playgrounds. Fitness enthusiasts can stretch their muscles at the adult and elderly fitness stations, or engage in games at the hard courts. Those who wish to gather with the neighbours for a friendly chat can do so at the resting shelters and precinct pavilions. The roof garden above the multi-storey carpark will provide an ideal spot for quiet contemplation or an evening stroll.

Located at the junction of Tiong Bahru Road and Henderson Road, City Vue @ Henderson is sited close to Tiong Bahru MRT station and Tiong Bahru Plaza.

This development comprises 5 residential blocks ranging from 27, 40 and 48 storeys public housing flats. There are total of 1,232 units of 2-, 3-, 4- and 5-room Standard Flats.

The name City-Vue @ Henderson reflects its prime location close to the city.

Rediscovering Singapore is as simple as taking a walk armed with a camera. Here in Little India, beyond the dazzling Deepavali lights, the simplest scenes were my richest discoveries.

After my shave, I chanced upon The Heritage shop. Home to a variety of antiques, I was really surprised they even carried the Canon 518 Super 8 movie camera (google it, it’s vintage!). Step inside and you’ll be transported to 40 years ago, which was when owner Mr Patrick started amassing his collection. He respectfully declined a photograph of the shop’s interior as he charges for it. However, he welcomes all to visit his place. 

Crawford street was my final stop. Allegedly home to some of Singapore’s oldest shops, what drew my eye was Adi’s barber. What sets this barber apart is it’s high ceiling and television area. Owner Mr Adi left the shop untended for a bit, and then I realised how the residents really trusted one another enough to leave a shop open like Mr Adi. Beyond the long-established brick and mortar stalls, I sensed something that cannot be captured through photography alone - “kampung spirit”, that sense of community and resilience that transcends time and continues to live on in these hidden spaces. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It’s an opportunity to re-live our nation’s history while tuning into modern narratives of “hidden” spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations. 
#SGIGRediscovers #SPCRediscovers  #SingapoRediscovers

post_caption:
【Ang Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiang】
People living in Ang Mo Kio are pampered with plethora of hawker food spread over nine major hawker centers and many other coffee shops. If you have only a day to try all the different types of hawker food in Singapore, Ang Mo Kio is definitely the place to go.

The name ’Ngoh Hiang’ refers a fried meat roll filled with minced pork and prawn filling. This traditional dish is said to have originated in Fujian province in China and is named after the five-spice powder used in Chinese pork sausages.

Nowadays, we refer to Ngoh Hiang as a hawker stall selling a whole array of crispy deep-fried items, usually eaten with vermicelli for breakfast or a lunchtime treat. Century eggs, prawn crackers, fish cakes, ‘guan chang’ (pink-coloured sausages) and of course Ngoh Hiang are some of the popular signature items. A Ngoh Hiang meal would not be complete without the accompanying bowls of pink, gooey sweet sauce and brownish savoury chilli sauce. It is not easy to find authentic versions of this well-loved meal these days, and hawkers continue to create more innovative items to vie for more regular fans. 

What are the items you like to include in your Ngoh Hiang meal? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this meal from, and where you can find a wide choices of ingredients. See ya!

Designed by Paul Rudolph
Completed in １９９４
.
.
.
The "Tropical Skyscraper", with the use of solar shading, communal gardens and external balconies. The tower is octogonal in plan, as the number "8" is associated with prosperity in Chinese culture.

We seem to overlook and forget the optimism and excitement that's brimming whenever something new is being built. These buildings transformed our urban spaces and gives us something to look up and forward to. Remember when MBS was completed in 2010?

I didn't get to feel the excitement that came when these skyscrapers were built, I'd love to imagine how it's like back then.
.
.
.

The Baobabs, Flower Dome
5 October - 1 November

Make your way into an urban oasis and take respite amidst the luscious shades of green and sweet floral scents.

The sight of the brilliantly coloured macaws instantly captures our attention, as do the beautiful blooms of the bamboo orchid, a native species that is used extensively in the landscapes of our metropolitan city-state. Man is innately attracted to nature and seeks to make connections with other life forms. This affinity with the natural world is known as “biophilia”, meaning “a love of life” in Greek.

The transformation from a Garden City to City in a Garden and the movement towards City in Nature have seen the integration of biophilic design into our concrete jungle. Treelined streets, skyrise greenery and world-class gardens and parks that teem with a diversity of flora and fauna are a reflection of how Singapore has successfully incorporated nature and its ecosystem into the urban fabric, integrating both harmoniously. These efforts have not only increased biodiversity in the city, but also influenced the way we work and play.

Redesign your work and living spaces by simply introducing some plants! Beyond their aesthetic value, plants also create a restorative environment to engage our senses, promote emotional and mental well-being, and boost productivity. Jam-packed with design and therapeutic benefits, it is no surprise that many have been drawn to nurture their green fingers whilst working from home! If you’re new to introducing nature to your home or workspace, a good starter option would be the air plant, a low maintenance houseplant that can be used as a table centrepiece or hanging ornament. Alternatively, the use of cut flowers like the exotic birds of paradise seen on display can liven up your space effortlessly!

Hey there! Origin Journeys is a new platform for authentic experiences in Singapore, allowing you to connect with grassroots businesses and to really be able to appreciate what our country is about. More so than that, we hope to be a force for good by channelling leisure dollars where they matter the most. Origin Journeys was conceived during this difficult period of Covid, where we went back to the drawing board and asked ourselves what travel and leisure really meant. The idea of looking at our immediate surroundings with fresh perspectives, since we're gonna be stuck here for awhile 💁🏻‍♀️, re-discovering our roots, tapping into narratives of our individual and collective heritages and being able to offer unique, personalised and homegrown experiences guided by the most knowledgeable and affable locals was foremost in our minds.

From short weekend escapades to deeper journeys into rediscovering the little nooks of our city, we offer experiences for all ages and personalities, thoughtfully crafted through our years of scouring this island for the absolute best it has to offer. 

Keep a lookout at this space for our upcoming launch campaign where you get a chance to win exciting experiences, meals at the hottest spots and a night or two at the most luxurious hotels in town!

Holding the camera at my belly button is something I started doing after watching the documentary of Vivian Maier.
I’m tall. Most of my photos are looking down on the subjects. This new camera position lets you see the world at the different level. 
I changed the angle of the LCD screen for the focusing. It’s a little hard to take vertical photos as this LCD screen doesn’t tilt side ways. Anyways, it’s been a very interesting experiment.

"All colours 🌈 on a tree!" 

Eucalyptus deglupta is a species of tall tree, commonly known as the rainbow eucalyptus, Mindanao gum, or rainbow gum that is native to the Philippines, Indonesia, and Papua New Guinea.
The rainbow effect is created as the bark peels off throughout each season, revealing the fresh, bright-green bark below. As each layer of bark matures, it turns shades of blue, purple, orange, and red.

If you want to know exactly how the trees' bark becomes rainbow-hued, or to witness this beautiful rainbow eucalyptus trees, you are in luck. 

Here in Singapore, the one and only! 
The heritage Mindanao Gum Tree in Katong Park, Singapore.

フランス旅行の代わりに？フランスのホテルブランド、Sofitel City Centreでステイケーション🇫🇷🤭
.
ここはロビーからお部屋、制服まで全てがお洒落で毎回訪れるのが楽しみなホテル🌹✨
. 
お部屋は広くて使いやすく、窓からは歴史的ショップハウスを一望できる圧巻の眺め！
.
ただコロナ対策として部屋の飾りやアメニティが色々撤去されており、仕方ないとはいえ少々見た目淋しくなってしまったのが少し残念でした。
.
.
忙しいビジネス街に位置し、こんな所でステイケーション…とも思うかもしれないけどホテルの中は別世界。
. 
ゆったりとした時間が流れており、場所柄美味しいご飯も食べに行ったりしてとても満喫できました👏✨

“Along the Marina Bay Waterfront Promenade lies a hidden gem that is missed by most – the Red Dot Design Museum. 
 
What I love about this place is the Design Shop where carefully curated design objects from around the world can be found. There are even ones produced by Singapore designers! It’s a perfect place if you’re looking for a gift – they have a variety of items ranging from scarves, fountain pens to cardholders!
 
If you’re taking a walk along the area, do pop by to check it out. For non-Muslim friends, they even have a Museum Cafe Bar to dine at with a good view!” 
 
Captured by @aanurul as part of #SingapoRediscovers.

The third #SingapoRediscovers series: Changi Jurassic Mile. This newest and largest permanent outdoor display of life-sized dinosaurs is part of the Changi Airport connector and the opening was recently officiated by the Minister of Transport on 11 Oct 2020.

With this connector, we now have the option to cycle, walk and jog to East Coast Park and Marina Bay from Changi Airport (in addition to other modes of transport like the bus, train or taxi).

While admission is free, do remember to refer to the website to verify if you are required to do any pre-booking prior to your visit. As the path is also shared among cyclists, runners and pedestrians, let us remain vigilant and be considerate to ensure that all users are safe when visiting this attraction!

And yes, keep your hands and bodies off the exhibits please.

Another photo stop along Coney Island Promenade. 

There were many other families sitting around and enjoying the view. The Promenade is good for families with strollers as beyond that, the paths are not as smooth. 

There were also some picnic-goers, but if you intend to bring food, do be warned that there are monkeys in Coney Island. As we walked on, we saw a group of them picking up plastic bottles and food packets left behind by other visitors. A reminder to all to do our part to maintain the natural state of the island and let’s not leave any rubbish behind.

"Kampong life"
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises.

How to Keep Your Body Smelling Fresh in Singapore's Humid Weather

The most sensitive areas where people can smell easily are the armpits. They are also one of the reasons why some people don’t like to take public transport during peak hours. When you sweat, the bacteria breaks down certain proteins in the sweat into acids. So it’s not the bacteria that stink. It’s the by-product of the bacteria down the sweat. Are you still worried that nobody will like you if they found out you have a bad body odour? We are going to save you! Let’s follow Tropika Club to dive deeply with you on how to keep your body smelling fresh at all time.

Let's talk about story-telling...

... through our tastebuds. The food we eat reveals where we’ve lived or travelled, what we appreciate or feel inspired by, and who we’ve met or spent time with. It is over a meal that we often share stories and create our own. As food brings people together, it becomes a story in itself.

In the first installation of our Culinary Series, we've handpicked impeccable restaurants for you to dine and delight in for your next staycay with us. With the exclusive dining discounts and complimentary hotel credits you get on our bookings, you can savour and save on the finest gastronomical creations by world-renowned chefs. 🤤

Where better to immerse in a kaleidoscope of cultures - Chinatown, a place that draws generations of visitors to its peculiar charm. Just like it’s contemporary counterparts, you can find relics that come alive in different forms by day and by night. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It’s an opportunity to re-live our nation’s history while tuning into modern narratives of “hidden” spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

There's a little fruit shop inside Tekka Market and it belongs to our friend Annie. The market which they are located in has quite a storied past. Tekka means "bamboo clumps" in Mandarin and was named after the bamboo that grew on either side of the canal. It was frequented by people from the working class, hence it became known as the "people's market". 

The original market across the road was demolished in 1982. Most of the store-holders, including Annie and family, relocated to the Tekka market that we know today. 

Our support for local businesses also mean this is the time when we will stop by and have some tropical fruits. We introduce you to fruits that are in season so you can have them at their absolute best (don't worry, durians not included 😂). This family business was started by her grandparents and has been in operations for more than 40 years, so its safe to say they know their stuff.
.
.

post_caption:
Let me tell you a #dirtylittlesecret. After nine years (and still going damn strong), the #bestshitresturant in town is #stillnotdead. Yes, you heard me right, the least authentic Middle Eastern restaurant, Artichoke, led by the creative genius Chef Bjorn Shen, is still constantly revolutionizing the food and beverage scene based on strong beliefs and faith, without caring less of the norm.
•
The definite and right way of a proper dining experience at Artichoke is to start off with a bag of Turkish bread and a spread of mezzes. Mezzes are essentially a collection of small plates of food served as sharing appetizers to whet your appetite for the mains. What we have on the table are some of the mezzes that are new on the menu such as the Turkish Eggplant ($12), Sea Asparagus ($12) and Crab Toast ($16) while the Hummus with Iraqi Spiced Mushrooms ($14) is an improved version of the previous. The newly band of brothers are perfect to go alongside the Turkish bread, especially the hummus which is creamy, rich and just pure decadent; when paired with the abalone mushrooms that has been seasoned in Baharat, a thyme spice mixed of 7 spices, sautéed with olive oil and garlic. The more interesting dish is the Crab Toast whereby instead of a usual one-biter food, this is Artichoke’s version of a two-biter open-faced “sandwich”, made with blue swimmer crab that’s mixed with Greek yogurt and other ingredients before topped on housebaked brioche. The finishing touches of adding deep-fried chicken skin and ikura creates the differing texture and flavour.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978
_________________

Did you know that the lush lawn in front of the Fort Canning Centre used to be a Christian cemetery? One can hardly tell when there. Despite the headstones on the side, there is a calm serenity on the lawn as people lay out their mats for picnics and kids run around playing catch. 

"Developed in 1822 by George Coleman – Singapore’s first architect and Stamford Raffles’ consultant on the first Town Plan – the Fort Canning Christian cemetery had approximately 600 graves interred. 

The cemetery was eventually closed in 1865, and the state of the burial grounds began to deteriorate. In 1953, the City Council exhumed the cemetery and created a “Garden of Memory”."

Some of the headstones have been incorporated into a beautiful brick wall that runs down the sloping hill.

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

post_caption:
So the hermits finally decided to head out and visit the Cloud Forest at Gardens by the Bay over the weekend 😋. We had visited the Cloud Forest when Big E was still a pre-schooler and I remember she was rather scared of the height and loud noise from the waterfall, and it also felt too cold for us then as we weren't dressed for it 😅. But this time round with the girls older and everyone dressed for it, the girls were able to better appreciate the environment and blooms. The mist, greens and light filtering in from the dome give the Cloud Forest such a magical quality that we all enjoyed the trip so much. 
.
If you're planning to visit too, do book your tickets early. We waited till the end of the week and by then most of the weekend slots were fully booked. But thanks to the limited capacity too, it wasn't crowded at all and we felt quite comfortable during our visit.
.
Btw you don't see many pics of us here, maybe it's just me but somehow with the masked faces, I find that the pics with us don't look so nice 😅 Anyway, we were all happy to be out finally and are now thinking of where to go for the coming weekend so we can book ahead if necessary 😆 Any suggestions? Meanwhile have a happy week ahead! 😘
.
.
.
.
.

One thing I really love about Little India is its rich culture and history that also live within unassuming hotel buildings.
 
Many of the smaller hotels in Little India such as The Daulat and Perak Hotel started off as shophouses, and what’s not known to many is that Hotel 81 Rochor was first built just before the Second World War. The Great Madras also takes up a building that has been proudly perched on Madras Street since the 1940s.
 
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your own hidden gem in Little India with #SingapoRediscovers.

Dealing with green is quite challenging.
Sometimes green in nature is overly vibrant. I sometimes reduce its intensity by lowering the saturation or by increasing its brightness. I could also shift its hue slightly to either yellow or aqua. Or I can reduce the contrast of the entire image so you can reduce the overall “power” of the image. In any ways, the decisions are hugely influenced by the existence of the green. This time I tried to weaken the presence of the green by strengthen the power of red to counter (opposite color hue). I achieved the aged old photo look accidentally. Very interesting experiment.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Stepped out of the world of colour for a moment with a #SingapoRediscovers stay at @hotelmonosg this week.

As borders are set to remain close for some time, I decided to have a staycation in the heart of Chinatown. Little did I expect to find one that is so instagramable. Tucked along Mosque Street, @hotelmonosg is a chic hideaway set in six conserved shophouses of modern design. Glad to have stayed here as it gave me endless opportunities to discover all the history and culture within Chinatown’s narrow alleyways. 

Hope that more Singapore residents will consider a local vacation so that we can all get to understand our culture, heritage better, and build a stronger Singapore identity together. @sgig @stb_sg #SGIGRediscovers

Festive Colours

Campbell Lane, situated just a street (Serangoon Road) from the ever popular Tekka Market, is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike. From my various visits (actually only twice in the last 2 weeks), it's always crowded and this is despite COVID still being a prevalent problem here in Singapore today. Its prime location between the Indian Heritage Centre and the Little India Arcade makes it a popular shopping street.

Walking along Campbell Lane, one may find themselves amongst garlands and other items that one may need for the Hindu festive season. Despite COVID-19, the festive mood is still present in Little India and many Hindu devotees still walk the streets of Little India looking for festive goods.

Whether you are taking timelapse for work or just for fun, why not do it like a pro.

Still can’t figure it out?

Sign up for an evening workshop to explore the ways and settings to create not just timelapse but great photos and other moving images with your iPhone.

I will guide you through your in-camera settings, learn about composition, how to photograph places and people including portraiture, experience different lightings to create stunning images  and how to edit your photos.

Duration: 1.5 hours 
Time: 6.30 pm to 8 pm
Location: To be advised upon booking
Fee: $60 per person

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Where are you going?!

Do you guys have a side you prefer to be on in pictures? Liz loves the left, so she’ll always sneak in either way to pose on the left. This is one of the few times we mix it up😂

This was at the iconic Raffles Hotel - the very first Raffles in sunny Singapore. Opened in 1887, it started as a beach house. Now it’s a symbol of unparalleled service, charm, and splendour in the most storied building on the island!

One day, when the world opens up again, and you find yourself in Singapore, you must stay at this legendary haven, even for a night, and savour a Singapore Sling🍹

Photo evidence that we did make it to Coney Island last Saturday. We managed to cover only half of the island, so our next trip there will be to check out the other half.

We actually enjoy checking out the local sights, best kept secrets  and unique sounds as part of #SingapoRediscovers . More adventures to come for sure!!

We finally have our own oculus! Swipe 👈 to see the journey from underground into the globe. Quite the architectural marvel.

Upclose.The front gate.

Iconic pastel shophouses along Koon Seng Road which combines a unique mix of Chinese & Malay influences seen in intricate detailing, motifs and tiles.

Information from URA/Architectural Heritage plaque: Koon Seng Road, formerly known as Lorong E East Coast was renamed in 1934 after Cheong Koon Seng, a prominent auctioneer, Municipal Commissioner and Justice of the Peace.

<369> “Interesting Ways To Enjoy The Beach At High Tides” 

What do you do when the waves are almost swept up to the edge of the beach?

Surely, you cannot build sand castles. There wasn’t much sand to walk on the beach as the waves were breaking close. But I discovered some interesting ways to enjoy the beach at high tides —take a selfie at the high rocks with your loved ones, take a walk barefooted in the water, or take a dip behind the rocks!

William

⁣⁣
We’re awed by their sensitivity to the medium and within mere 3 hours managed to attempt different printing methods; manually by hands and using the press machines.⁣⁣
⁣⁣

Join us in our #nomondayblues series of indigo dyeing workshops! Guarantee to shade away your Monday blues & get a blue hands experience instead!⁣ 🙌🏻🔵💙
⁣
Date: Monday, 19 October 2020⁣
Time: 10.30 - 12.00⁣
Instructor: Clara Simanjuntak⁣
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695⁣
⁣
Course Fee: SGD35⁣
Price inclusive of tools and materials⁣
⁣
Indigo is one of the famous natural dye from plants in Asia. It is known as tarum in Indonesia and nila in Malaysia. In this workshop, participants will learn about indigo dye, as well as other natural dye sources, and to use indigo as dip dye in fashion items.⁣
⁣
Participant will get to bring back one piece of their indigo dyed cushion cover (45x45cm).⁣
⁣

Happy midweek! I’m taking a break from my LexSpreadHappiness campaign to share about my #Singapoliday staycation at @sentosa_island last weekend. In partnership with #SingapoRediscovers, a joint campaign by @stb_sg, @esg.life and the Sentosa Development Corporation to support local lifestyle and tourism business and encourage Singaporeans and residents to explore different sides of Singapore, we bring you the Singapoliday staycation package at @capellasingapore which features an itinerary themed around Heritage Discovery. 总值3亿2000万元的重新探索新加坡（SingapoRediscovers vouchers）消费券将在今年12月分发，每名18岁及以上的新加坡公民将获得100元消费券，用于购买景点门票、导览及支付酒店住宿等。

这项“重新探索新加坡”消费券（SingapoRediscovers vouchers）计划将在今年12月至明年6月底推行，长达七个月。

新加坡旅游局今天（16日）发文告说，每张消费券面额为10元，国人可通过个人电子政府密码（SingPass）领取，相关领取详情将在11月公布。此外，政府也将为孩童和青年门票提供10元津贴，每个消费券用户可使用政府津贴购买最多六张孩童或青年门票。📸：档案照

So near yet so far.
