post_caption:
Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...
.
.
.
.
.
.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

[SGRediscovers CONTEST REMINDER] Have you had a chance to photograph any of the “hidden gems” on @aikbengchia’s itinerary yet? If not, you still have until 4 October to get out, shoot some great shots, and win some pretty cool prizes like staycations to Marina Bay Sands or Mandarin Orchard, brought to you by the Singapore Tourism Board! Check out the link in our bio for the full details and itinerary.
 
As Singapore continues to navigate the current climate, we want to rediscover locations around the island that are a bit more off the beaten path. But remember! Your photos aren’t limited to the places on the itinerary - any “hidden spots” within the listed precincts are welcome (the listed locations are just examples)! Photographers are welcome to exercise their own judgment and practise discretion when capturing these images too.
 
We hope you join us in rediscovering a lesser-known side of Singapore, and we’re looking forward to seeing your shots! Remember to share with us what does rediscovering Singapore means to you, tag @stb_sg and @sg_photocommunity in your posts and use the hashtags #SingapoRediscovers and #SPCRediscovers to submit your entries. 
 
Happy shooting and best of luck!

Very honoured to be part of @NeverBeforeSG; Singapore's first and largest online art showcase  presented by National Museum of Singapore @natmuseum_sg and curated by Yang Derong @derongisyang. 

Arranged in nine chapters about our take on #Covid19, it showcases 140 works by 91 Singapore based creatives who consist of photographers, videographers, writers, artists, architects and designers.

These are the images I captured during and after the “Circuit Breaker”. Most of the photos are primarily blue in colour, reflecting the blue mood: lots of uncertainty and a feeling of loneliness.

Blue, however, is also the colour of the sea and sky, which I was able to spend more time admiring and learning to appreciate nature more.

#NeverBeforeSG

Someday we'll look back and say that "Yes, those were crazy times. And we made it."

Someday.

post_caption:
Yesterday. All was peaceful and calm in the beautiful Bambusetum. The sun shone through the wispy bamboo leaves, casting dappled patterns on the path, and a slight breeze made them rustle soothingly. And then suddenly, the silence was broken. Someone was belting out Mandarin songs at the top of his voice. It seemed to be coming from the small gazebo perched above me. But as he was so enjoying himself and putting so much soulful expression into his songs, it seemed only right to leave him to it. He sure did have a powerful set of lungs though for he continued at full strength for more than an hour as I moseyed about the Learning Forest...

.

.

We are staying home this weekend, but here's a throwback to our @sentosa_island visit last weekend where we bought tonnes of goodies from @candyliciousshop! 
.
If you don't already know, there's a storewide sale at Candylicious now (swipe to see some of the stuff on sale!) and we went crazy loading up on discounted chocolates and candies. Regular items are discounted at 25% but some are sold at substantial discounts (up to 70% off) as they're close to expiry dates like end-October. My family are chocoholics, so we got some of the heavily discounted chocolates and within a week our purchases were already half gone 😅 We've always liked the variety of chocolates and candies at Candylicious, and they sure bring in a lot of interesting and good quality stuff.
.
The gelato counter is also having a 1-for-1 promo for their medium and large cups, so the kids finally got to eat their fav Blue Sky gelato! The Annette ice-creams are also going at 2 for $5! 
.
There was a short queue to enter the store the late afternoon Saturday we were there but the shop itself wasn't too crowded at all. Not sure how long the sale will last but if you want to go, Candylicious is now only open 2-9pm Thursdays-Sundays. 
.
We had such a fun time shopping and eating, hubs says we'll need to make another trip there to get more bargains 😆 How's your weekend going? 😉

post_caption:
<340> “A Walk Among The Trees”

How is it like to walk among the trees?

I stepped up the elevated steel walkways of Forest Walk and continued running. The pounding sound of my feet on the steel surface startled some hikers who were walking in front of me. I decided it’s better to take a walk instead. 

It was an unique experience of walking above the forest, having a close-up look of tall trees at eye-level, and enjoying a bird's-eye view of the forest canopy and the nearby housing blocks.

William

I've passed by Bedok Reservoir Park numerous times on practically all sides, but this is the first time I've gone in! 😅

It's a lovely place to exercise and de-stress, and quiet on a weekday early afternoon when I was there. One could sit with a book at the many sheltered spots in the park.

The solar farm is a great idea, making use of what nature provides. There's construction work going on, so I expect there'll be more attractions like the flying fox adventure park and kayaking coming up. I hope it won't get too busy, but I suppose Singapore has to optimise all its limited resources.

[Sembawang Precinct] Rediscover Sembawang hot spring with super grandma

Rediscovery is about going to a known place with a local "expert" and then appreciate the way of enjoyment of the place

Always go with an local “expert” when doing exploration. Come explore with super grandma Mdm Tan  to the only hotspring in Singapore. Just bring the essentials all in a plastic bag like a true blue Singapore veteran . She brought a pail, a scoop and a towel. That is all you need to enjoy the hot spring. 

If you want some better protection, you can bring an umbrella. For a complete experience, you can also bring some eggs to do hard boiled eggs with the hotspring water. 

This is the next best alternative to travelling for hotspring.

P.s. Mdm Tan is also featured in DBS  #protraitsofpurpose. Do support and vote for photo1 :) link in my profile.

post_caption:
[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Beyond the colorful

Rediscovery is about having a listening ear and appreciation to the heritage of the place.

Joo Chiat is a place with so much rich history as well as street “historians”. In both visits, I have had strangers who are residents or former residents coming to chit chat with me. They told me interesting stories as well as places to shoot. Most of us, including myself, will focus a lot of attention on the colorful peranakan house.  One of them ( her name is Diana)  was told that there are more. For example, I should also be paying attention to the tiles of those other chinese or penakan houses. Those are imported from Europe in the pre-war days, and often use a symbol of wealth for people staying in the area. 

She also shared something interesting about what is shown in the last photo. Can you guess what that is for?

@stb_sg

@sgig

#SGIGRediscovers

#SingapoRediscovers

#SGunited

#ExploreSG

Kampong Glam is one of my go-to hangout spots but today’s visit was made even more meaningful through the #SingapoRediscovers campaign. At one of Singapore’s surviving street side barber, I waited in queue to get a shave. Mr Chen, unperturbed by onlookers, continued executing his craft like a hyper focused surgeon even as I hastily took a few snapshots. 
When it was my turn, Mr Chen introduced himself and swiftly finished the shave. We did not get to talk much though, as Mr Chen bantered with his friend who arrived shortly during my shave. In that moment, it felt like I returned to the 1990’s. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It’s an opportunity to re-live our nation’s history while tuning into modern narratives of “hidden” spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations. 
#SGIGRediscovers #SPCRediscovers  #SingapoRediscovers

Not even the rain can stopped me from taking photos anymore  The last couple of #instawalk tours with @tribetours were met with bad weather. And what a juggling act I had to perform, sheltering myself under the brolly, angling my phone to demonstrate the shots and grabbing the mic to share what goes on behind the screen, I’ve actually grown a liking to rainy days

For starters, the weather was a lot more bearable. The rain brings some kind of drama to the photos, creating a different kind of mood compared to a bright sunny day. It also teaches me to balance my props, and utilising them

I love how well coordinated my boots and brolly are in this shot. Not forgetting, puddles of water creating the perfect reflections

Have you tried rainy day shooting too?
—
📸 @yocksong

post_caption:
<332> “A Fishing Platform Inside A Park!”

Look at all those wooden planks, massive nets and house-like structure above the water! This place exudes the rustic charm of “kelong”, a Malay word that describes an offshore platform built by fishermen for fishing, which are commonly found in the coastal areas surrounding neighbouring countries such as Malaysia, the Philippines and Indonesia. 

I heard that a handful of “kelong” remain around Singapore, but they are supposed to be out there somewhere in the seas. Yet, I discovered one right inside a park in a residential estate! 

William

9-pound cannon, one of a pair originally used as decorations for the main gate of Fort Canning. I usually listen to some sad ass songs when I’m taking photos on street because they kinda fit my photo style and it’s easy to get into the usual vibe with them. 
For no particular reason, this time I was listening to ‘It’s Beginning to Look a Lot Like Christmas’ by Michael Bublé and I still get this sad ass photos.
I thought I was feeling happy while listening to the song.
But I guess my soul can’t help but show its true color as you can see in the photo. 
I guess I don’t even need those sad songs to be sad because Ima sad ass bitch by heart.
Or I guess ‘Christmas’ in my heart is more like ‘Merry Christmas, Mr. Lawrence’ Christmas.

Hey my Dreams HOME 

Pinnacle@Duxton is a public housing project at 1A Cantonment Road. It is the first 50-storey public housing project in Singapore, and also the first in the world with two sky bridges linking seven towers. The sky bridges create two layers of sky parks that offer panoramic views of the city. Resulting from the first international competition for public housing in Singapore, Pinnacle@Duxton is regarded as groundbreaking for redefining the concept of public housing with its unique design features.

with the tagline “The Peak of City Living” – under the HDB’s Build-to-Order scheme on 29 May 2004.

La kopi somewhere at Chinatown: “Sweetea Caffe 一杯夏日” at 15A & 15B Trengganu Street (2nd & 3rd floor of a conservation building at 15 Trengganu Street).
Just curious to go up to this heritage building to sit inside, chillax and admire the wall decor. High Tea with decent sweet and savoury food choices, there’s also main course food choices for lunch / dinner. Ordinary food for youngsters standard, please go without expectations. We are the most elderly patrons there, the rest are almost half of our age (or some younger than my Kopi Kaki’s child age) on a weekday afternoon, probably cos this place is so instagrammable, but I first saw this place online from TikTok 😆😄

[Wear proper shoes if going to check out this youngster cafe, the staircase of heritage building felt more steep when coming down.]

15 TRENGGANU STREET history:
Located at corner of Temple Street, at junction with Trengganu Street.
The three-storey building featured is the former Lai Chun Yuan opera theatre, believed to have been built in 1887, offering Cantonese opera performed by local, China and Hong Kong troupes.

HDB • 60 - 3 of 3

Ever since I was young i remember being fascinated at the different types of HDB estates out there (yes very nerd I know), the varying designs and amenities are never really the same for each area.

The #gobackhome photowalk series is for me personally a way to share with others my interest in HDB architecture, and I'm glad that this interest is being resonated with others as well.

Of course given that now COVID-19 has prevented us from gathering in large groups, photowalks have to be either postponed or scaled down.

It's been awhile since I have done one - perhaps it will be back sooner rather than later. #shapesofhome

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Bird watchers paradise. Sungei Buloh has a lovely 1.9km walk around the tidal pools, sprinkled with shelters where you can spot redshanks, greenshanks, herons, mudskippers, kingfishers, and the passing crocodile. There is a 1.3km Coastal Walk which is nice, but we didn’t enjoy it as much as the nature trail. Best to go in early morning when you can explore with a cool breeze and birdsongs. #singaporetravel #singaporediscovers

Today is the last day to join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest in collaboration with Singapore Tourism Board!

All you have to do is to check out our itinerary (link in bio), visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. We’ve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well! These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts.

3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3, Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers.

You will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: 4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
8th, 9th and 10th prizes: 3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

For more info on the contest and its T&Cs, please click on the link in bio.

Busy and well spent Friday! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
brought meatball to say hi to lao gong and lao ma at his virgin trip to a temple. haha he saw the space for their urns and was asking alot of qns. had to explain that it’s like a hdb block, they stay level 5 and nearby are all neighbors. 🤷🏻‍♀️ ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
after that a happy play date at toa payoh safra with the usual gang! think i clocked 7k steps just chasing/running away from the kids in what seem like 5037 rounds of shuttle run! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
took a 2 hour nap, and went to city hall ippudo for dinner! meatball got a free children’s set as part of their promo! good to see many restaurants giving treats! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
went for a walk from city hall to boat quay and clarke quay to soak in the city’s lights! there’s so much things you can explore on foot and i’m happy to inspire the hub and kimmy to walk more, drive less! 🤪 ended with late night shopping at don don! slept at midnight....😜⁣
⁣

Joo Chiat & Katong are places in Singapore that are rich in culture & heritage! Apart from the well-known Peranakan shophouses with their colourful motifs and famous food havens like Katong Laksa, you will find many hidden gems like the Former Queen's Theatre.

Besides Joo Chiat & Katong, we hope you had a great time rediscovering other places in Singapore. If you haven’t, do join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest! All you have to do is to visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured in the itinerary and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. Click on the link in our bio to check out the itinerary!
 
3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3. Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers and a gentle reminder to make your account public so we are able to track your submissions!

Your submissions do not necessarily have to showcase the interior of the featured locations - any "hidden spots" within the precincts are welcome (the listed locations in the itinerary are just examples) A gentle reminder to exercise judgment and practise discretion when capturing these images too!

Winners will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket) and
3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

More info on the contest and its T&Cs can also be found on our link in bio.

Contest ends 4 October 2020, 2359 hours (GMT+08:00).

Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is one of the largest parks in Singapore. Built in 1988,1 the park was revamped between 2009 and 2011 under the Active, Beautiful, Clean Waters (ABC Waters) Programme launched by PUB, Singapore’s National Water Agency.

 Subsequently, the park was reopened in 2012. Spanning 62 ha, it stretches along Ang Mo Kio Avenue 1 from Upper Thomson Road to Bishan Road.
An iconic feature of Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park is the naturalised river meandering through it. The three-kilometre waterway was converted from a concrete canal that channelled the Kallang River at the edge of the park. 

When the water level in the river is low, visitors can walk down the gentle river banks to get closer to the water; but during heavy rain, the parkland next to the river doubles up as a conveyance channel and carries excess water downstream.

Concrete slabs from the original canal have been stacked up to create a mound called Recycle Hill. An award-winning sculpture by Kelvin Lim Fun Kit titled An Enclosure for a Swing can be found at the top of the hill, where visitors can enjoy a good view of the entire park.

To be honest, i never really like to drink coffee until my trip to New Zealand in 2017.. My husband bought a coffee and i took a sip, since then i am a convert! I was a tea lover but now i love coffee too! ⁣
⁣
The coffee i tried in New Zealand was The Flat White, then i also enjoyed having Latte.. And when i was on low carb diet i always had black coffee with butter or coconut oil.. It’s kinda weird but that combination boost my concentration and curb my hunger.. ⁣
⁣
I was stopped having caffeine when i got pregnant last year and now i am back enjoying coffee again.. My fav now is Latte.. What is your favourite coffee? ⁣

<309> “A Paradoxically Intriguing Temple”

Don’t you find it paradoxical to see an ancient-looking 100-year-old Chinese temple surrounded by modern, high-rise buildings and located in a street named after Mohamed Sultan? That’s so uniquely Singapore! 

The three big red Chinese characters on the walls of the temple are read “鳳山寺“ (Fèng shānsì in Mandarin or Hong San See in Hokkien), which can be literally translated as “Temple on Phoenix Hill”.

A Phoenix is a mystical bird that rises from the ashes. Coincidentally, the temple was restored to its glory ten years ago and had since gone on to win an Award of Excellence in the 2010 UNESCO Asia-Pacific Heritage Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation. Isn’t the name befitting?

What’s more, the temple worships the God of Fortune. I would have climbed up those steep steps without hesitation if I had known that earlier. Times are bad, every prayer counts. 

William

Remark: I was later informed by someone in my IG that the temple’s main deity is not the God of Fortune. Alas! There goes my glimmer of hope that a prayer at this temple may bring me some fortune. (laughs).

A Love Story

Rediscovering Singapore has once again led me to a place I didn't know existed. This time, it brought me to the house of Tan Teng Niah. Little India is not short of colourful shophouses -- not unlike Kampong Gelam -- but the house of Tan Teng Niah stood out for me first and foremost with the Chinese engraving on its front door. "A Chinese residence in Little India?" That was the thought that first surfaced to my mind. In fact, I chanced upon this place, attracted by the colours and the inscription.

Written on the front door of this vividly vibrant house is a couplet referring to the wife of Tan Teng Niah, 秀松. While I did not manage to find any sources on an interpretation of the couplet, from my very basic Chinese understanding (hopefully not embarrassing my Chinese teachers), the couplet describes her wife as a beautiful (秀丽景色), pure and morally upright person (松柏操持). While one can only guess why he made such a couplet, we may infer that Tan Teng Niah left the couplet on the door for the generations to come, to remember not just him but also his wife. He sounds like a romantic, loving husband if you were to ask me.
Happy to stop by Rower’s Bay Park again. It is proving to be a great final pit stop before the push to complete my usual island route. #singapoREdiscovers #merida #cyclingsg

Celebrating love ❤️

The W Hotel in Singapore has found itself at the centre of the latest instance of the culture war over LGBTQ rights in the country.

On Monday, 14 September, the five-star luxury hotel at Sentosa Cove posted a photo of gay influencer couple, fashion model Andee Chua @andeecys and Taiwanese YouTuber Hugo Liu @hugo_tw, on their social media. 

“We are in the business of welcoming all and occasionally feature guests with their permission on our social platforms,” @wsingapore told Yahoo Lifestyle SEA. 

The hotel was promoting its staycations as travel restrictions remain in place because of the COVID-19 pandemic.

| Full moon 
• Sony a6000 + SEL55210 •
#1: ISO 800  210mm  f 7.1  1/160 sec
#2: ISO 800  80mm  f7.1  1/160 sec 
.
.
Tested out my spankin' new SEL55210 lens last night on Chang'e! 😍 And I'm loving the results!

We had planned a photowalk a couple of weeks back without realising it coincided with mid-autumn festival. It was only on the bus towards our destination then did we realise. How?

Before getting to the planned stop, we saw the moon big, low and round on the horizon, peeking from behind MBS. That's when my friend mentioned, "It's mid-autumn today!" Ecstatic, we quickly got off the bus laughing as we literally chased the moon. 

Perfect timing! 📸

Будто смотрим в калейдоскоп в детстве!

Мост Helix в сингапурском заливе Марина-Бэй был вдохновлен геометрическим расположением нити ДНК, в результате чего пешеходная дорожка окружена противоположными двойными спиральными структурами из нержавеющей стали. 

Извилистый мост длиной 280 метров позволяет пешеходам переходить по изогнутой палубе с одного берега реки Сингапур на другой. 

Отмечайте в комментариях того,с кем хотели бы прогуляться по Сингапуру!

post_caption:
Guess the fish! 🐠🐟

Indigenous to the lower Amazon region, primarily the Parnaíba River of Brazil, this mystery fish is found in flooded forest regions as well as in creeks and small tributaries. This fish typically is smaller and more stout in build. It has a shorter head and rounded snout. Also, it has a silvery gray body. Furthermore, a dark zigzag stripe runs along the lateral line from its gill to its tail. Above and below this dark line is a section that is not spotted, beyond which are many small, isolated black spots of varying size. 

Additionally, its dorsal fin is transparent with a large black blotch on the upper fin that does not extend down into the body. The caudal fin has vertical rows of dark brown spots that gives the appearance of striping. The anal, adipose, pectoral, and ventral fin also has these spots, but it is much paler in colour than on the caudal fin. Instead of scales, this fish has overlapping hard plates, known as scutes.
Overall, this fish can reach an adult size of slightly over 2 inches.

Stay tuned as the answer will be revealed tomorrow!

The topic of reading today is on “Succeeding in Singapore & Japan”.

As a consulting expert in retail, Japan and entrepreneurship, we have to constantly reading up to gain new knowledge, analyse the current markets, and devise new strategies, short, mid and long term to stay ahead of the curve. 

The current headwinds in the industry, uncertainties worldwide and perfect storm tensions in north asia, we are caught in the storm of the lifetime. 

Yet, we must never take our eyes off the vision, we must keep moving towards it. Taking steps to work out the right direction, hiring the right people to power the efforts, and reaching out to the targeted markets.

The lease in Mandarin Gallery is due for renewal this October. We hope the terms will be workable and the Reits is appreciating the long term efforts we have put in. And all our customers too.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sembawang Hot Spring Park

The entrance of Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Sembawang Hot Spring Park is located in SingaporeSembawang Hot Spring Park
Type	Hot spring
Location	Sembawang, Singapore
Nearest town	Yishun
Coordinates	1.4344°N 103.8224°ECoordinates: 1.4344°N 103.8224°E
Area	1.1 hectares (11,000 m2)
Opened	4 January 2020; 8 months ago
Owned by	NParks
Public transit access	 NS13  Yishun
Facilities	Hot spring
Website	Official website
The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring and a public park in Singapore.
It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, and its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser and Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership and potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle and bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020.
It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

-Vintage-

Taking a solo trip down to Little India alone last weekend to rediscover Singapore made me realise all the little things I overlook in life.

I had less pressure with time when I roamed around alone, and had the tenacity to speak to the people in the neighborhood. I learnt so much more when I spoke to the locals - Knowing why they came here for, what their struggles were (especially during this pandemic), their dreams and even the history of the places around us. And I truly miss traveling (solo) for the same reasons!

I don’t usually post carousels, but these pictures truly piece together a beautiful set of stories of what Little India is all about - A mix of old and new, people, culture, art and history.

1. A box of vintage old films outside Sajeev Digital Studio

2. The studio upstairs, where foreign workers take portraits to send home the pictures for their families to matchmake them with potential wives

3. Sajeev Digital Studio from outside

4. An Indian foreign lady, named Mary, who works outside a pop-up stall at House of Tan Teng Niah (the colorful house 2 posts before). She’s making prayer garlands using Jasmine, Rose, Orchid and Marigold and has been here for over 10 years

5. Massive mural which juxtaposes modern vehicles and the old-school way of transporting tiffins. Lorry as scale

6. Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple, Singapore’s oldest hindu temple that is dedicated to the goddess and destroyer of evil, Sri Veeramakaliamman or Kali. Early Migrant workers worship this goddess for safety in this new foreign land

This is the longest caption I have ever had, made with time, sweat, with sore legs and neck. Would appreciate it if you drop a comment below and tell me which photo caught your attention the most. Keep exploring, everyone!

This is the only village left in SG. Pretty unique and memorable one for many of the locals.
Me as a Malaysian, this is truly a nostalgia.
Like most early childhood memories, the rest of my kampung recollections are spare, fragmented, truncated; the equivalent of cinematic stills, with no soundtrack, no entertaining stories. Still, the few images that come to mind are vivid, enduring. The rough concrete floor of my grandmother's house; the splintered texture of the wooden walls, the chickens running free around the compound, the rickety chicken coop that I once tried to climb and nearly fell off the well with its column of cold damp air enclosed by stone.

Exploring the Garden City. While high-rise buildings can be found all over Singapore, the city has an abundance of urban greenery!

Lush with city parks, tropical nature reserves and botanical gardens, there’s something to be seen everywhere. Can you believe this picture was taken in Singapore?

post_caption:
Not many would expect to find a small, quiet village tucked away in the modern metropolis that is Singapore. Yet here stands Kampong Lorong Buangkok: Singapore’s 𝗹𝗮𝘀𝘁 𝗸𝗮𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗻𝗴 and a relic of a simpler and slower way of life.
.
In the minds of younger Singaporeans today, the kampong is a construct of oral history passed down from their parents and grandparents. Few have seen an actual kampong in the flesh. Far from being secluded, Kampong Lorong Buangkok is but a few metres away from the residential area of Yio Chu Kang. The zinc and wood houses of this little village stand in stark contrast to the concrete of its neighbouring HDB flats.
.
Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a rare gem: it is a part of Singapore’s living history, one which might soon be lost to the unceasing pace of development and renewal in this city-state. To say that I felt an overwhelming sense of nostalgia would have been excessively romantic. Like many of my millennial peers I grew up not knowing what kampong living was like. Visiting this little kampong is not simply akin to traveling back in time and gaining a glimpse of the kampong experience. It is about rediscovering Singapore – the Singapore once inhabited by my grandparents. To be able to see how they might have once lived is truly a blessing: in rediscovering Singapore, I have also gained a deeper appreciation of my own roots.
.

Sajeev Digital Studio is more than a photography studio. Taken by Mr K Sajeev Lal, these photographs perform an important social function: they help South Asian male migrant workers find love back home in India and Sri Lanka! Mr Sajeev happily claims that he has a success rate of 100% 😉
.
An affable and jovial soul, Mr Sajeev gave me a tour of his studio and shared his personal story. I learned that he taught himself photography on a Yashica film camera when he was 15. He learnt film developing later, and adroitly turned his passion into a profession. I’m also glad that Mr Sajeev was game enough to pose for my photographs. As a photographer, I know that willing subjects are hard to come by. Mr Sajeev’s willingness made the photo-taking experience so much more fun and imbued deeper meaning into these photographs that you see here.
.
One more thing that stood out for me was the thousands of portraits of migrant workers the adorned the walls of the little studio. These portraits formed an eclectic mosaic of untold stories. I took a moment to appreciate the fact that much of Singapore’s modern development would have been impossible without them, and that they too have suffered greatly because of the coronavirus. Looking at these portraits turned out to be a gentle reminder that we can do more to appreciate our migrant workers in our midst. I realised that rediscovering Singapore is not just about visiting local places of interest because we can’t go overseas – it’s about rediscovering the different threads that form our magnificent social fabric, and how it is up to each and every one of us to make it stronger.
.

Masjid Sultan Mosque⁠
Surrounded by rows of shophouses Masjid Sultan Mosque stands out with its massive golden domes and huge prayer hall, it is one of the must-see sites if you’re in the historic Kampong Gelam district. ⁠
The mosque has a long history that goes back to 1824 when it was built for Sultan Hussein Shah, the first Sultan of Singapore. It has since passed through many development stages before becoming what it is today. ⁠
While you’re there, check out the onion-shaped domes as each dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute. ⁠
In 1975, the mosque was gazetted as a national monument, it has been a focal point for the Muslim Community. ⁠
To find out more about the mosque, click on the link http://sultanmosque.sg/about-us/sultan-mosque-history⁠

post_caption:
The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise qigong before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

Nature is not a place to visit. It is home. —Gary Snyder

Grasses and weeds have a role in the ecosystem. There are many that are pretty too! 💚

Hydrocotyle verticillata, also known as whorled pennywort, whorled marshpennywort or shield pennywort, is a flowering plant found in South and North America and the West Indies. The creeping plants with unusual leaves give it its common names. It grows in places that are marshy, boggy, and wet. Hydrocotyle verticillata is used in aquaria, where it is undemanding but prefers a good substrate, and at least moderate light. It benefits from additional carbon dioxide.(Nature's #aircleaner!) (Source: Wikipedia)

【Ang Mo Kio #3 - Fried Rice】
Where do you get your fried-rice-fix? Where is your favourite _zhichar_ or western food stall? If you are craving for some old school western food and fried rice, you have to visit Yummy Western stall located at Blk 409 Ang Mo Kio Avenue 10 (avoid peak hours if you are in a hurry). The chef cooking this fried rice has been in the business for about 20 years - no wonder the fried rice tastes so good and full of ‘wok hei’ flavour! Truly satisfying!

This week, #dabaogram tried a new dimension of food plating with a floral touch. Greens like cucumbers and parsley were added to give it a refreshing look and feel . We reshaped the side dishes and positioned them like an arrow pointing upwards. Can you see it?  Finally, we used some of the accompanying chilli sauce to add some vibrant colour to the dish. Viola!

We would like to thank Yummy Western for preparing such delicious fried rice and western food. According to the owner, all dishes were marinated using a  special curated sauce. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‘dabaogram’ at home. 

Next week’s makeover dish is our favourite for Ang Mo Kio. Stay tuned cos’ you won’t want to miss it, see ya!

For generations, Singaporeans affectionately called it "NTUC" despite its official name is "NTUC FairPrice" or "FairPrice" in (@fairpricesg) in short, mainly because this supermarket chain is a co-operative of the National Trades Union Congress (NTUC), the main trade union body in #Singapore.

The first outlet of this chain was first opened in #ToaPayoh (as shown) in 1973 as #NTUC Welcome Supermarket and it is still in operation.

The setting of this supermarket in that era was to allow Singaporeans to buy groceries and other daily necessities at affordable prices because of the high inflation rate back then.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Katong / Joo Chiat precinct

In Katong Joo Chiat area, you can discover conserved heritage shophouses with Peranakan culture or influence /designs.

Although this area is very well known for it's colourful street, Koon Seng Road, Katong Joo Chiat precinct, has other good attractions as well.

1. Teong Theng Co is a old school crafted rattan based furniture maker that has 70 years of history in Joo Chiat.  This is a good time to rediscover, some of our heritage shops and at the same time, feels the nostalgic vibes

2. China Collection (antique) shop is painted blue and white and this Chinese shop house  has now turn itself into a modern building with a minimal twist. Those who likes minimal design will appreciate the paint work

3. I couldnt resist taking a shot of this old school hair salon, everytime I pass by

4. Rumah Bebe in Katong is a Peranakan heritage boutique, a school, a bake shop and also a mini museum. I simply love the interior (more like exterior) decor.

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival everyone! May your personal and professional life be blessed with moments of joy and happiness! 

Come over to Qian Hu Fish Farm and celebrate with us!

Also, head over to our ecommerce store at https://www.qianhushop.sg/ today! 

https://www.qianhushop.sg/ offers you a wide range of aquarium and pet accessories!
 
Here are some interesting findings about the festival:
According to some experts, the Mid-Autumn Festival was traditionally a time to express gratitude to the gods. It is also a time of year that the moon is at its brightest. This explains why lunar legends have always been attached to the celebration. 

I trust many of us are aware of the story of Chang Er, the wife of a merciless king who drank the elixir of immortality he had intended to drink, so as to save her people from his tyrannical rule.
It is believed that she has ascended to the moon upon her brave act, and has been worshipped by the Chinese as a Moon Goddess ever since.

Many would enjoy the occasion by attending moon-gazing parties. Family and friends would sit in gardens lit by the soft glow of paper lanterns, sip tea and nibble on mooncakes.

Children in particular love this festival as they get to tote lanterns. In the past, there were only traditional lanterns with wax candles that are made from paper. Today, there are also plastic, battery-operated versions.

Mooncakes are the main highlight of the Mid-Autumn Festival. It is believed that they helped to free Yuan China from Mongol rule, after rebels organised an uprising by passing messages hidden in these mooncakes.

Today, there are not only traditional flavours with lotus seed paste and egg yolk but also snowskin versions filled with everything from chocolate to durian. They are best enjoyed with a strong, palate-cleansing cup of Chinese tea.

Old is indeed gold and time truly stood still here at Tong Ah Eating House the moment you stepped into the restaurant with all the interior setup and food that they are serving, which hasn’t changed much from many years ago. Instead of going for their extra crispy toast, we decided to get their French toast that comes with a slab of melting butter on top the toast with their own homemade moreish kaya by the side. The kaya is slightly different from the rest as theirs are eggier with a clumpy texture that is not as smooth as others. While the setup might not appeal to many, the quality of the traditional brewed Nanyang coffee more than makes up for it, the aroma and thickness will awaken any senses. I truly hope that the charm of this old-world heritage establishment remains as it is for many years to come to contrast all the modernization that is happening now to the F&B industry.

This multi-sensory dining experience by @rwsentosa combines culinary artistry and visual splendour and will run till 31 October 2020.

While you tuck into a four-course sustainably sourced seafood meal, be treated to rich theatrics and effects, as well as underwater performances by divers in the Open Ocean Habitat. 

Only slots for October are available, so book your spot pronto at http://bit.ly/aquagastronomy

I seriously think Bray's a rural boy trapped in a city! ⁣
⁣
Thanks to award-winning tour agency @letsgotoursingapore, I got to verify this in a morning at Kampong Lorong Buangkok, for a cosy and interactive 《𝐀 𝐋𝐨𝐧𝐠 𝐋𝐨𝐧𝐠 𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞 𝐀𝐠𝐨: 𝐕𝐢𝐥𝐥𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐬 𝐭𝐨 𝐇𝐢𝐠𝐡 𝐑𝐢𝐬𝐞𝐬》tour. This curated guided tour is from a NEW LAUNCH of the 'This is Home' Local Edu-Tainment Tour series, part of 10 exciting, educational, immersive and experiential walking tours to encourage locals to rediscover Singapore, explore our local culture and heritage, nature, art, and architecture and more! ⁣
⁣
When we started in the morning, our friendly guide, Yap, asked Bray if he would like to stay in a Kampong. He hesitated and replied meekly, "No...Because very muddy!" However, in less than an hour into the tour, he was so mesmerised spotting millipedes to poke (🙈😝) and declared that he would love to stay here anytime! ⁣
⁣
What else did he say and we do?⁣
It was so fun that I'd to blog about it!⁣
Check it out k! #linkinbio too!⁣
👉 https://belandbray.wordpress.com/2020/09/10/letsgotour-kampong-experience/⁣
⁣
Look out for more immersive and experiential walking tours by @letsgotoursingapore!⁣
Suitable for families with children, students, couples, and small groups of friends, their curated tours will be great bonding activities for the weekends or school holidays. Singaporeans will also be able to utilise their #SingapoRediscovers Vouchers (tourism credits) on these tours!⁣
⁣
Thank you @letsgotoursingapore & @atmcbizexpert again for the awesome #mediainvite. The lovely Kampong tour is really one-of-its-kind! ⁣

✨ [Pulau Ubin Guided Tour from $58/person] ✨
.
Take a day trip to this beautiful island and discover all the beauty that it has to offer. Visitors will be picked up from their homes 🏠 to the jetty and take a 15-min bumboat ride 🛶 to the island with our licensed tourist guide.
.
You will have a glimpse into Singapore's yesteryears, alongside 🌴 coconut rubber plantations, fish farms and Singapore’s last-remaining kampong (traditional village).
.
Originally known as Pulau Batu Jubin (Granite Stone Island in Malay), this 1020-hectare island’s granite quarries once provided the stone used to construct structures like the Istana and the Singapore-Johore Causeway.

Have you gotten it right? 😆😜

The answer is Leopard Corydoras, which is commonly known as Corydoras julii! Great job to those who guessed correctly! For the rest of us, nice try! Let’s all try harder again in the next round! 

Corydoras julii is not demanding and tolerates a range of initial water parameters. Water can be slightly acidic to slightly alkaline, with soft to medium-hard water hardness. The substrate in this fish’s tank must be soft, as it will scavenge the bottom for bits of food. Sand or small and smooth gravel is suitable. Driftwood is recommended, as well as other items that can serve as hiding places. Plants are also essential. Floating plants are often used to dim the lighting, as this fish does not appreciate bright lights.

Furthermore, Corydoras julii accepts most food. You can offer it sinking tablets or pellets as their primary diet. Live foods like brine shrimp, daphnia, and bloodworms can be offered to supplement their diet. Because it is a nocturnal, it is best to feed it before lights are turned off.

Lastly, Corydoras julii is best kept in a school of a minimum of four or more. It gets along well with small catfish and small peaceful fish. Possible tankmates include small members of the tetra family, rasboras, dwarf cichlids, danios and other small community fish. You should avoid any large or aggressive fish.

As a West-sider, the Eastern part of Singapore is somewhere I rarely step foot into. A month back, while visiting a friend in the east, I decided to explore Joo Chiat/Katong area - Singapore’s first Heritage Town. 

Since then, I’ve returned twice more to check off a handful of must-eats there, and to hunt down Instagrammable spots like these unique pre-war shophouses.

Moments like this make me think about the upside of being trapped in Singapore (although not indefinitely). I’m “forced” to rediscover my country, which brings along opportunities to learn about and view this little red dot through a different lens. Can’t wait to check out more sights & makan places around Singapore , and looking forward to playing host to foreign friends again when leisure travel resumes!

raffles has always been a dream of mine to stay in and so far, it has not disappointed. the restoration is absolutely stunning - if you know me, you know i love my heritage buildings and colonial interiors! 🌴 there’s something so special about staying in a place so rich with history. @raffleshotelsingapore doesn’t even feel like you’re in the middle of the city! i feel at home here 🥰

Five international dance troupes will be celebrating this Mid-Autumn Festival "together" by putting up an online Chinese dance performance on 30 September 2020 (Eve of the Mid-Autumn Festival). 

The concert will feature dances from Atlanta Chinese Dance Company (USA), 一般社団法人 中国舞踊サロン Chinese Dance Salon - CDS (Tokyo, Japan), 澳門英姿舞園 Macau Ieng Chi Dance Association (Macau SAR), 新加坡华族舞蹈剧场 Singapore Chinese Dance Theatre (Singapore), and Shadow Danceland 影子舞团 (Mauritius).

Do join us at our respective Facebook page on 30 September 2020 at SGT 8pm (GMT +8) to watch the “live” stream. Don’t miss it!

Trithemis aurora, the crimson marsh glider, is a species of #dragonfly in the family Libellulidae. It is a medium-sized dragonfly that is commonly found in weedy tanks and ponds, marshes, channels, and slow flowing streams and rivers in the lowlands and mid-hills. It breeds in streams, rivers, canals, ponds and tanks. (Source: Wikipedia)

Recovery Walk along East coast for Food & Coffee. Past by a few heritages establishments. Guillemard Camp (1969-2003) -  home to the First Singapore Infantry Regiment. One of the oldest furniture shops in Singapore, that specialises in classic rattan furniture. A old styled coffee and bakes that is permanently closed. A new Starbucks outlet at colonial-era former Joo Chiat Police Station that was built in 1928. And lastly, Katong Shopping Centre - the first air-conditioned mall in Singapore. Now well-known for its Chicken rice at the food court in its basement level.

Can you see the moon tonight?

Tomorrow night, 1st October, will be a full moon night. The moon will be at its roundest and biggest, also known as the Harvest Moon. It is also the Mid Autumn Mooncake festival.

Enjoy your moon photography tomorrow.

This photo of the moon was shot with a Sony G-Master 70-200mm lens. Shutter speed was set at 1/125, aperture at f/8 and ISO200.

1 Ekim 2020’de Ankara Singapur Büyükelçiliği’nde küçük bir Singapur dostu Türk grubuyla (#FriendsofSingapore) Ay Festivali (Mooncake Festival) olarak da bilinen Güz Ortası Festivali’ni (Mid-Autumn Festival) kutladık. Birbirinden lezzetli ay keklerinin tadını çıkararak Çin çayı içtik ve festivalin tarihi ile mitolojisi hakkında bilgi edindik!
.
Çok ırklı ve çok dinli bir ülke olarak, Singapur topluma farklı görüntüler, sesler, tatlar ve inançlar mozaiği sunan, geleneksel ve dini birçok festival kutlar! Güz Ortası Festivali, Çin asıllı Singapurlular tarafından kutlanan ve MÖ 1600 yılına dayanan bir festival olup, hasat zamanının başlangıcını ve Ay’ın en parlak olduğu zamanı kutlar!
.
Elçilikte yapılan kutlamanın kısa bir videosuna buradan erişebilirsiniz!
.
On 1 October 2020, we celebrated Mid-Autumn Festival or 中秋节 (also known as Mooncake Festival) at the Singapore Embassy in Ankara with a small group of Turkish #FriendsofSingapore (due to social distancing requirements). We enjoyed a variety of delicious mooncakes and Chinese tea, and learnt about the history and mythology behind the festival!
.
As a multiracial and multireligious country, Singapore celebrates a wide range of festivals – both religious and traditional, giving our society a vibrant mosaic of sights, sounds, tastes and beliefs! The Mid-Autumn Festival is celebrated by the Singaporean Chinese and is one of the oldest festivals dating back to 1600 BC. This marks the start of the harvest season and a time of year that the moon is at its brightest! 
.
Here is a short video of the celebration at the Embassy!

Retired birds from @jurongbirdpark.sg Kings of the Skies show will now enjoy the rest of their golden years in a new aviary open to the public. 🤗

The oldest resident at the senior aviary is Rod Stewart (first slide), an Egyptian vulture who is estimated to have hatched in the early 1960s making him close to 60 years old. With an average of 21-year lifespan for this species in the wild, Rod has lived way beyond his life expectancy and is said to remain “spritely for his age and likes to roam about the ground level of the exhibit.”

Passiflora suberosa is a species of passionflower native to the Americas. It is commonly known as corkystem passionflower due to the corkiness of older stems. The fruit is not hardy and transitions from green to indigo, purple and, lastly, black as it ripens. This species is a host plant for several species of caterpillars and a larval host plant for the glasswing butterfly (Acraea andromacha) in Australia.~ Wikipedia

With more varieties of flowers, we should see more butterflies! 🦋💚

It reminds me of the God of Wealth's hat! 🤣

post_caption:
Appreciating the hidden gems of Little India, Joo Chiat and Chinatown 

📍Little India
•Little India - Once a place for racecourse, cattle herders and brick kilns. Now one of Singapore’s most vibrant districts.
•Little India Street Art / Five Foot Way -Explore Little India's rich multicultural history through its vibrant walls. ☝🏽On a side note, did you notice that 5-foot-way? the roofed continuous walkway commonly found in front of shops, the name refers to the width of the passageway. These walkways were meant to protect pedestrians from the hot tropical sun as well as rain.
•Deepavali Street Light Up - One of the major cultural festivals in Singapore, Deepavali (also known as “Diwali” or the “Festival of Lights”) is a celebration that marks the triumph of good over evil. 
•House of Tan Teng Niah - windows of the unique and colorful Chinese Villa that was built in 1900

📍Kampong Gelam
•Streetside Barbershop
•Spiral Staircases of Bugis - These external pre-cast concrete staircases first made their appearance at the rear of shophouses from the mid-1920s. Their introduction facilitated an important regular routine for households and residents living in the shophouses – the collection of night-soil. Night-soil is a euphemism for human faeces. The term came about, as human waste was collected in buckets in the silence of the night and sometimes, soil was used as a cover. A night-soil carrier would enter the alleys behind the shophouses and climb these spiral staircases to each storey. That was where buckets filled with night-soil were placed.

📍Joo Chiat
•Peranakan Shophouses of Joo Chiat

📍Chinatown
•Peranakan Shophouses of Bukit Paso 

In my heart, Singapore is more than just a face of industrialization. Inside her is a soft spot waiting to be discovered. She is more than just a pretty face. Indeed, worthy of our love and respect. Majulah Singupara!
.
📱on iPhone

Old and New meet at the ever changing, glam Kampong Glam.

Pigeons famous, Kampong Glam is the Muslim center of Singapore, and is traditionally home to mosques, carpet shops, and Middle Eastern cuisine, while more recently the area has seen a surge in boutique cocktail bars and funky restaurant openings. Sightseers will enjoy the picturesque streets with their beautifully restored shophouses, while shoppers are in for a treat with a selection of Singapore’s best offbeat boutiques selling cult labels and vintage clothing.

(Oh yes, after only 200 shots her majesty the glam pigeon quickly flew into place which is appreciated by me.)

Walkcation nostalgia: This building used to be known as the Asia Insurance Building. When I passed there occasionally as a school boy, I would crane my neck to gaze at the tall building. At 82 metres, it was once the tallest building not just in Singapore but also in South-east Asia. Now it is a dwarf in Singapore. Good that the government has preserved this and the Customs House as heritage buildings. We need them to anchor our memories. --- gct

post_caption:
[Under-the-radar hub-and-spoke café ✈️☕️]

@hubandspokecafe is a very young new ground level café located just minutes away from @changiairport Terminal 2. 

Most of the café's offerings are western-style brunch, pastas, salads, breakfast toasts, and the usual coffee/tea offerings. What stands out and to keep with modern times, is that they have bubble tea offerings too. 

This isn't a food review though, but just to publicise such a place exists. 

Also, they accept your own cups and bottles if you wish to use your own to-go cup in replacement of the single-use cups they offer for cold drinks! 💚 

The café also has showers (coming soon)! 🚿🛀

Right now, the café has great views of the main road, which includes glimpses of buses passing by as they exit the Terminal 2 Passenger Building. 🚌🚌

One incentive to visit this café is if you cycle along the Park Connector Network from East Coast Park via the Jurassic Mile. Bicycle racks are available, with a bicycle rental service by Go Cycling as well. 🚲

There is a vending machine selling items from cables to wet tissues and face masks.

If you are going to take a walk from @jewelchangiairport , it's about 2k–3k+ steps each way via the Terminal 2–Jewel link bridge. 

Once any travel bubble or when the SQ tours set in, hopefully we will see more traffic at this cornerside café. It's not that accessible unless you park at the South Carpark near Terminal 2 or the Carpark 2A and walk in (if it's open?).
.
.
2020
Changi Airport, Singapore

Always welcome for a cuppa of coffee right in the middle of Raffles Place when the sun sets. ☕

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Sago Lane / Sago Street, in Chinatown

Sago Lane (and Sago Street) gets its name from the many sago factories in the area in mid-1800s Singapore. However, Sago Lane is more famous (or infamous) for another reason - its death houses.

In the past when most Chinese immigrants lived in Chinatown area, the terminally ill would go to a death house where they literally awaited their fate – death.

Now the street has just been revitalised with new arch Chinatown signs and Chinese orientated shelters. 

Of course the main attraction is still the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple. Even if you are not there to pray, the lanterns or lighting (during some festive periods) are an attraction itself.

Given the most depressing covid period, any nice temple or street lighting certainly cheers us up and gives us hope. 🙏

This is Sajeev. He is the owner of Sajeev Digital Studio in Little India, a cramped but friendly space where the walls are lined with thousands of past portraits he’s taken over the years.

His main clientele consists of foreign workers from India and Sri Lanka who send their portraits back home so their families can help in the matchmaking process and search for their future wives. He says his business has been affected by Covid as new foreign workers have stopped entering the country. Still, he was gracious enough to give me a quick tour of his studio, observe a shoot, and discuss a bit of his unique story and business model.

Never write off the waters of Singapore! 💯

Felt so weird cos we surfaced from our dive to the view of refineries and breakwaters compared to the usual palm trees and white sand beaches in other countries.

Pulau Hantu is perfect for macros and those going on a nudi hunt! Much less on the bigger stuff due to the shit vis, though we were super super lucky to get a turtle, a bamboo shark and a school of ikan bawal (yum yum!) towards the end of our dive 🤙🤙🤙 slowly starting to think that I’m a turtle whisperer...... 🙊

10/10 would do it again! Thanks @cuddlefishdivers for having us :)

post_caption:
And on the right side of the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple lies Sago Lane (Street of the Dead). 
In the past, the street was much longer and was home to funeral parlours or death houses. 
The lane's famous Chinese death houses came into existence in the late 19th century. This was the place where people near death will be left to die.
As people were superstitious and believed that it was inauspicious to die in their own home, many chose to pay a small fee to stay in these death houses to wait for their time.
Sago Lane after all is not just a lane, it is a History in itself.
.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Thanks to @poojakawatra latest post that reminded of my visit and moments at National Museum of Singapore last year.

I am fond of art and got totally absorbed in the work I saw of some of the proficient painters in the art gallery and exhibitions at the museum. I was in awe of the architecture of the building as you can see I coudnt stop clicking photos!

This marvel of architecture and art has every corner befitting as Instagram portrait!

Hope it gives you a fair and justified idea of this beautiful place, a must visit in Singapore 🇸🇬 if you appreciate art, literature, history and architecture.

I was randomly checking their website and found virtual gallery experience wherein you have a collection of exhibitions of various artists and documentary photographers to choose from to see their work online. Also, they have family oriented art activities for an immersive experience.

A kampong's beauty
.
The Last Kampong in Singapore - Appreciate that the last kampong on Singapore’s mainland, not only does Lorong Buangkok serve as an important cultural and historical symbol, I feel that its camaraderie is also something that we can learn from. Residents there welcome each other’s presence and help each other out.
Even though HDB flats attempt to imitate the kampong spirit and induce cohesion among the residents, the camaraderie present is but only a feeble imitation of the kampong spirit.

Kampong Buangkok’s postal code was 1954, when Singapore still used only four digits for postal codes before 1st September 1995. It has since been changed to a six-digit postal code now, but this sign remains as a nostalgic reminder. There's always a sense of warmth and presence of human touch in such a peaceful environment like how friendly Mak Cik (malay auntie) was when I chatted with her. 
Hope this place will be kept and allow the younger generations to learn those valuable lessons we can never learn in class.

Remember to seek Mr and Miss Sng for approval to walk through this wonderful kampong. Seek the residents permission and respect the residents' privacy when are in their premises. 
.
.
.
.
.
.

Bussiness goes on. . . Earning a living after the circuit breaker. The last of Singapore’s streetside barber start his busssiness during the phase one.

Undying dedication to his trade and a master of the art, the one old-school barber. Streetside barbers used to be a thriving industry back then. Haircuts, and shave has been his passion for the last 56 years. A "A+" classic... .
.
Mr Lee is located behind Moosehead along Telok Ayer Street and he usually opens from 10.30am-4pm from Mon-Fri and 10.30am-3pm on Sat. To make an appointment, call him at 97712146. I am so wanting to try nostril hair trim 😄

The Ice-Cream Street Hawker.🍦
Ice-cream carts like this can be found in housing estates, along Orchard Road or in the town area. They have become part of Singapore’s hawker culture and heritage. However, since their licenses are personal to the holder and non-transferable, and new ones are no longer issued anymore, we may one day see this unique trade disappear.
The ice-cream uncle here was having a snack before the customers came over, which explains why he didn’t have his mask on. 😷

Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖with permanent exhibits is officially opened on 11 Oct 2020 😃 
Between 16 Oct 2020 to 3 Jan 2021, visitors will have to reserve a slot on Changi PlayPass https://playpass.changiairport.com/ or iChangi App if planning to visit the Jurassic Mile on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays between 9am and midnight due to current COVID-19 era safe distancing concerns.

Approx. 20 mins walk from Hub & Spoke cafe (next to Changi Airport Terminal 2 Carpark 2A end / across South Carpark) via the new Changi Airport Connector (red pathway) to reach Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 ;
or just take bus or vehicle directly to Changi Airport Terminal 4 Carpark 4A that is next to one of the entrance of Changi Jurassic Mile. We took about 1 hour 10 mins to walk to-and-fro the stretch of Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 including some time spent on photo-taking 📷📸

新加坡🇸🇬最新打卡景点：Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖 @ Changi Airport Connector. Next to Changi Airport Terminal 4, Carpark 4A.
开放24小时、入场免费、永久展览；在疫情期间，如果打算在每逢星期五至星期天的时段参观，必须上 Changi Airport 的网站或 iChangi App 预定入场票。

Alone but not lonely.

Can you spot 3 people who are alone (and in their own world) in this photo?

Personally, i'm a huge proponent of #metime. Spending time alone is actually a good thing as the relationship you have with yourself is the most important one in your life. 

According to research, dedicating some me time to yourself has benefits such as increased productivity, happiness, gratitude and empathy. It also allows you to recharge your batteries, slow down and take your mind off from the hustle and bustle of everyday life. 

When was the last time you really spent quality me time with yourself?

You have heard of Singapore Sling, but do you know the origin of this cocktail?🍹Step back in time…the Singapore Sling’s history began from as early as 1915, developed by a bartender working at the Long Bar in Raffles Singapore Hotel. Originally created as a lady's drink and thus the pink hue, it has become a world-renowned cocktail still being mixed in Raffles Singapore.

A different experience exploring in the dark and coming up close to animals at night. You can only do this at the Night Safari, the world's first nocturnal zoo! It was the kids' first time at the Night Safari and we had a great time there! There were moments where it was pitch dark when we were on the tram and our senses were heightened so we could spot, hear or smell something nearby. 

Swipe to check out our video where we had close encounters with hyenas and cheetahs! 

The kids were exhausted after we exited the Night Safari because it was close to their bedtime but they agreed that it was an awesome and refreshing experience to see animals at night. We missed the Creatures of the Night Show because it was full but we will be back again!

Discover this hidden gem at Fort Canning Park, the next popular Instagram-worthy place. 

The Fort Canning Tree Tunnel is an underground crossing with spiral staircase that links Dhoby Ghaut to the park. If you look up, you can see a circle of lush greenery.

When it comes to Mid-Autumn Festival, the first thing that comes to my mind will be the moon cakes. My family and I will love to get a box or two of the moon cakes from the shops in Chinatown. At home, we will sit together in front of the television and enjoy the moon cakes with a cup of green tea. We also love to meet up with my parents, sisters and nieces in their home or in a park for lantern walk. Well, for me I will love to go down to Chinatown to take photos of the beautiful Mid-Autumn festival street decorations and walk the streets of Chinatown to get the feel of the festival there.

A Heart Warming Mid-Autumn 2020

牛车水庆中秋2020

You never know which way life is gonna head. There are so many turns, twists, detours and roadblocks that there is no point sweating on the small stuff. So do the things that make you happy. Get inspired and get outside that comfort zone. Don’t listen to the voices of doubt that hang around us and go for it. Life is like too bloody short to sit around and wait for good things to come 😊👍 That’s why we wouldn’t trade what we have built for the world. “Going to an antique shop may not be an idea of fun for most people but I’ve always loved stopping by The Heritage Shop, located along Jalan Sultan with my kids. 

We would pick one item and ask them what they think it is for. I think an antique shop can teach kids about history through items and help us appreciate how far we've come. 

There was life before us and fascinating stories of people who have walked on the same ground as us!”

It’s already 945pm by the time we reached and we rushed to find the spot! We then snapped and made @monicalodia profusely spin so many times 😂😂😂.

• Sony a6000 + SEL20F28 •
• ISO 100  F 9.0  30 secs •

Something I've always enjoyed about night photography is experimentation with long exposures. I love the effect I get with clouds, moving water and of course, light trails with moving objects.

To envision with your mind's eye and then be able capture what the eye is unable to physically see is truly satisfying. Using photography to capture more than just light - capture time and space.

Everyone is buzzing over the new floating Apple Store that I just had to pay homage to the original structure on water, The LV Island Maison!

[ Who Painted The Tree? ]

I have visited Katong Park and walked pass this tree more than times than I could count but I have never realised the beauty of it until recently someone told me that there is a "Rainbow🌈" tree in this park.

As I walked and looked closer, the tree does look like someone painted it, but it is actually naturally gorgeous. From the #NParks signboard I learned that this colourful tree that features rainbow coloured streaks along its trunk is called Rainbow Eucalyptus. As the tree sheds its outer bark at different times to reveal the neon green bark underneath, over time, this layer is exposed to air and ages into different colors — from green to blue to purple to orange to maroon before finally falling off the tree.

This colourful tree is also the only one of its kind in Singapore and has been listed by the National Parks as a Heritage Tree. If you are the type that like to chase after rainbows, it is located at Katong Park, near the Fort Road exit of East Coast Park.

p.s. No tree was harmed in the making of this series

[Kampong Gelam Precinct] - The Iconic Zam Zam food stall

Re-discovering Kampong Gelam again starting with food and its people.  Rediscovering is about documenting great people working hard amidst the pandemic to serve us with great food with passion.

You should not miss out the friendly people from Singapore Zam Zam. It is established in 1908 and one of the most popular Indian-Muslim restaurant in Singapore. They are well-known for their murtabak (in photo), Roti prata, Nasi biryani and many other dishes for over a century.  The best part about this place  is that their staff are very friendly and engaging. Love to capture their moments

Meet the 🌈 multi-coloured old Hill Street Police Station! It is one of Singapore’s favourite spot for visitors and locals alike that love to take photos! This Skittles-like facade with 900+ windows is quite central and convenient to get to. It is at the Clarke Quay MRT station 🚉  and after your photo session here, you can either go hang around #ClarkeQuay for a drink or a munch... or head over towards Fort Canning, a beautiful oasis in the middle of the city, also home to a few other very photogenic places!

This structure dates back to 1934 and once housed the Hill Street Police Station and Barracks. Today, it is used by the Ministry of Communications and Information and Ministry of Culture, Community and Youth.

🇸🇬 2020 CAN STILL BE YOUR YEAR! 🇸🇬
𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗸𝗻𝗼𝘄 𝘄𝗵𝗲𝗻 𝗮 𝗻𝗲𝘄 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿 𝗮𝗿𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗲𝘀, 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗼𝗳𝘁𝗲𝗻 𝘀𝗮𝘆 “𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗶𝘀 𝗺𝘆 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿“ ... 𝗪𝗲𝗹𝗹 𝗶𝘁 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗹 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗯𝗲!
Instead of focusing on the things that don't matter, get obsessed with who you're becoming, where you're going and all of the amazing things you're going to accomplish!

More than ever, this year in which everything has been on pause, has been the best time to do everything you always wanted to do! Your personal projects, your side-hustles, etc!

To think that there is only 3 months left to this year is crazy, but don’t let that time pass by, use it wisely and create!

It has been such a year, not much travel, but on a positive side, I got to see so much more of what Singapore has to offer, to create great friendships and have many wonderful projects involving talented people.

Hope that you got the chance to optimize this weird 2020 as well and celebrate little wins!

I was strolling around Sago Lane and its surrounding area a week back. It used to be the home for several funeral parlours or death houses. As I walk on the Sago Lane closer to the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, a gust of wind blew strongly, shaking the red lanterns hung around the temple. It felt a bit spooky, but it also brought in a sense of amazement in me.

Continuing after, I went to the adjacent side of Sago Lane, called Sago Street. It was named that way because during the 1800s, there were many sago factories there. I also learned that it used to house a number of brothels around the late 19th century. 

I explored into some alleyways in wonder and in one moment, I realized that I got to pick up my camera and shoot.

When we are able to go back traveling again to Singapore, go visit Chinatown! It is an amazing precinct rich with history :)

Shopping for Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

During its peak, up to 300 people visited the hot spring daily. On 1 March 2002, it was closed for two months while upgrading & improvement works were carried out to the area around the spring, which had become sodden & muddy. Littering had also become a problem because of the increased numbers of visitors. The former dirt track leading to the spring was paved with cement, & lined with bougainvillea bushes & high fences to ensure the security of the air base. Drainage pipes were also installed. Mindef, which owns the land, allows public access between 7 am and 7 pm daily, free-of-charge. When the spring reopened on 1 May 2002, more than 100 people visited the site despite the afternoon drizzle. At the same time, some new free-hold condominiums were built in the surrounding area; one of the developments, built by the property arm of F&N in 2001, is called Seletaris, named after the company's former mineral water.

In July 2005, a Business Times reader proposed that the authorities should explore the possibility of tapping the geothermal heat that lies many miles under Sembawang—similar to the project in South Australia's Cooper Basin—in order to aid Singapore's reliance on oil and gas. The proposal was not acted upon.

 As of 2014, the well can still be seen locked inside a red-brick enclosure with a steel gate, & its geothermal heat can be felt outside the building. Some plastic chairs, pails and mini-tubs kindly donated by visitors are stored at the perimeter of the compound, which has a makeshift shed in one corner. A caretaker, paid for by Mindef, takes care of the place to maintain its overall cleanliness, but there is no toilet on location. The hot spring is less frequented nowadays but remains rustic for rural & suburban families to discover & explore.

Karma is an action, not a result. The future is not set in stone as you can change the course of your life at this very moment by changing your intentional acts and self-destructive patterns.

Karma is energy and it’s our intentional thoughts and actions. The energy we generate now and in the future will affect us. It has nothing to do with reward or punishment. 

For us, our karma is treating life as big collaboration. Individually, we are one drop. 
Together, we are an ocean.
Daily, in your own little ways, the best we can all do is stay positive, support each other and put a smile on the face of people around. 

Kindness, Positivity, Support, Collaboration always win.
Anger, Negativity, Resentment, Jealousy ... well we don't care about the outcome as they are ignored and dismissed.

Stay positive! Keep communucating with your loved ones and we will go through this 2020 year all fine 🙏🏼

post_caption:
The Mid-Autumn Festival means more than just lanterns and mooncakes to me, it's a celebration of tradition, culture and time spent with the family. 

As per tradition, we spent a full day at Chinatown, amidst the smells and the sounds we ate a hearty lunch and strolled passed the usual routes. Bought somethings here and there and visited the Buddha's tooth temple.  Following that we returned home to a comforting and lively family gathering at grandma's place in celebration of the Mid-Autumn Festival. 

It's hard to get time with everyone in our hustle bustle life but just a simple meal with the ones you love is all that you need. 

Photos are in the back after the video. 
@chinatown_festivals 

#ChinatownMAF2020
#singaporediscovers 
#ChinatownSG

Pictures in the following order.

3. Ann Siang Hill Water Well - which used to serve the Traders in the old days 

4. Dead houses - Sago lane used to be the dead houses in the olden days. 

5. Former Queen’s Theater - an entertainment venue for more than 6 decades. 

Visit these places and rediscover #Singapore. #visitsingapore

The Fullerton Hotel Singapore at night.

The magnificent Fullerton Building is a grand neoclassical landmark built in 1928. Gazetted in December 2015 as a National Monument, it was once home to Singapore’s General Post Office, the Exchange Room and Exchange Reference Library, and the prestigious Singapore Club.

Went to @gardensbythebay a few weeks ago before my injury. It was my first time visiting the Cloud Forest. I also brought along the @samsung_sg Galaxy Tab S7 to do some sketching at the Cloud Forest and also try out the Samsung tablet that I got.
.
The battery life is pretty good, it lasted the entire day and the pen can be used for drawing without charging. The sensitivity is on-point too. I used Clip Studio and Adobe Sketch for the sketches during my visit.
.
The cloud forest visit itself was a nice experience as well. I think I spent about two hours in it, the mosses reminded me of the trip to Kibune earlier this year.
.

Relish in the ultimate beauty experience at Darshini Beauty & Spa, where you'll feel beautiful inside and out. Their professional beauticians come with years of experience from India, so you can truly enjoy their stunning array of beauty services, available for any occasion.
