post_caption:
Heard the good news? The government is giving out $100 tourism credits for us to use on staycays, attractions and more! 

We’ve got plenty of suggestions to make the most out of your SingapoRediscovers vouchers. Ready to start planning your Singapore holiday?👇

🛵Roam around in vintage Vespa sidecars 🛵

Hop on board a retro Vespa with @singaporesidecars and explore heritage trails from Tiong Bahru and Tanglin to Joo Chiat and Katong to Kampong Glam and the Civic District.

🐠Explore the underwater world 🐠

The perfect indoor option for rainy or scorching days, S.E.A Aquarium at @rwsentosa is filled with more than 100,000 marine creatures, from hammerhead sharks and giant moray eels to sea nettle and reef manta rays.

✈️ Jet off to Bali in a jiffy ✈️ 

Well… sorta. Boutique hotel @lloydsinn brings us straight to Bali with an outdoor bathtub in The Big Sky Room, an alfresco roof terrace and a dipping pool. 

✨Admire displays of art and science ✨

Satisfy your love for both at @artsciencemuseumsg which currently holds two exhibitions including Future World, an interactive space filled with intriguing light art displays.

🏝Splash and dash at a floating aqua park 🏝

At @hydrodash.sg, you can slide, leap, bounce and climb your way through a massive inflatable obstacle course on the waters of Sentosa.

Date: Saturday, 24 Oct 2020⁣
Time: 15.00 - 17.00⁣
Instructor: Tony Sugiarta⁣
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695⁣
⁣
Course Fee: SGD20⁣
*Price inclusive of tools and materials.⁣
*$10 will be refunded upon successful completion of artwork.⁣
⁣
This workshop is part of 1+1 = Infinity: A Collaborative Digital Batik Art (www.batikinfinity.com) project by @anerdgallery, in collaboration with Lokka Lekkr Makers Studio. The project is part of #SGCultureAnywhere and is supported by National Arts Council.⁣
⁣
Batik is both personal and collaborative. Batik is both structured and free. Batik is both wild and meditative. Let's explore Batik!⁣
⁣
Let's create a batik artwork/pattern that reflects your "Singapore". In this two-hour session, we will introduce common batik motifs as a warm-up and as an inspiration. This will be followed by a guided batik-making session where you will explore your inner artistic expression while tapping on the creative exchange among your fellow artists. ⁣
⁣
Need technical help about batik-making for the project? Or you simply want to have fun creating artworks with friends? Join us in this unique in-person session, get inspired and express yourself in batik!⁣
⁣
Note: This session is designed for adult participants. However, the DIY batik kit is suitable for participants who are 7 years old and above. You may sign-up to get it delivered to your place at batikinfinity.com/register. ⁣
⁣
Tony Sugiarta is the founder of aNERDgallery, "an-art-gallery" which specialises in promoting Indonesian textile art of batik and tenun. Through the platform, Tony aims to educate and to connect makers and textile enthusiasts through experiential workshops, exhibitions and textile trips.⁣
⁣

Since the signage reads “Supreme Pork Chop Rice”, there’s just no way I will order anything else besides their pork chop rice. Situated in the basement of a nondescript building along Beach Road, the stall is housed in an area with other F&B outlets. However, the clear favourite stall and the one with the queue is selling pork chop rice. At a cost of $4.30, it comes with a bowl-sized fried rice, some coleslaw, an egg and a glorious piece of deep fried pork chop. The star of the show shines brightly on the pork chop which is neither greasy nor fatty inside. Throw in some of their chilli for that spicy kick which sorts of alleviated the dish even further.
_________________
Supreme Pork Chop Rice
Address: 67, Beach Road, Bulkhaul House, Unit B1-01, Singapore 189688

Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖with permanent exhibits is officially opened on 11 Oct 2020 😃 
Between 16 Oct 2020 to 3 Jan 2021, visitors will have to reserve a slot on Changi PlayPass https://playpass.changiairport.com/ or iChangi App if planning to visit the Jurassic Mile on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays between 9am and midnight due to current COVID-19 era safe distancing concerns.

Approx. 20 mins walk from Hub & Spoke cafe (next to Changi Airport Terminal 2 Carpark 2A end / across South Carpark) via the new Changi Airport Connector (red pathway) to reach Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 ;
or just take bus or vehicle directly to Changi Airport Terminal 4 Carpark 4A that is next to one of the entrance of Changi Jurassic Mile. We took about 1 hour 10 mins to walk to-and-fro the stretch of Changi Jurassic Mile 🦖🦕 including some time spent on photo-taking 📷📸

新加坡🇸🇬最新打卡景点：Changi Jurassic Mile 🦕🦖 @ Changi Airport Connector. Next to Changi Airport Terminal 4, Carpark 4A.
开放24小时、入场免费、永久展览；在疫情期间，如果打算在每逢星期五至星期天的时段参观，必须上 Changi Airport 的网站或 iChangi App 预定入场票。

Hydrotherapy
Natural Spring Water
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

According to local geologists, the exact source of the spring remains unknown, but it is believed that its origin may be southwest of its actual location, possibly at Bukit Timah. Hot springs are formed when underground water comes into contact with hot rock masses. The resulting high pressure causes the water to seep upwards through cracks, forcing itself out of the ground as a spring.

A series of tests conducted by the PSB Corporation and SGS Testing & Control Services found the spring water contains 420 mg of chloride per litre, an amount which is substantially higher than the 35 to 100 mg in the water from Choa Chu Kang & Bedok waterworks. It was also found that the sulphide content is three times more than tap water & the spring water is also slightly alkaline due to the presence of minerals. Natural spring waters may have health benefits, similar to the hot springs of other countries near tectonic plates with volcanoes, in a search for cures for some skin conditions, as well as debilitating ailments like rheumatism & arthritis. Although local rheumatologists conceded that hydrotherapy is an accepted treatment that can be helpful for mild forms of rheumatism or muscle strain, they, along with dermatologists, remain skeptical of claims about the alternative healing of the natural spring water.

Hot hard water bubbles continuously in the well, releasing a slightly unpleasant sulphur mud-like odour together with steam. The temperature of the spring water is measured by precision instrument to be constant 70 °C (160 °F). In an investigation carried out by the Nanyang Technological University in 1994, the hot spring was found to have an estimated yield of approximately 150 litres (33 imp gal; 40 US gal) per minute at ground level through installed steel casings.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

The old #shophouses in Singapore are an important part of our heritage and they are a delight to photograph. Along Duxton road, you can find rows of two- and three-storey shophouse units that are beautifully-restored.

One great example is the former Six Senses Duxton, a boutique hotel that took up eight restored shophouses. Sadly, they have ceased operations not long ago.

#FunFact: Duxton Road had a seedy reputation for its opium dens, gambling dens & brothels during the early 19th and 20th centuries!

Check out our blog #linkinbio for more fun facts & secret insights about Singapore >> www.monsterdaytours.com/travel-tips-and-guides

Went back to Jewel again this weekend and visited Canopy Bridge (not part of Canopy Park btw)! The bridge gives you a close up view of the Jewel waterfall five stories up! Other than the close-up and height, the novelty of the bridge also lies in the fact that it is translucent (I say translucent as I couldn't see thru clearly due to reflection) so my younger girl was a bit scared 😅 Oh, and we really like the effect of the mist when we enter the bridge 😄
.
Actually I had thought  the bridge would let us walk around the waterfall but you only get to walk past the waterfall and it's really quite a short bridge. If you don't linger to take photos, you'll be at the other end within a minute 😂
.
Tickets cost us $3.60 each. Guess I didn't really mind as I bought the tics with the 55% discount they are having for Jewel attractions (only till 31 August). I probably wouldn't pay full price for this 😅 But still, we had a good ten minute fun enjoying the view and having wobbly knees 😄 How did your weekend go? 😉
.

Like many Singaporeans, I’m a great fan of Mustafa Centre. This place started its journey as a makeshift shop set up by Mohamed Mustafa and his son to sell ready-made garments on Campbell Lane. Over the years, Mustafa Centre was gradually built up from one shop to two large buildings along Syed Alwi Road. It was only in 2003 that Mustafa Centre became a 24-hour shopping centre, now with some adjustments to its operating hours. Not to worry – you can still buy almost anything there!
 
Take a look at all the spots I have rediscovered over at @STB_SG, and share your favourite part of Mustafa Centre with #SingapoRediscovers.

Last workshop in our September school holiday series! Spend meaningful time with your child and teach them the importance of preserving Mother Earth 🌏 through this beeswax wrap making workshop!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Date: Saturday, 12 September 2020⁣⁣
Time: 10.30 - 11.30⁣⁣
Instructor: Clara Simanjuntak⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Course Fee: SGD45/parent & 1 child⁣⁣
Price inclusive of tools and materials⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Clara Simanjuntak is Nyananyana Eco-fashion founder and designer. The clothing and accessories brand was conceptualised in Singapore in 2011. After a long journey of sourcing and research about all natural fabrics and dyes from plants, the brand finally launched in 2017 in Jakarta. Nyananyana is currently based in Singapore.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
She conducts workshops to introduce natural dye as a form of Nyananyana’s green campaign.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Clara also the founder of Jakarta Museum Playdate, community of parents and children where she visits and eco friendly themed workshop in museums.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Beeswax wraps have become more popular as eco-friendly household items, replacing cling wraps that are non-biodegradable. In this hands-on workshop, participants will learn the use of beeswax wraps, materials needed and how to make a wrap step-by-step.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
By using certified organic fabric with natural dye and organic forest beeswax, say goodbye to single-use plastic covers. Each participant will get to bring back one piece of their self made beeswax.⁣
⁣

-The Deities and the Dead-

I have always walked by this temple and never thought much about it apart from its distinctive Tang Dynasty design in our urban environment.

Rediscovering Singapore is how I adapt to this new change (or new normal)! While finding local iconic spots to shoot in new perspective, I discovered that the Sago Lane beside this temple was known to be the “Dead People Street”, as the terminally ill would go to these houses to wait for death. 

The business-minded Chinese would make the upper floors of the shophouses the “death house”, while the ground floor serves as a funeral parlour, and that stretch of road would be the road to send off the dead!

How many of us truly know the history and cultural heritage of these newly developed places? Anyone know more spots like this to share with me, or you would like me to explore more?

Visited the National Gallery last weekend and what an experience it was!

Loved the beautiful architecture preserved from yester-years which tells of Singapore's history from the times when we were under British rule to when we strived for independence.

I can't believe it's only been 55 years since the times of the night soil man and kampung dwellings to today's cosmopolitan city and high rise HDB flats. 🤯 Its amazing how things have changed and I can't imagine living through all these changes in a single lifetime.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Today’s mural (by Mr Yip) depicts a shop packing for pilgrims embarking on the Haj. The batiks represent the immigrants from the Malay archipelago while the carpet represents immigrants from the Middle East. 🧐

Beautiful view of AMK ❤️ 
Anyone stay AMK ? 
5 OCt 2020

Ang Mo Kio in Hokkien literally means the ‘red-haired man’s bridge’, where ang mo is a colloquial term for a Caucasian person. The name makes reference to the bridge over Kallang River in the area, built by Johnson Turnball Thomson, Government Surveyor of the Straits Settlement from 1841 to 1853. Another saying was that there were 9 bridges connecting the rural area back in those days, earning it the name ‘Kow Tiao Kio’ or Hokkien for ‘9 bridges’.

The town was largely uninhabited until the rubber boom in the beginning of the 20th century, which brought cultivation and habitation to the Chinese district. Ang Mo Kio comprised mainly farms and attap houses scattered among rubber estates.

The colourful Alkaff Bridge at Robertson Quay in Singapore.

Built in 1997 in the shape of a  tongkang—a light boat that shipped goods along the river—this 55-metre- the long pedestrian bridge was named after a prominent family who lived in  Singapore in the early 20th century. In 2004,  Filipino artist Pacita Abad painted it with whimsical patterns using 55 colours. This artwork is also one of The artist’s final projects.

Shot on Nikon Z5 + NIKKOR Z 24-200mm f/4-6.3 VR lens.

This place is probably the most common thing you have ever seen in your Instagram and Facebook feed right now! 😂 so I gonna compile everything into one post so I won’t spam you guys as well! We shot this on the second day of opening and we did a reservation before heading so take note! This place is inspired by the pantheon in Rome and it’s located at Marina Bay Sands! 

Tips when heading there : 
1) Remember to reserve your slot and timing online at the Apple website and one email is entitled to two person. 
2. Head there early even thou you might need to wait for awhile but it’s always good to be early then late.
3. There will be an Apple staff bringing you around and this tour is around 15 mins so for those people who wanna shoot, do know what’s the angle and view you wanna shoot so go there aim and go if not you have to come back another day! 😂😂😂
Lastly enjoy yourself there and take lotsa photos! 💕

Special thanks to @teelip from @apple for bringing @may_6reen @yongyichuaaa and me around! 🥰

3. Irvingia malayana, also known as wild almond or barking deer’s mango,is a tropical evergreen tree species in the family Irvingiaceae. The specific epithet malayana is from the Latin meaning "of Malaya".

Lantern Installation: “Rolling in Abundance”
(Supported by 78JO)
Produced by Hong Kong artist Sunny Tam of the collectible label, 78JO in collaboration with the Sun Yat Sen Nanyang Memorial Hall, “Rolling in Abundance” is an outdoor installation featuring four large roly-poly fish lanterns. In Chinese culture, fishes (“yu”) symbolise completeness and abundance, as it is a homonym for the Mandarin word for “abundance” (“yu”). The rounded nature of the design is doubly symbolic, as roundness (“yuan”) also sounds similar to the Mandarin word for “reunion” (“tuan yuan”), and pays homage to the full and bright mid-autumn moon. 

“Rolling in Abundance” utilises wordplay to present traditional beliefs and values in a modern context, and encourages deeper understanding and appreciation of the beauty of the Chinese language. More importantly, in these trying times, the installation embodies our hope for more abundant years to come, and gives thanks as we reunite with families and loved ones during Phase 2 of Singapore’s circuit breaker period

Date: 15 September - 11 October
Time: 10.00am - 9.00pm (daily)

Where better to immerse in a kaleidoscope of cultures - Chinatown, a place that draws generations of visitors to its peculiar charm. Just like it’s contemporary counterparts, you can find relics that come alive in different forms by day and by night. 

Rediscovering Singapore gives us the chance to revisit the beginnings of our little red dot. It’s an opportunity to re-live our nation’s history while tuning into modern narratives of “hidden” spaces and people, hearing out the countless achievements and challenges from our forefathers and future generations.

“Little India is filled with vibrant colours that represent its rich culture and heritage. Besides Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple on Serangoon Road, one of the oldest temples in Singapore that was built in 1881, you can also explore Shree Lakshminarayan Temple, Singapore’s first dedicated place of worship for Northern Indian Hindus. 
 
Some other buildings that caught my eye over the years are two historical churches – Kampong Kapor Methodist Church and Church of the True Light. Not forgetting the Abdul Gafoor Mosque and the eclectic exterior of Sakya Muni Buddha Gaya Temple. All these buildings add unexpectedly to the vibrant facade of Little India.”
 
Captured by @darrensohphoto as part of #SingapoRediscovers.

Rediscovery is about capturing something beautiful in a new perspective. 
Beaulieu House may be one of Singapore's most well-preserved neo-classica and romanticl heritage buildings facing straits of Johor. The name means beautiful place in French and was built in 1910 by Jewish Businessman  Joseph Brook David as a holiday home.

I have decided to present this building in a different perspective to showcase its beauty as I re-visited the place recently. Great to visit with your lover ones.

📚 The last book you read?

Spring Well
“Village of Hot Water”
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1909, a Chinese merchant named Seah Eng Keong, the son of Chinese pioneer Seah Liang Seah, discovered hot springs in his pineapple estate in Sembawang. The three springs were channelled into one, so that the water would be conveniently concentrated in one area. A well was built along with the spring, which became popular with the villagers, who frequently sought the waters for their supposed healing powers. The spring's fame spread, resulting in the village becoming known as Kampong Ayer Panas, which means "Village of Hot Water" in Malay.

Soft drinks firm Fraser & Neave (F&N) acquired the site in 1922, & set up a bottling plant at nearby Semangat Ayer to tap the mineral water, which they labelled Seletaris. During the Second World War, the spring's flow was temporarily interrupted when a bomb fell near the well during a Japanese air raid over Singapore in 1942. After the fall of Singapore, the Japanese military seized the place & converted it into recreational thermal baths (onsen).

The hot spring was frequented by gamblers in 1960, who took "good luck" baths before the start of horse races. That same year, the villagers urged the authorities to develop the area into a spa-like onsen tourist resort. However, F&N shelved the suggestion after geologists could not trace the source of the spring water. In 1967, the proposal of the spa surfaced again, when F&N proposed plans for the development of a bathhouse, restaurants, a miniature golf course & even a nature reserve. However, the plans did not materialize, so the hot spring remained untouched & forgotten.

#SingapoRediscovers：新加坡首家可口可乐主题便利店🥤

@7elevensg 与可口可乐跨界合作，在新加坡推出一家双层的可口可里主题便利店，酷！这家店铺的装修以美式风格为主，墙上有超酷的霓虹灯装饰外，也有设计独特的桌椅，每一处都是拍网红照的好地方😍 

拍完照后，是时候来电好吃好喝的🤤 除了有售卖各种小吃饮料，你还能在店里度过悠闲的下午，玩玩桌上足球机、在bean bags区域和朋友聊天，还有充电插座，不担心电话用到到没电啦~

👉凡在在店内消费满7新币（须购可口可乐、Sprite或A&W商品），就可获得1次免费机会，参加抓娃娃活动。奖品包括折叠自行车、行李箱、野餐餐桌等等!

【7-Eleven x Coca-Cola Concept Store】
📍 4 Robinson Rd, Singapore 048543 （House of Eden in Raffles Place）
⏰ 7am to 11pm

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] Reflection of Joo Chiat’s best ambassadors 

Rediscovery is about having a good listening ear  and keen observation of the place and people.

Joo Chiat is a place with a rich history. We often see elderly around. Some leisurely walking around while others cycle. What is unique is the friendliness of the people. I was there twice recently. On both occasions, I have had elderly (residents or former residents) who came to chitchat with me about the heritage of the place as well as interesting places to shoot. They seem to be the best ambassadors of the place - For their knowledge and their part in the history of this place- to help us rediscover Singapore.

This is a reflection ( literally) of the elderly from Joo Chiat with the colorful peranakan house

鰻満 🍱Man Man Unagi 🎏

Man Man Unagi Japanese Restaurant 

Nothing comes fresher than Man Man’s char-grilled Unagi, their freshwater eels are air flown live from Mikawa Isshiki region, know for supplying the best freshwater eel in Japan. 

True fact: We were never a fan of unagi until Man Man came to Singapore 🤤

They do not have the legendary freshwater fish mud smell, nor that sweetness overload tare BBQ sauce which most eateries use them to cover up the mud.

COVID-19 took the world by its ankles and lifted it off, tumbling downhill since the start of spring 2020. With the much reduced number of daily reported cases and Phase 3 in sight, Singaporeans have slowly returned to the streets of Singapore. While travelling overseas is still not an option on the table, we may contribute to the economy and support the local tourism industry that has been hit hard by the pandemic.

Here in Little India, preparations for Deepavali are underway. Hindu devotees may be found purchasing festive goods in Little India, the streets are installed with festive lightings and are ready for the festival of light. As a whole, the nation seems ready to move away from the shadow cast by COVID-19, and instead look forward to celebrating Deepavali.

During my trips to Little India in the past 2 weeks, I noticed these beautiful road signages that seem to be unique to Little India. From my research, I found that these signages can be found on several streets: Campbell Lane, Buffalo Road, Kerbau Road, Veerasamy Road, Serangoon Road and Upper Weld Road. Despite my best efforts to collect them all, I've only managed to photograph 4 of the 6 that I've listed. Locating the Serangoon Road sign left me with unglam tanned lines that shall remain on me for sometime. Perhaps in this case, rediscovering Singapore may lead you to locating this road sign that has slipped through my fingers.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok, built in 1956, is probably the last Kampong in mainland Singapore

I decided to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks, who are always obliging for a chat or phototaking

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my late uncle house's  in Pasir Ris Kampong

The kids here run freely and love it here. The 70 year old uncle I spoke to, says the family always like to gather at their mom's house on weekend

You can see herbs, mango, banana and even a coca tree here.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone, to experience this kampong way of life. 

Just make sure you respect their privacy if they are not keen to have their pictures taken.

Note: Permissions have been granted to take the pictures of the residents, in their house compound, from afar.

ICYMI: All Singaporeans aged 18 and above will be receiving $100 worth of vouchers digitally accessible via Singpass to spend on staycations, local attractions and tours.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
The vouchers will be credited to you this December, perfect as a Christmas gift! It will be valid until June 2021 and can be used to offset ticket purchases and hotel stays so start planning your staycations now!⁠⠀
⁠⠀
The vouchers will also be distributed in denominations of $10 so it can be used in your preferred way, whether it’s spreading the $100 out across several visits or using it all up on a hotel stay.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
This is part of the $320 million SingapoRediscovers scheme announced last month, which is an effort by the government to promote local tourism amidst the pandemic as they are one of the most heavily affected sectors.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🎡 What would you spend these vouchers on? Share with us in the comments below!⁠⠀

post_caption:
Do you know😯: There's more than just golden ornaments and sweets during Deepavali. Observe the grand Silver Chariot Procession and you'll see that Deepavali is a humble celebration between family and friends as well. Comprising priests, devotees and volunteers, the procession begins its journey from Singapore's oldest Hindu temple every year a week before Deepavali before making its way into Singapore's heartlands with the simple aim of allowing Hindu families to offer their prayers to the presiding deity. #singaporediscovers @stb_sg

Try something new this weekend and go for a walking trail with your family! MacRitchie Reservoir is a water catchment area in central Singapore. Filled with wildlife, you can take a nice relaxing walk around the lake and away from the noise of city life. In Malaysia, Sungei Lembing offers a beautiful spot to watch the sunrise as well as a majestic waterfall. Bring your family to catch the rainbow that forms every morning.  ⁣
⁣
Over in Cameron Highlands, Malaysia, cooling temperatures await in a place known as the Mossy Forest. The fog in the air guarantees a magical atmosphere for you and family, as well as the perfect setting for an impromptu photoshoot if you feel up to it!⁣

post_caption:
First geocache - Easter Egg [GC8T562]
🗝 They always say - first step is the hardest. 

So, we take a baby step to start an adventure. 

09Oct2020 (Pandemic ~ Covid19 🦠) That was D day - Children’s Day, a School holiday in Singapore. Probably the best reason to not we procrastinate any further. 

We decided to get out and explore this day with E, our daughter, instead of coping at home studying and mugging for exams. Mugging a word often used for Singaporean children to go on drilling for their exams. 😄Muggle used in #harrypotter to describe someone who doesn’t know anything related magic and the wizardry world. Often used in Singapore to describe anyone who is not geocaching. 🤣 

Ok I went off-point. 

🗒 We started with a short walk along the footpath towards the treasure following the description. Surrounded by overgrown creepy green leaves, it took us about ten minutes (normal pace) to reach the coordinates. 

Walking with masks in this horrible humidity and heat was another challenge. 

This, however, did not deter E’s enthusiasm. She loves treasure hunting and detective stories. #geocaching will be the best family bonding activity, well, a family hobby. Besides, we had a pretty heavy lunch (steamboat/ hotpot!), so it was time to walk it off. 🤗

Soon we reached the exact spot but we just cannot find it!

Trying to clear some soil by rubbing our shoes on the ground, yes(!) we are neat freaks and too virus conscious nowadays. Everything seemed to have a layer of germs on it. 🤪

After fifteen minutes of poking and brushing the tips of the grass with my slippers, we decided to message the owner of the cache.

Funnily enough, while waiting for the reply, G being the man as he always is, decided to dig into some suspicious ground and found the Yellow Egg! It was a lovely “Easter-egg” Hunt! 🥳 

We are grateful to find our first cache in this little adventure of our mundane life. 🙏🏻 looking forward to more little hunts in the future. 

Meanwhile, stay safe and mask on! 😷

⠀
Make your staycation an unforgettable one with these unique experience with the amazing wildlife animals.⠀
⠀
🐧 Singapore Zoo/Night Safari⠀
This package includes admission tickets to the Singapore Zoo or Night Safari with every booking. Whether you’re looking for a fun-filled day or a night full of adventures, you are definitely in for a ride with this package!⠀
⠀
🐼 Experience with Orangutans/Pandas⠀
Get up close and personal with the orangutans or giant pandas when you purchase this package. You’ll even be able to learn more about them through WRS’ expert zoo keepers and animal care team.⠀
⠀
🚐 Private Buggy Tour at Singapore Zoo/Jurong Bird Park⠀
Explore the Singapore Zoo or Jurong Bird Park with your very own private buggy and personal guide without having to sweat under the hot sun! You can even plan your own itinerary so you’ll be able to catch all the exhibitions and shows!⠀

Besides these exciting packages, look out for discounts off the hotel room rates! Check out the link in our bio for more information.⠀

Join us for the #SingapoRediscovers photography contest as we bring you some “hidden gems” across Singapore in collaboration with Singapore Tourism Board and @aikbengchia!

All you have to do is to check out our itinerary (link in bio), visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2 original shots captured in your own style. We’ve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well! These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts.

3 steps to take part in the contest:
1. Share with us what rediscovering Singapore means to you in the post caption
2. Follow @sgig and @stb_sg on Instagram
3, Hashtag #SGIGRediscovers #SingapoRediscovers.

You will stand a chance to win the following attractive prizes:

1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)

Consolation Prizes:
 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: 4 x #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
8th, 9th and 10th prizes: 3 x Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)

Of Murals and We-fies

The Gelam Gallery rejuvenates the back alleys of Kampong Gelam, where glamorous pictures are taken against the backdrop of paintings, bright and colourful. These murals bring new life to the historical site, engaging the new generation with the past. New memories of this place are created, tying generations of Singaporeans together.

While Kampong Gelam used to be the enclave for the Malay community in Singapore, and in the present where much of the district's flavour revolves around the Malay heritage still, places like the Gelam Gallery act as an avenue to attract the nation to visit Kampong Gelam and learn about its history and the Malay culture. By giving it a fresh paint of life, it ensures continuity in the knowledge of its history.

Warehouse
.
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Gai gai (街街) refers to going for a leisurely walk.. ⁣⁣
It’s a word we tell @dearbbkai everytime we bring him out.. As the things started to opening up slowly and almost back to normal, we took a courage to bring baby out weekly, capturing more moments because he grows up rapidly! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Happy to be able to witness his milestones as i still working from home for half of the week.. As you can see from IG stories now @dearbbkai able to rolls over, need to be extra cautious now.. ⁣⁣
Some of you asked me how me and hubby manage to take care newborn while working full time without any help.. We didn’t hire helper and our Moms are staying overseas, so we have no choice to take care baby on our own.. It’s not that hard to be honest, we both need to be very hands-on and have to get use do thing efficiently.. So if you are on the same situation like me, especially due to this pandemic you can’t get any help, don’t worry too much!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
📍Chijmes⁣⁣
CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and ‘MES’ was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.⁣
⁣⁣
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840–1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. (Source: Wikipedia)⁣⁣
⁣⁣

post_caption:
A few years back, from a small stall at a pop-up food village with his iconic Durian Creme Brûlée, that was my first encounter with Chef Deming. His love, passion and advocacy for local Singapore food can be seen, felt and tasted at The Quarters. Beyond and above, his forward-tasting and thinking in local Singapore cuisine started a new wave of modern Singapore (Mod-Sin) cuisine through a fusion of traditional and modern cuisine, in a communal dining known as The Quarters Experience. 

More than just preserving and holding on to our local Singapore food cuisine and culinary, Chef Deming belongs to a group of young food entrepreneurs leading the way to preserve, uphold and spread an important segment of our Singapore’s intangible cultural heritage and our love obsession with food. 

The time is now to start your own #SingapoRediscovers #sgfood journey! Visit @thequarterssg and rediscover a new world of Mod-Sin cuisine. 

#PortraitsofPurpose @dbsbank

I’ve been to South Beach couple of times in the past but only for dining. This time round after a night of exploration, I realized there is so much history and innovation behind the place - it really is an attraction on its own!

We chanced upon this corner and love how it captures the blend of heritage with modern architecture - the new building set against the old SAF NCO Club and the arched entrance of the old block 9. 

Singapore has been progressing at such a fast pace with our landscape always  changing with new developments, so all the more I appreciate the restoration work by South Beach to keep a part of our history alive. 

Hope by sharing what I see though my amateur eyes, you may be inspired to rediscover Singapore too 〰️

#HelloSouthBeachSG #SingaporeForEveryone

Good news! Many hotels are reopening, just in time for an end-of-year getaway 😍 Here are some unique staycation ideas that will make you forget that you are actually in Singapore.⁣
⁣
The Warehouse Hotel is known for its historic industrial character, transporting us back in time to experience the old-world glamour.⁣
⁣
Next, we have So Sofitel, housed in a neo-classical heritage building in the heart of the city. The hotel is a perfect blend of French elegance and local cultures, recommended for couples looking for a romantic stay! ⁣
⁣
Last but not least, if you are into nature and minimalistic interiors, be sure to check out Lloyd's Inn for a tranquil and immersive experience. It is located in Somerset, just a five-minute walk away from the Orchard Road shopping belt!⁣
⁣
Which fits your vibe best?⁣
⁣
1. 📷 @thewarehousehotel⁣
2. 📷 @sosofitelsingapore⁣
3. 📷 @lloydsinn⁣

POSITIVE STUFF 

There are only 24 hours in a day, 1440 minutes, 86,400 seconds. So how are you spending your day? Are you Working out, working on projects, spending time with family and focusing on the positive? Stay locked in and don’t waste your energy on negatives, and trust me, there is a lot of them out there!! 

Each of us have 86,400 seconds every day. DON'T let someone's negative 60 seconds ruin the remaining 86,340
-
📸 #ShotoniPhone 
🇸🇬 More photos of 📍Singapore #AdventureFaktoryInSingapore
🗺 Travel guides & inspiration ➡ @adventurefaktory

Travel photography is not just about shooting nice places or destinations or good food. 

It is about connecting viewers to the uniqueness of the place, it’s people, it’s culture and nature. 

It is a powerful tool to create awareness of cross cultural exchanges and many more that you can achieve through travel photography. 

It is beyond camera settings and filters.

Those are the fundamentals that I will share in my travel photography workshops and coach  potential photography participants who want to learn more on travel and documentary photography.

What is travel photography to you?

Before you sign up for any of my workshops, I encourage you to read, not just reviews on my workshops, but my works as a Travel and Documentary photographer to see whether my expertise and workshops match your requirements:

Shooting For A Change - 
https://singaporemagazine.sif.org.sg/shooting-for-a-change

My Life As A Travel & Documentary Photographer -

Before the Butterfly Block was constructed, early HDB residential blocks were largely designed as simple slab blocks and point blocks as the focus then was to build efficiently. With its unique curves and aesthetic façade, the Butterfly Block is an effort to create more variety and character in public housing estates through innovative designs.

Paul Fernandez (b. 1940) and his family moved into the Butterfly Block in 1975. He recalled, “There was a circular carriage way, Rumah Bomba (Malay: Fire House) Circus, at the end of the Butterfly Block where the itinerant hawkers would set up their food stalls. The firefighters from Alexandra Fire Station and the expatriates from Gillman Barracks would frequent the food stalls.”

post_caption:
Exploring the hidden gems of Chinatown and Little India

📍Chinatown
•Sago Lane / Street of the Dead - In earlier times, funeral parlours lined up this lane.
•People's Park - the "people's shopping centre", the complex is strategically located in one of the most populous areas in Singapore's Central Business District. Also nicknamed as "Streets in the Air"
•Jinrikisha Station - last reminder of the once ubiquitous rickshaw (and yes, it used to be a rickshaw terminal)

📍Little India
•Sri Veeramakaliamman Temple - one of the oldest Hindu Temple in Singapore (Gopuram/ front tower in photo) 
•Flower Stalls - every street corner of Little India has this
•House of Tan Teng Niah - the last surviving Chinese Villa in Little India
•Sajeev Photography Studio - Most clients are foreign workers whose portaits are sent to their parents back home, to look for their potential brides. (see all those film rolls? can you imagine the numerous love stories that were developed from those!)

Rediscovering Singapore is like getting to know her again for the first time..this time, she looks lovelier than ever as she unfolds stories that were almost forgotten.
.

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival  is one of the most important religious events for the Taoist community in South East Asia. 
 
On the first day of the festival, the devotees gather along the shores of East Coast Park to wait for the arrival of the palanquins and the temple entourage from Leong Nam Temple –for the commencement of the receiving ceremony (“请水仪式 qing shui yi shi” in Mandarin). 
 
The ceremony is initiated by a priest who calls upon the Nine Emperor Gods to bestow his presence while devotees pray fervently with a joss stick in their hands.  After the initiation and invitation ceremony, the palanquins carrying the holy artefact (usually an urn) containing the Nine Emperor Gods continue to sway vigorously while the carriers attempt to depart from the coast, and back to the temple. 

Note: Adapted from www.heritagefestival.gov.sg

post_caption:
A compilation of the beautiful house of Tan Teng Niah; 
Built in 1900, the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India. Tan Teng Niah was a towkay (Chinese businessman of good standing) Many believe that Tan built the house for his wife and that the inscription referred to her. The design of the house were beautifully crafted including the main door inscription made just for his wife. Note of the blossom flowers on the windows. The former house of Tan Teng Niah has eight rooms.

To the Chinese, the house design was auspiciously designed. Each doorway was beautifully decorated with carvings including the twirling wooden stairway of the golden dragons which impressed me most. The carvings were so detailed, precise and elegantly designed. Kudos to the 1900s skillful carpenters. 

The house was restored and conserved in the 1980s for commercial use, and the restoration project was awarded the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention in 1991. It is partially rented out Mr Chandran who had been there for more than 10years. He is a retired police officer whom set up this flower bussiness. I  was fortunate to have him sharing of his experiences and allowing me to take the beautiful interior of the villa.

⁣
Date: Monday, 19 October 2020⁣
Time: 10.30 - 12.00⁣
Instructor: Clara Simanjuntak⁣
Location: 727 North Bridge Road #02-01, Singapore 198695⁣
⁣
Course Fee: SGD35⁣
Price inclusive of tools and materials⁣
⁣
Indigo is one of the famous natural dye from plants in Asia. It is known as tarum in Indonesia and nila in Malaysia. In this workshop, participants will learn about indigo dye, as well as other natural dye sources, and to use indigo as dip dye in fashion items.⁣

Strolling among the planting of Tower Tree and Yellow Iris shrub, isn’t this feel resembling the walk through Paddy Field?!⁣
⁣
Isn’t it planning for staycation make us very excited for now?!⁣
Last time planning overseas trip that made us very excited but for now i guess staycation is the only “holiday” we can do.. ⁣
⁣
Hoping for a birthday staycation in December, which is only few months away, how time flies! Seriously i can’t wait for 2020 to be over 😅 and see what will happen in 2021.. ⁣
⁣
Anyway took this photo at Capella Hotel in Sentosa Island, one of my fav hotels in Singapore.. ⁣
⁣
Capella Singapore was built in the 1880s to accommodate the British officers of the Royal Artillery and their families. Capella Singapore is made up of both modern and colonial buildings. Among them are Tanah Merah I and Tanah Merah II, bungalows built in the 1880s to accommodate the British Officers of the Royal Artillery, Coastal Defence Command based on Sentosa Island. Known as the Officers' Mess, it was where the officers and their families ate and relaxed by dancing and playing tennis. ⁣
They were given conservation status on Aug 7, 2000.⁣
The hotel receives its guests at both bungalows, which have been restored. ⁣
⁣
Do you have your personal favourite hotel for staycation in Singapore?⁣

Fusion food holds a special place in our heart (and stomach), living in a multicultural city like Singapore. Here are some of our favourite contemporary fusion restaurants you might not have heard of!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Whitegrass is a fine dining restaurant showcasing classic French fare with a contemporary Japanese twist. Whitegrass focuses on using the freshest seasonal produce to create dishes that are thoughtful and respectful of nature. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Next, we have Restaurant Lerouy by the renowned Chef Christophe Lerouy. Tucked away on Stanley Street, Restaurant Lerouy offers a skilful blend of modern French cuisine with Asian ingredients. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The list wouldn’t be complete without Wild Rocket, with their signature Mod-Sin cuisine. This cooking style takes on a modern and innovative approach toward local dishes. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Interested in trying any of them?⁣⁣

Family Outing
Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

The Sembawang Hot Springs Park is a natural hot spring & a public park in Singapore. It is located beside a military camp about 100 metres (330 ft) off the main road, Gambas Avenue. Like hot springs worldwide, it can have health healing properties with proper use in moderation, & its natural spring water had once been bottled commercially by Fraser & Neave, under the brand name of Seletaris. Since its discovery in 1909, the spring has been through a few changes of ownership & potential redevelopment proposals. The hot spring has a rural rustic feel for visitors to unwind from the hustle & bustle of the modern metropolitan city. The National Parks Board took over the ownership of the park for redevelopment, which officially reopened on 4 January 2020. It's one of the two hot springs in Singapore with the other located on Pulau Tekong.

post_caption:
Take a walk around the estates of Adam Park and Alexandra Park, and be brought back to the Singapore of a different time. Admire the splendour of British colonial houses and their unique black and white characteristics, set within lush greenery, that paved way to an unrivalled architecture legacy in the region. You might just rediscover snippets of forgotten stories or surprise yourself with the history these houses hold and tell.⁠
⁠
You may even get the rare chance to visit a Black & White home, along with a private viewing of the owner’s collection of interesting antiques and curios over the years. Soak in the ambience, chat and socialise over tea and treats. 🍵⁠
⁠
Who would you like to take on your time travelling journey? 🚀 Share with us in the comments below.

Singapore is known for her diversity in cultures, ethnicities and religions. Due to the travel restrictions and the SingapoRediscover campaign, I have started to explore our neighbourhoods and the history behind these places.

Most locals would know about the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple in Chinatown. This Tang-styled temple is an architectural icon and I like how it contrasts against the modern city skyline in the background. 

Did you know that the street beside it has a sombre history and is known as the "Dead People Street"? Early Chinese immigrants, many of whom had no relatives, lived out their last days in the death houses here. 

Today, this area is a lively and vibrant place. Chinatown Complex is built over part of the street and many elderly folks can be seen playing chess or checkers at the communal spaces. 

Do you know about the history of your neighbourhood? How about taking this opportunity to Rediscover Singapore?

TEOWCHEW MOONCAKES?!
The only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. It’s just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill!
.
Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit a Teochew-style residential building. Uniquely different from other mooncakes, Teochew Mooncake is made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from Mitzo.
 
More features of mooncakes shot around Singapore at @stb_sg.

The colourful Alkaff Bridge at Robertson Quay in Singapore.

Built in 1997 in the shape of a  tongkang—a light boat that shipped goods along the river—this 55-metre- the long pedestrian bridge was named after a prominent family who lived in  Singapore in the early 20th century. In 2004,  Filipino artist Pacita Abad painted it with whimsical patterns using 55 colours. This artwork is also one of The artist’s final projects.

Shot on Nikon Z5 + NIKKOR Z 24-200mm f/4-6.3 VR lens. By @javan

Punggol Waterview View - Reflection of kelong inspired housing by Punggol Waterway

Waterview view is a distinctive HDB housing project that is inspired by the estate’s early beginning as a "kelong", or fishing village.  The blocks’ textured face mimics wood and their outdoor decks column resemble stilts of a kelong. At the same time it features  bioswales, bioretention ponds, and other water-sensitive urban design techniques with the waterway.   This housing project blends in beautifully with the waterway and features especially during the blue hour.

post_caption:
La kopi somewhere at Chinatown: “Sweetea Caffe 一杯夏日” at 15A & 15B Trengganu Street (2nd & 3rd floor of a conservation building at 15 Trengganu Street).
Just curious to go up to this heritage building to sit inside, chillax and admire the wall decor. High Tea with decent sweet and savoury food choices, there’s also main course food choices for lunch / dinner. Ordinary food for youngsters standard, please go without expectations. We are the most elderly patrons there, the rest are almost half of our age (or some younger than my Kopi Kaki’s child age) on a weekday afternoon, probably cos this place is so instagrammable, but I first saw this place online from TikTok 😆😄

[Wear proper shoes if going to check out this youngster cafe, the staircase of heritage building felt more steep when coming down.]

15 TRENGGANU STREET history:
Located at corner of Temple Street, at junction with Trengganu Street.
The three-storey building featured is the former Lai Chun Yuan opera theatre, believed to have been built in 1887, offering Cantonese opera performed by local, China and Hong Kong troupes.

The best thing about cable car rides at @sentosa_island has got to be the stunning views you get to see 💕 Throwback to last weekend's trip to Sentosa when we got the Mastercard 1-for-1 fun pass promo. Other than ten minute each on the Mega Bounce at Mega Adventure for the girls, the fun passes got our whole family on round trips on the Faber and Sentosa cable car lines.
.
The cable car ride is quite a novelty even for us adults and I must say we all so love the views on both lines (an empty Adventure Cove was a little sad to see tho 😔). The younger one was a bit nervous initially 😅 but at the end of the rides they were rather bummed that we couldn't go again.
.
Without the promo, I doubt we would have thought of going for cable car rides. But with the promo it came up to $40 for the four of us - pretty good deal if you ask me 😄
.
Weekend's coming! Have you made plans for it? 😊

Waiting for phase 3 like… 🙄😬🥵🤞🏼

It’s been a while that I posted on here, as the situation in Singapore hasn’t changed yet. We have been in phase 2 of Singapore’s reopening for almost 4 months now and everybody seems to wait for updates on the situation. Meanwhile, I took the time to explore Singapore a little bit more and I always made sure I have my camera with me to capture the best food places and weekend getaways in our little red dot. So stay tuned for more local guides on my blog. Happy weekend and stay tuned! 💚

Es ist schon eine Weile her, dass ich hier gepostet habe. Die Situation in Singapur hat sich in den letzten Monaten nicht geändert, obwohl zumindest Corona im Griff zu sein scheint. Aktuell warten wir alle auf ein Update zu Phase 3, die hoffentlich ein paar Lockerungen mit sich bringt. In der Zwischenzeit hatten wir mehr als genug Gelegenheiten, auch die letzte Ecke Singapurs zu erkunden. Und wir finden immer wieder neue interessante Nachbarschaften, ausgezeichnete Restaurants und interessante Spots. Selbstverständlich habe ich immer meine Kamera dabei und schreibe gerade fleißig an neuen Beiträgen für meinen Blog. Ihr dürft also gespannt sein ☺️ Bis dahin wünsche ich euch allen ein schönes Wochenende. ✨

Most don't think much of a simple Tutu Kueh - little steamed rice-flour cakes filled with single fillings such as peanut, coconut and occasionally chocolate, served over pieces of pandan leafs. As Singapore's hawker culture slowly declines, these little gems are nowadays hard to come by. You find them at traditional shops but rarely are they freshly prepared. 

As a part of Singapore's unique food culture and identity, shops such as Tan's Tutu Kueh are doing their best to keep the hawker culture alive. Known as the OG of Tutu kueh, the family business has been delighting locals with their freshly steamed kuehs since mid 1900s. 

Really enjoy their chocolate and coconut filled Tutu Kuehs and it has become ny go to place for good Tutu Kueh. Heck, I wouldn't even bother trying Tutu Kueh from any other places, they just don't come close. 

Hope that everyone gets to try their famous Tutu Kuehs! They have 2 outlets, located at Havelock Rd and Clementi. Note the timings are different so do check them out before heading down ☺️

Always expected these venerable creatures to break out into a flurry of martial arts moves ever since I saw Kungfu Panda.

So please remind me to NEVER, EVER prevent my kids from adopting a pet pooch, y'all!

【Ang Mo Kio #3 - Fried Rice】
Did you know that it was in the 1970s, that the Chinese name for Ang Mo Kio was changed to “宏茂桥“ which means "Bridge of Expansiveness and Prosperity”? Surely such an auspicious name bodes well for the hawkers in this neighbourhood!

China has the earliest record for fried rice from 1,500 years ago. Fried rice is believed to have originated from the Chinese practice of creating a meal with the leftover dishes (and rice) from the  previous meal. Our tradition of not wasting food created a whole new genre of Chinese cuisine.  Some of the usual ingredients for fried rice are rice, scallion, eggs and other small bits of meats & vegetables. 

In Singapore, we have the Chinese version which comes with side dishes like fried egg, hot dog sausage, pork cutlet, etc. Nasi Goreng is the Malay version of fried rice, usually  stir-fried with ikan bilis (anchovies) and tomato sauce. Perhaps because of all the different types of fried rice we get to taste in Singapore, we are known as the ‘Fried Rice Paradise’ ?

What kind of ingredients do you  include in your fried rice? Comment below and share with us. See you on Thursday and see where we dabao this delicious packet of fried rice full of ‘wok hei’. See ya!

post_caption:
Double Rainbow over The Pinnacle @ Duxton HDB. What a beautiful view of the city from my neighbourhood at HDB Kim Tian Green. In this neighbourhood, there are seven blocks of 40 storey tall HDB public housing flats. Every flats have different breathtaking view of the city, ports, towns and nearby islands too. Sometimes, we may get to see rainbow in the morning or in the late afternoon just after the rain. Whenever I saw one in the sky, I will inform my neighbours so that they will not miss seeing the beautiful colours of the rainbow. And I quickly grab my camera and tripod, take the lift up to the highest floor to capture this amazing double rainbows over the city.

HDB Kim Tian Green:

Kim Tian Green have Blk 126A, 126B, 126C, 127A, 127B, 127C & 127D at Kim Tian Road are 40 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. Kampong – a term to describe traditional villages or urban slum areas in towns and cities. 

In the early days, there used to be many kampongs scattered all over Singapore. However, with development and urbanization, these kampongs have been replaced with modern skyscrapers.

As an urban kid, kampong lifestyle is something that I find it hard to visualize and the only references I have of it are from my grandparents’ narration of their happy childhood days back in the kampong era.

Upon knowing that there is still the last kampong in Singapore (Kampong Lorong Buangkok), I jumped at the chance to explore it. It was a strange feeling walking through the kampong. Despite being surrounded by the all-so-familiar modern architectures and bustling roads, time seemed to come to a standstill here. Low-rise single-storey houses made of wood with zinc roofs instead of high-rise apartments; lush greeneries instead of dense man-made structures; a peaceful and quiet surrounding instead of the hustle and bustle of the city, this is indeed a whole new world to me!

I took my time to explore and admire the place, soaking up the atmosphere of this lovely location (and at the same time trying very hard to ignore the constant attacks from the bloodsucking mosquito..). This visit has definitely changed my impression of Singapore – there is more to Singapore than meets the eye!!

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! 🌕✨ #SeteMilKmEmSingapura ⠀
⠀
One of my favourite things about living in Singapore is celebrating cultural festivals that weren't on our radar before moving to Asia. Today we're celebrating the Mid-Autumn or Moon Festival, which has a history dating back 3000 years! ⠀
⠀
Traditionally it was a time to thank the gods at the end of the autumn harvest, and the festival is celebrated every year on the 15th day of the 8th lunar calendar month. This marks the day the Chinese believed the moon was at its brightest and fullest size, so we're spending the evening looking up to test this theory 😂⠀
⠀
Paper lanterns in every shape and size can be found decorating many spots in the city, and even though the festival was scaled back this year because of the pandemic, @gardensbythebay still went all out!🏮⠀
⠀
📸 Shot with the help of @blondiewanderlust ⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Feliz Festival da Lua! 🌕✨ Uma das coisas que mais amo morando aqui em Singapura é acompanhar os festivais que a gente não conhecia antes de se mudar pra Ásia. Hoje a China e países do Leste Asiático celebram o Festival do Meio do Outono, que tem uma história de mais de 3000 anos!⠀
⠀
Era a época de agradecer aos deuses pela abundância da colheita do outono e o festival acontece todo ano no 15º dia do 8º mês do calendário lunar. Esse é o dia em que os chineses acreditavam que a lua estava em sua forma maior e mais brilhante - por aqui vamos passar a noite olhando pro céu testando essa teoria 😂⠀
⠀
A cidade fica toda enfeitada com lanternas de papel super detalhadas em todos os tamanhos e formatos. Esse ano a programação do festival está reduzida por causa da pandemia, mas o Gardens by the Bay manteve a tradição e está ainda mais lindo! 🏮

Waking up here in a weekday ain’t that bad, especially when I get to edit photos all day - which can be really therapeutic! 

I know of people who absolutely abhor the process of photo editing but truly love the act of shooting. Over the years, I’ve gravitated to enjoying the former more.

These days, I carve out time on a Friday/weekend night to edit photos and this has become some sort of a meditative process for me after a tiring week at work. Beyond this, I typically select a playlist on YouTube/Spotify that I currently feel like zoning out to, make a cup of tea, get comfortable and let the magic happen.✨

Really admire Ms Tan Bee Hua, the current owner of Tan's Tutu Kueh. Have been her customer for years and often find myself heading down to her shop just to satisfy my Tutu Kueh cravings. My family is also a fan and Tan's Tutu Kueh is the only place we head to for authentic, pillowy Tutu Kuehs. 

In frame: Ms Tan sieving the rice flour to make it as fine as possible. Running a Tutu Kueh shop alone is tough and labour intensive! You will find Ms Tan at both outlets (Havelock Rd in the early afternoons and then she proceeds to the Clementi outlet at night). Materials have to be prepared in the morning, such as cooking the coconut in gula Melaka and preparing of peanut fillings. All these are very time consuming so I am amazed at how dedicated Ms Tan is. Plus, she mans the shops on her own so you would imagine how many Tutu Kuehs she makes a day, all by hand! 

Really hope that the culture will live on for many more years to come. Glad that nowadays with social media, younger people gaining interest for the hawker culture and local foods. Perhaps in the future, our Singaporean delicacies will be well loved worldwide.

#Didyouknow International Plaza was one of the pioneers Singapore in the 1970s of integrating multiple operations into a single mixed-use development? Before the work-live-play concept was trending, International Plaza was a forerunner,  integrating apartments, sports facilities, offices and a retail mall in a single building, epitomising the concept of living and working in the financial hub of the city.

Understanding the past, a window to the future is what this #DiscoverTanjongPagar BID programme is about. With the rejuvenation of the precinct through the BID programme, we need to join hands to further the transformation of Tanjong Pagar through synergised efforts.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

post_caption:
Own the moment with a sweet #suite escape! 😘 

Look forward to a charming Escape For Two with our exclusive package, bit.ly/WSG_Offer_ForTwo

While my wife had lunch with her friend, I took a chance to try something I've only heard about, Salted and Hung. I went for the "Feed Me" dégustation menu to have an understanding of Salted and Hung's repertoire. Set aside just under S$200, and be prepared for a culinary ride through Australia, with a dash of Southeast Asia familiarities. 

The range felt playful to me, especially how the very opening bite was an Ebi Panna Cotta... Who the heck starts with dessert? So what's familiar is turned upside down, with this dessert being savoury to the palate. The IPA Sourdough was divine, esp when paired with whipped lard WITH a generous drop of chili oil (you have to try to understand how it plays with you mind!). The other butter was seaweed based, and it was yummy, giving the crunchy bread flavours of the sea. 

Chef Drew and his professional crew did everything so intently, you sense the purpose of the ingredients coming together. More often than not, contemporay fusion food can be a turn off when it's in the chef's mind, but the execution just doesn't mindmeld it to the diner. These guys just did a Spock on me, and I'm pretty damn sure you'll get it too once you give it a go! 🧐

 ⁣

Join us to experience a printmaking session where you will be introduced to the basics of linocut carving and printing techniques. 5 Quick Facts About the SingaporeRediscovers Vouchers

After the year we’ve had, Christmas can’t come soon enough. Come December, all Singaporeans aged 18 and above will get $100 in digital vouchers for staycations, leisure attractions, and local tours. Totalling over $320million, the government first announced the SingapoRediscovers Vouchers schemes last month in the hopes of re-energising Singapore’s battered tourism sector. But what can you do with the vouchers? And how do you get them? Read on as Tropika Club lays out everything you need to know about the SingapoRediscovers Vouchers.

Find out more at https://magazine.tropika.club/5-facts-singaporerediscovers-vouchers/

post_caption:
Sago Street

Did you know the street received its name because there were numerous sago factories in that area during the 1840s. In the late 19th century, this area became well known for its number of prostitute dens.

Fast forward to the more recent history, this street were occupied by mostly wet and dry markets as well as hawkers. Currently this street is known mainly as a tourist attraction that sell a range of souvenirs and street food, also for the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple which is located along the street.

I did enjoy rediscovering Singapore and finding these hidden photography spots while also trying out street photography which I must admit that I’m totally bad at it.
.
.
.

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! 🏮🏮⁣
Time to eat mooncakes 🥮🥮🥮⁣
⁣
Every mooncake festival remind me of my late father, he always bought me mooncakes and celebrating this Chinese culture. The mooncakes he bought not as fancy as the mooncakes nowadays but it made my heart full! And when he no longer with us, my family didn’t really celebrate this festival anymore.. only when i moved to Singapore then i am immersed in this yearly celebration again.. The yummy mooncakes are very hard to resist, isn’t it?!⁣
⁣
Just want to show the beauty of art installation at Gardens by The Bay.. The Apricot Grove, which features apricot flowers at various stages of blooming, enhanced with gobo lighting effect to simulate falling flower petals, is inspired by the Chinese fable of Dong Feng “董奉”, who is a skilled and generous medical practitioner from the Three Kingdoms period ”三国时代”.⁣
⁣
This installation happening from 18 Sep 2020 - 4 Oct 2020, Lantern sets will be lighted up at the outdoor gardens from 7.00pm to 10.00pm and the Admission is free!⁣
⁣
It’s always crowded here and as usual do photoshop magic to make the picture “cleaner”. When i was there i was so tempted to remove my mask when taking photo, but i saw warning signs to keep mask on are everywhere and i wasn’t dare to take the risk, anyway it’s for my own safety and other people safety too!⁣
⁣

Culture and Fashion

It's difficult to not notice women dressed in Kurtis -- the most widely worn women traditional attire in India -- while strolling in Little India. As seen here, they come bright in colours and with floral designs. It brings out elegance and is stylish even in today's times. It's a no wonder that even young Indian ladies would wear them out on the streets today.

1. Elderly lady and her companion outside Tekka Centre.
2. Two ladies exiting from a shophouse onto Campbell Lane.
3. A lady waving for a taxi along Serangoon Road adjacent to Buffalo Road.

On this 🇸🇬 #NationalDay

1) went to explore a part of SG that used to only have a 10m or so back alley of Haji Lane, now with more street art to boost its vibrant funkyness

Nice to see art incorporated among air-con compressors, electrical boxes, motorcycles and flying wild pigeons 

2) noticed an unprecedented number of people wearing red and masks with SG logos on it, somehow can really feel the pride of those wearers this year ✨

3) Also visited an ex-colleague friend from 🇵🇭 who's gonna give birth and has to leave SG.

Grateful to have worked at a backpacker hostel before the pandemic, getting to know hardworking Filipinos, the challenges they face and who contribute a lot to SG economy, as well as many Nigerian guests who may intimidate people with their body-build, but are generally polite well mannered with sense of humour

[Chinatown Precinct] - “Potato Head”

Rediscovering is about appreciate the historic value of a place and the finding the best time to shoot it. 

When rediscovering Chinatown, the pre-war shophouses at the junction of Keong Saik Road and Teck Lim Road ( dated 1939) should not be missed.  This place has a colorful and rowdy past until 1980. It  is now occupied by the restaurant-bar Potato Head and now nicknamed as Potato Head. I love the heritage chic and vibe of this area at night. As a photographer, I find it most beautiful in the bluehour of the early morning. This photo was taken during blue hour and just before a heavy rain( which explains the lens flare from the rain drops)

*Taken during the stipulated period. It is challenging during a rainy period. Hope that I made  best of situation.

Every time I think I have experienced the pinnacle of @lesamisrestaurant’s cheese trolley experience, I am so happy to be proven wrong. Like on my most recent visit when Resident Cheese Master @manoj_sharmahm brought out these beautiful bottles of Le Château d’Estoublon olive oils. As explained by him, each has its own unique characteristics and can enhance the taste of different cheeses when savoured together. We went to town with that in mind - matching the cheeses he plated up for us according to his recommendations, before venturing on to experiment a little on our own with different combinations. Suffice to say, we found the “Fromage” course exceptionally fun, enriching and very, very delicious.
If you love #cheese, the #cheesetrolley is something to look forward to when you dine at Three MICHELIN Starred Les Amis.

《Exploring Singapore》

Art doesn’t have to be found on the walls of a gallery. While Singapore certainly has its share of world-class museums, exhibitions and art spaces, it’s also home to a wealth of street art and iconic wall murals.

Go on a hunt through Singapore’s diverse neighbourhoods—from the South Asian enclave of Little India to the lively streets of Chinatown—and discover art that will both inspire and expand your artistic sensibilities.

The National Museum of Singapore is our all-time favourite spot for bringing the kids to learn about Singapore’s history and hear inspiring stories.

 

Did you know that it is the nation's oldest museum?

 

The kids got to learn about Singapore’s journey to becoming a modern city. Amazing to see how this city has evolved over the years!

 

Take a look at all the spots we rediscovered over at @stb_sg and also share your own content with #SingapoRediscovers

#PassionMadePossible #Mums_Babies #sgmums #familytime #singaporetourism

Tanjong Rhu Suspension Bridge is 
Singapore's first suspension footbridge built in 1998. The bridge spans the Geylang River, allowing residents of Tanjong Rhu to cross over to the Singapore Sports Hub.

Definitely the next Instagram-worthy place to be at.

#ibisbudgetsgexplorer #ibisbudgetsg #geylangriver #tanjongrhubridge #exploresg #singaporediscovers #passionmadepossible #exploringsingapore

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

7-8 years ago (I think), I came here alone and explored this north part of #singapore with a deep history of #colonial past. Things have remained pretty much the same - there has been no upgrade or redevelopment to this area in #seletar which used to house British military staff. Nonetheless,  the bungalows are one of a kind with double chimneys and even with maid chambers. They are probably beautiful and glorious in the olden days, and though old and derelict and abandoned now, they look as beautiful amidst nature looking to take over the houses. Given their long abandoned state, there is also something eerie about the windows, I can imagine pairs of eyes looking out! Hahaha . I wouldn't dare to explore the insides of the houses, despite my curiosity.  Some of the houses (those with glass panels and are refurbished) are now for commercial use. Within the surroundings, there are also many interesting streets with #british #streetnames such as Hyde Park (the last time I visited, it was barricaded for redevelopment) and Oxford Street, a huge reminder of our colonial past. For now, I can also make pretend that I am travelling in the UK 😁🤣 oh ya, check out the super unique tree in the first picture! Have never seen anything quite like it!

[Little India Precinct] - The Flower Guys of Little India

This is dedicated to the friendly and 
handsome flower garland selling guys of Little India.

Rediscovery is about relooking and presenting the beauty of people in their environment

I am always attracted to the stalls selling colorful flower garlands. Those flower garlands are used for religious purposes during those festivals. Often, those guys are so friendly and always open for a nice photo and chitchat. As I rediscover, I see the beautiful people ( those eyes.. ) and color flower. Cannot help but to capture them in my photos.

*Taken during the stipulated period .Hope that this project to re-discover Singapore can spark the interest of Singaporean exploring more of Singapore.

When my Mom came from overseas exploring Singapore, i brought her to visit landmarks such as Esplanade and Merlion Park.. ⁣
⁣
I told the taxi uncle to send us to Esplanade, but he didn’t seem to understand then we described it as “building with thorns” then he said “oh the Durian! OK! Let’s go!”⁣
Lol, so locals have dubbed it "the Durian", as the venue’s twin structures resemble the spiky tropical fruit.⁣
⁣
Durian is famous fruit here in Singapore.. Talking about this seasonal fruit, i hated it back then due to its pungent smell, however just few months ago during the season, my hubby brought home some durian and i can eat it! Since i become a mother, i feel that somehow i could accept and not too fussy on certain things lately.. ⁣
⁣
Anyway, “the Durian” always remind me of my mom, due to Covid, i am not so sure when i could see her again.. 😭⁣
.. ⁣
⁣
•⁣

Who's planning to visit Jewel this Sep holiday? 😄 Throwback to our last two weekends when we visited Jewel and it was still relatively quiet. Space for Interaction

Beyond the exterior façade of being a vibrant place for Singaporeans and tourists to visit, Kampong Gelam is first and foremost a community. Even today, while its early days residents have left, Kampong Gelam continues to instill its energy and vibrance into its visitors, connecting people.

Friends and family, young and old, may find a space in this community that they may relate. This, in particular, can be observed if one were to walk along Haji Lane where friends gather in bars and engage in merrymaking day and night, capturing and creating memories against the colourful shophouses. Not to forget, the relationships forged between the shophouse owners, employers and employees over time. Strangers arrive at Haji Lane and may leave as friends. It's a place to feel alive, to be alive!

Outing with @meixinmacy

The 27 metres long kiln is fired up with wood, creating rivers of fire that engulf the pots in it. The melting ashes then deposit themselves on the pots and reacts with their glazes. This process results in precious one-of-a-kind wares, where each has unique flushes of scorch marks depending of its position in the kiln.

At Thow Kwang, the dragon kiln is fired two to three times a year.

Tour By Hong Thai Travel

Book your staycation at The Fullerton Hotel Singapore, Singapore’s 71st national monument. A central part of Singapore’s history, the landmark building houses the five-star luxury hotel amid the heritage district. Boasting views of Marina Bay and the Singapore River, the neoclassical-style of this heritage hotel extends a stately elegance from the foyer to the poolside, to restaurants, and to each unique room.

Begin your experience of The Fullerton Hotel Singapore’s excellent service and rich history from just $266++, including breakfast and late check-out. Upgrade to a Straits Club Heritage Room, a special room reflecting the historical nature of the hotel, and enjoy exclusive access to The Straits Club, including personalised service and complementary Chandon breakfast, afternoon tea, cocktails and canapes. Or enhance your stay with a spa treatment at the top-class The Fullerton Spa for just $99++ to complete your Fullerton experience.

⁣

Soon after the morning rain, rainbow appears over Jalan Bukit Merah.

HDB Kim Tian 119:

Block 119B, 119C & 119D at Kim Tian Road are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 200 units with 128 units of 4-room unit type and 72 units of 5-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

HDB Membina 118:

Membina 118 have Block 118A, 118B, 118C & 118D at Jalan Membina are 30 storey HDB public housing flats in Bukit Merah, District 03, Singapore. It has a total of 172 units with 172 units of 4-room unit type in every block. These flats were completed in 2001 and has a 80 years lease remaining.

“We are going to be served Hashbrown.” Yes, you heard me right, Chef Bjorn Shen has created, what could possibly, be one of the best hashbrowns that you have ever tasted. New on the menu and to take a dig at the Golden Arches, this version of Homemade Hashbrown ($14) is made from peeled Russet potatoes that have been steamed, grated and seasoned with corn flour and salt before getting a tan in the oven for an hour. If you thought that’s the end, it’s certainly not as the potato is then fried and topped with sour cream and fresh za’atar. This might seem like any other hashbrowns that you can get elsewhere but #nothingistooimproper when it comes to Artichoke. The crispy outer shell is just the first layer of amazingness before you reach deeper in to get the warm and starchy potato. The sour cream gives it an uplifting zing that awakens your palate while the spices accentuate the flavour and aroma.
_________________
Artichoke Singapore
Address: 161, Middle Road, Singapore 188978
_________________

If you a fan of traditional kopitiam that has not only traditionally brewed authentic coffee aroma but also an old uncle complete in his iconic blue-strip pyjamas, then this time-stood-still coffee shop is for you.  Toasted bread are done over charcoal fire and coffee are done pouring in and out of the brownish-stained coffee bag.  There is even a good olden day timber counter that is no longer used by a cashier, but are stack with traditional biscuits and cookies kept in containers that appear to be used since day one.  If Singapore is serious about preserving its food culture, then this shop has to be gazetted for its intangible cultural heritage that dated back to the 60s and 70s
