post_caption:
We always work for a better tomorrow. But when tomorrow comes, instead of enjoying, we again think of a better tomorrow. Let’s have a better today.

What a view of Clementi❤️
13 Oct 2020
Clementi is named after Sir Cecil Clementi Smith, the Governor of the Straits Settlement from 1887 to 1893. Part of Clementi used to be swamp land. The other part was made up of kampungs and villages with squatter-type homes, backyard trades, cottage industries, and farms.

As one of the earliest HDB towns, Clementi’s development took place in the 1970s with plans for the town to be self-sufficient and support an adequate range of facilities and services with job opportunities to meet various social and economic needs.

Clementi has grown from its humble beginnings into a vibrant and popular estate. The town is also known for the many tertiary educational institutions located there, including Ngee Ann Polytechnic, Singapore Polytechnic, and the National University of Singapore.

Singapore Tourism Board (@stb_sg) and Visa have signed a three-year MoU to buoy up tourism and lifestyle SMEs that have been impacted by Covid-19. The collaboration focuses on two areas to revive the local tourism industry: marketing partnerships, as well as joint research and analytics.

In the first phase of their marketing partnership, which will be launched in October 2020, both organisations will tap on their respective campaigns – #SingapoRediscovers and #WhereYouShopMatters – to encourage Singaporeans to shop from local retailers and support the domestic economy.

In the past, I didn’t really thought much when walking past Sago Lane. Did you know during the early 20th century, this lane is famous for its Chinese death houses? 

People in the past were superstitious and believed dying in their own home is considered inauspicious which is why many paid to live their last moments in these houses. 

These houses were banned subsequently in the 1960s. The Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, you see today along Sago Lane was only recently built in the 2000s.

Rediscovering Singapore also brings me back to the area along Sago street, where uncles gather around for a game of chess even during this difficult times (Of course with masks on and social distancing). One of my favourite hobby in the past was to have a game of Chinese chess. It kind of brought me back to the past just by watching them engaging in their mind games. I ended up spending 30 minutes of my time watching that exciting game of chess.

Hardly in our busy work lives, we get to take a walk down these cultural places and enjoy the modern construction as well as the forgotten meaning of these places. Since we couldn’t travel for the time being, why not join me to rediscover Singapore?
.
.
.

Delve into the Peranakan culture of yesteryear. 

Colourful two-storey houses with ornate facades, intricate motifs and ceramic tiles, these houses can be commonly found in the eastern Joo Chiat and Katong area. Some have been converted to stores or museums, and even rentals like @figment.live where you get to experience the old wonders.

Did you know other than Katong, these houses can be found in other areas of Singapore?

Five international dance troupes will be celebrating this Mid-Autumn Festival "together" by putting up an online Chinese dance performance on 30 September 2020 (Eve of the Mid-Autumn Festival).

Do join us at our respective Facebook page on 30 September 2020 at SGT 8pm (GMT +8) to watch the “live” stream. Don’t miss it!

I missed Kampong.

SingapoRediscovers:  Exploring Kampong Lorong Buangkok

Kampong Lorong Buangkok is a village located in Buangkok in Hougang, Singapore. Built in 1956, it is the last surviving kampong located on Singapore Island.

Decide to do a local tour there and I met with some very friendly folks there and one even invited me to their home for a chat.

The kampong village retains the rustic beauty and it reminded me of my kampong childhood, living in my grandfather's house in Chua Chu Kang.

The kids here run freely and the  folks here are always obliging for a chat and phototaking, which is true in the kampong spirit.

You can see herbs, mango trees and even coca plant.

Along the way, we met some visitors who brought their kids to learn more about our traditional kampong heritage.

This is certainly an enjoyable  trip and would suggests everyone to experience kampong lifestyle.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷千秋
九月初🗓🙏🙏🙏

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

There’s never a bad time to enjoy hotpot! And if you’re a fan of Beauty In The Pot (like us! 😋), chances are, you’ve probably eaten the seafood from this family’s business before. 

As self-professed seafood lovers, Hong Seafood supplies their frozen products to popular restaurant chains like Paradise Group and hotels from Shangri-La to Ritz Carlton. 

This humble family business started from only selling prawns, to now supplying a wide array of seafood to both local and international establishments. But when borders closed and dine-ins at local eateries stopped amid the COVID-19 outbreak, they found themselves facing their biggest challenge in 34 years of operations.

Hear how they managed to rise above the odds at 6:30pm tomorrow — on all of our platforms!

“When the Circuit Breaker started, it was like a ghost town. It’s heartbreaking, especially for my mother, who is known to be a chatterbox.”

Tucked in the corner of Little India, @rasoolshop_sg has been selling special spice mixes blended from their family’s secret recipes for over 60 years — even before Singapore achieved independence! They are so popular that their customers come from all over the world, even famous ones (who can’t be named 😉).

But for the first time in all their years of operations, Shah and his mother — the folks behind Rasool Shop — found themselves stuck in a predicament. Business was poor, and customer footfall was low amid COVID-19.

Luckily, they managed to find new ways of reconnecting with old customers and new friends by bringing their shop online. Now, anyone can easily purchase Rasool’s spices with just one click!

Look out for Rasool’s story tomorrow at 6:30pm!

Science, milk and low-waste! Take a closer look into what goes behind the making of our #consciouscocktail Got Milk?⁣
⁣
Milk is first put through a clarification process to preserve it. A delicious 3-layer pudding garnish is then put together with repurposed ingredients.⁣
⁣
First layer: curds that are leftover from our milk clarification⁣
Second layer: pumpkin remains from the infusion of pandan, bourbon and rum⁣
Third layer: Gula Melaka, a nod to our Asian roots.⁣
⁣⁣

The announcement of the winners of the Design For Deities competition will be delayed by a couple of weeks. Our day jobs have been keeping us busy... our apologies! 

In the meantime, here's sharing another shortlisted entry. 

This is from product designer Jason Fok, originally from Mauritius, now based in Singapore. (www.fokchiseng.com)

In his design, the Monkey God is posable and made of simple geometric shapes. Unlike the traditional effigies, his design uses colour sparingly. The traditional motifs of dragons and armour is reinterpreted with elegance - peach-shaped armour plates and whimsical clouds on the base. The movable parts encourage you to tinker with it constantly, a departure from the reverence and distance that traditional effigies exert on worshippers. 

A few hundred people have voted in the competition so far. Pls join them to support our amazing designers by voting via the link in bio!

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

Who else starts the week already thinking about the next weekend? 🙋‍♀️😂 I think we'll spend a day in Pulau Ubin as Nic couldn't make it last time, I can't wait to show him around the island! #SeteMilKmEmSingapura⠀
⠀
Pulau Ubin is one of the 64 islands/islets that make up Singapore and a welcome tropical getaway if you want to escape the city for a day. The once bustling island used to be explored for its granite - Pulau Ubin actually means "Granite Island" in Malay - but nowadays the abandoned quarries have turned into lakes and less than 50 people live there.⠀
⠀
Hiking, biking, swimming, kayaking (and of course taking pictures 😂), Pulau Ubin has lots to offer just a 10 minute boat ride away. There are also bike rentals, little shops and restaurants owned by the locals - probably the last witnesses of the Singaporean way of life prior to the country's fast modernisation.⠀
⠀
📸 Shot with the help of my hiking buddy @blondiewanderlust ⠀
⠀
⠀
🇧🇷 Quem também começa a segunda já planejando o final de semana? 🙋‍♀️😂 Acho que vamos passar um dia em Pulau Ubin já que Nic não pôde ir quando eu fui, quero tanto mostrar a ilha pra ele!⠀
⠀
Pulau Ubin é uma das 64 ilhas/ilhotas que formam Singapura e uma ótima pedida pra quem quer fugir da cidade por um tempinho. A ilha era explorada pelo seu granito - por isso o nome Pulau Ubin, "Ilha de Granito" em malaio! - mas hoje em dia as antigas pedreiras se transformaram em lagos e menos de 50 pessoas moram na ilha.⠀
⠀
Trilha, ciclismo, passeio de caiaque (e claro, tirar muitas fotos 😂), Pulau Ubin tem muito a oferecer a apenas 10 minutinhos de barco da ilha principal. Também tem onde alugar bicicleta, lojinhas e restaurantes administrados pelos locais - provavelmente os últimos guardiões do antigo estilo de vida comum antes da modernização de Singapura.

Central Fire Station
⁠
The Central Fire Station (CFS), also known as the Hill Street Fire Station, is Singapore’s oldest surviving fire station. Completed in 1909, the distinctive red-and-white brick building was gazetted as a national monument by the Preservation of Monuments Board in recognition of its significance in Singapore’s history. The Singapore Civil Defence force subsequently embarked on conservation and reconstruction work, including building the Heritage Gallery to commemorate the contributions and rich history of the local fire service and its firemen. The gallery is located in the oldest part of the station, and features photographs of major fires, old firefighting equipment and uniforms, interactive displays, and audio-visual presentations to engage the public. Its highlights include a 19th-century fire engine, and the 30-metre lookout tower that visitors can climb up.⁠
.⁠
Source: eresources.nlb.gov.sg⁠

Few weeks ago I followed @andy1um, @izmyphotos, @victorl0 and @photographyholic to the peranakan houses in Joo Chiat. It was a bright day... why these people love to roast me under the over-excited sun during a photowalk ah? 😅

Not sure if you notice; because of the fengshui, peranakan houses are designed symmetrically with entrance located in the centre flanked by windows on the both sides. It’s also common to have Chinese inscribed signboard hung above the main door as well as ventilation openings carved in wood with symbolic decorations.

On Koon Seng Rd, Joo Chiat, you can find the bat-shaped ventilations which actually symbolize Good Luck. Here is something I’m very sure you didn’t notice until now; swipe to see a close-up, spot the bat-shaped ventilations and compare it with the logo of @stb_sg 😉

SingapoRediscovers 3 Oct 2020

It's saturday fever.  Nobody in the street in early morning.  A rare and quiet scene around Chinatown. A contrast between the used to be buzzling town filled with festive moods and lifestyle comparing to the diminishing kampong village where I grew up from.

Ironically, this Sago street used to be death houses and today a temple is built here.

Covid-19 may have slowed down our lifestyle, our economy and taking away many lives.  While what were lost, there are always new opportunities, new beginnings and new discovery.

To me, Singapore rediscovers is to revisit some of my growing up fond memories places and/or find new created memories and values through every visits.

Walking down the memory street, checking out what we have been missing during those vibrant good days, refresh our childhood memories, spending more time with family, revisit Singapore and it's diverse culture and foods.  Without covid-19, we may be complacent, and always think that the other part of the pasture are greener.  It is this covid-19 that set our mindset to another new level of critical thinking, to unlearn, learn and relearn. To appreciate and be thankful that we are borned in Singapore, with the great contribution from our fore fathers especially from our founding father Mr Lee Kuan Yew.

Will Singapore continue to be a vibrant first world country? It's a test on #SGUnited.

post_caption:
Delightful chaos and beautiful disarray. That is usually the state of the studio after a full day of workshops.
.
TBH, preparing for and cleaning up after classes take up a lot of time and frankly aren't much fun at all. And these are just some of many invisible behind-the-scenes things we do to create the art experience we want to deliver for every single guest who visit the studio. 
.
But the hard work all pays off when we see the galore of works that our workshop participants create after every session. Each piece different and always inspiring in one way or another. And if even when only one person leaves the studio having a renewed perspective towards art, we do a little dance in our heart.💃
.
So when you're feeling tired like we do today, take a moment to look for that delight in chaos and beauty in disarray, and then find new strength to keep going. For us, we wake up grateful every day to be able to call this our career, our passion and our mission 👩🏻‍🎨 Here's to another brand new day. Fighting!
.
#gratitude🙏 #artforthesoul #whywedowhatwedo

When one makes their way to Fort Canning, one can hardly miss this huge lawn in front of the Fort Canning Centre. 

This was the lush lawn I had previously mentioned in my earlier post that used to be a Christian Cemetery. 

Here's a short history of this place:

"Developed in 1822 by George Coleman – Singapore’s first architect and Stamford Raffles’ consultant on the first Town Plan – the Fort Canning Christian cemetery had approximately 600 graves interred. 

The cemetery was eventually closed in 1865, and the state of the burial grounds began to deteriorate. In 1953, the City Council exhumed the cemetery and created a “Garden of Memory”."

For this weekend, we decided to visit Canopy Park at @jewelchangiairport and the Walking Net inside the park! We had always wanted to visit #CanopyPark but had been putting it off thinking that it would be rather crowded since it was fairly new and the prices to the attractions inside are really quite steep. Well, now till end August there's a 55% off for the attractions at Canopy Park and that finally got us there 😆
.
Some of the attraction tickets, including our Walking Net tics, include Canopy Park entrance fees and essentially we paid slightly over $20 for our family of four. I had thought my girls would be fine with the Walking Net given that they were fearless at Airzone (the net playgound at City Square Mall), but they were rather spooked by the height (you can see all the way down to the mall) and they said a lot harder to walk on compared to Airzone. I quite agree with them; we were all drenched in sweat by the time we made our way to the end of the net. But that said, we got the hang of it - the trick is to side step - and soon we all found the net to be quite enjoyable to walk around and sit on 😆
.
It wasn't very crowded when we were there on Saturday morning - only a little crowded with children at the Foggy Bowls. We were expecting more people given that Jewel just started a promo where you can redeem Canopy Park entry for 2 pax with one receipt of any amount spent at Jewel (1st 500 redemptions). The girls had a field day at the Discovery Slides (only 2 slides out of 4 operating btw) and they didn't even have to queue despite a capacity limit of 5 at any one time at Discovery Slides.
.
We're thinking of the Bouncing Nets (bookings for these seem to have sold out fast!) and Canopy Bridge next. Anyone know if these two attractions are good? 😊
.

This building along #ToaPayoh Lorong Two is the headquarters of Singapore Federation of Chinese Clan Associations (SFCCA) since 1997. 

Prior to that, this premises used to belong to Heng A Khe Bong #School, a primary school that started in 1973 but traced its roots to two separate institutions - Heng A School (founded in 1918) and Khe Bong School (in 1920).

The two schools came together and stayed together before it closed down in 1993.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

There are dinosaurs in Singapore!! 🦖
But as you can see, don’t worry they won’t eat you if you get too close🙅🏻‍♂️
The new Jurassic Mile trail in Changi has nine different types of dinosaurs on display. They include a fierce T-rex trying to break out of its cage, a Brontosaurus dipping its long neck into a pond for a drink, and mischievous baby Pterodactyls stealing golf balls from the nearby course ⛳️🏌🏻‍♂️
Entry is free for all cyclists and joggers (or walkers, like me, haha). I for some reason thought it a good idea to walk from East Coast Park to the Jurassic Mile, and then onward to Jewel Changi. I can’t feel my legs now😂😂

Puddle Reflection
HDB Central Horizon

At HDB, the development of Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme (SERS) replacement projects to high standards of quality, design, and environmental innovation. As a result, many SERS replacement projects have won prestigious awards and accolades. These is just one of the examples.

The Development:

Block 79 Toa Payoh Central used to be a single 10-storey block. Today, the site is home to Central Horizon, a distinctive Toa Payoh landmark offering scenic panoramas of central Singapore.

HDB Central Horizon is made up of 5 towering 40-storey blocks, with a total of 1,158 units of 4-and 5-room flats.

The Honours:

• HDB Design Excellence Award 2008 (Housing Category)

• BCA Universal Design Award for Build Environment 2009 (Residential Building Category)

• SIA-NParks Skyrise Greenery Award 2009

Hike in the city at Fort Canning.

Since we’re encouraged to be local tourists, we decided on a hike at Fort Canning Park. 💡Here’s a tip for parents, print the map 🗺 from NParks and make your kids the “tour guide”, with Jubilee Park as the last stop so they’ll press on for the PLAY incentive!
 
There are nine historical gardens and we explored half of them yesterday. We started at The Foothills after lunch at Clarke Quay and made our way up the Raffles Garden where we were greeted by the Fort Canning Lighthouse on top of Fort Canning Hill. Next was the Instagram worthy Sang Nila Utama Garden 🌺with Javanese split gates, recreated to resemble the 14th century royal palace gardens. We spent some time at the Artisan’s Garden which featured an archaeological dig exhibition site along with displayed artefacts that were unearthed since the 1980s. We didn’t manage to cover all 9 gardens and it’s a pity The BattleBox tour is now closed due to COVID-19 but I’m sure we’ll be back again.

To conclude our day of adventure- play time at Jubilee Park which is across Liang Court. The climbing nets and long slide are now closed but thankfully the swings, see-saw, log scramble and slides at the toddler area kept the young and young at heart very happy! 

Fort Canning is easily accessible by train from Fort Canning and Clarke Quay MRT stations. Don’t forget to put on comfortable walking shoes, slap on sunscreen, mosquito repellant and go armed with a sense of adventure where you’ll definitely be rewarded for a journey back in time experience!

NATURALBOOM brings you to places.

Where have you visited in Chinatown recently? Share with us your favourite snaps!

We finally explored a beautiful oasis so close to our home here in Singapore: the Sembawang Hot Springs. We rode our bikes and found great bike park facilities, restrooms and surprisingly a cafe that rents & sells buckets for the hot springs. The pools are nestled in regenerated natural bush and the only sign of the busy neighbourhood is the occasional helicopter overhead.  The surprise and delight of the ‘egg cooking’ station was surpassed by our genuine surprise at how hot the water is in the foot bath spring pool. We’ll definitely be back (with a bucket).

Happy 1st Birthday, Jewel @ Changj Airport
.
Officially opened on October 18th, 2019. Jewel receives about 300,000 visitors a day. In October 2019, six months after its soft opening, it had already welcomed 50 million visitors, exceeding its initial target for the whole of the first year. 
In November 2019, Jewel Changi Airport was awarded the Special Jury Award at the year's Mapic Awards, which recognises excellence, innovation and creativity in the global retail real estate industry. Jewel Changi Airport had initially submitted entries in two categories - Best Leisure Concept and Best Shopping Mall - but the panel, comprising top retail real estate experts, gave it the Special Jury Award, which goes to the jury's favourite project among all the entries.

The Changi Jurassic Mile
Changi Airport Connector
Airport Boulevard
Singapore

22 "life-sized" dinosaur models along the Changi Airport Connector, a new 3.5km path that links the airport to East Coast Park.

The cycling and walking path, which starts at Terminal 2, opened on Sunday (Oct 11). It runs parallel to offices providing ground handling services, Terminal 4 and Tanah Merah Country Club.

The Changi Jurassic Mile – a permanent outdoor display of 22 dinosaurs from nine species – is located between the Terminal 4 pit stop and the entrance to East Coast Park.

#deskerroad is located within the Rochore planning area in the Central Region of Singapore.1 This stretch of road was built after the completion of land reclamation works in the old Kampong Kapor area.2 It is laid out in an orthogonal (at right angles) manner between two main roads – Serangoon Road and Jalan Besar.3 It was named after Andre Filipe Desker, a former resident of the area and butchery owner in the 1860s.4 

Once notoriously known as a “red-light area”,5 Desker Road still retains its old-world charm with its rows of conserved terrace shophouses lining some parts of the road.6 In addition, it is the site where 88 flats under the public housing programme were built by the Housing and Development Board (HDB) in 1982.7 The prevailing vibrant landscape of Desker Road is linked to other commercial developments such as condominiums, restaurants, shopping and hotels, located within the areas around Jalan Besar, reflecting the current needs of the population it now serves.

post_caption:
【Sengkang #1 – Char Siew Noodle】
Situated at the North-Eastern part of Singapore, Sengkang was once occupied by fishing villages, rubber and pepper plantations. During the mid-20th century, this area was known as “Kangkar” which literally means “Foot of Harbour”.

Although with younger generations residing at this district, the love of local hawker food remains identical to any other part of Singapore. Sengkang has a wide array of hawker fare and even had their very first vending machines café for all the dabao-food lovers.

To kick-start our feature on Sengkang, we picked a traditional staple menu in most hawker centres – Char Siew Noodle.
 
A perfect serving of Char Siew Noodle contains egg noodles cooked al dente, tossed in flavoured sauce and topped with slices of yummy, slightly charred roast pork and leafy vegetables. Simple but satisfying!

Where is your favourite Char Siew Noodle stall? Comment below to tell us where to find this traditional dish. Stay tuned for our post when we reveal the stall name and learn about our behind-the-scenes process. See ya.

Stroll through the colourful enclaves of Joo Chiat/Katong, home to hipster cafés, historical shophouses and Peranakan culture.  Immerse into the beautiful culture,  blend of old and new. Family businesses and quaint shophouses sit alongside cool cafés and hip boutiques.

Alongside the walls, the beautifully painted mural art will wow you and selfie worthy. 

Most of the murals here are a result of the Katong Joo Chiat Art Circuit ( #KJCArtCircuit ) organised by The Admin SG – same folk who set up Gelam Gallery in the back alleys of Kampong Glam – and commissioned by the Singapore Tourism Board to revitalise this area.

Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. The lanterns display will depict traditional Chinese motifs and characters such as Chang’e, Goddess of the Moon in Chinese mythology, it will also illustrate this year’s theme – “family”, as a core element in getting Singaporean unite together as one big family to overcome the challenges ahead and emerge stronger.

Date: 17 September – 16 October 2020
Time: 7pm – 12mn (Daily)
Venue: Along New Bridge Road, Eu Tong Sen Street and South Bridge Road

[Kovan/Buangkok Precinct] Last Kampong in Singapore and amongst us

Rediscovery is about exploration and searching for new perspective to present it.

Do you know we still have kampong in Singapore? 

Do you know that the last kampong is right next to our public housing estate?

We have come a long way for housing in Singapore. It is great to rediscover the old kampong days of Singapore face to face. You can get to see those old road signage with 4 digit postal code ( Photo 1). It is amazing to find a real kampong amongst the green (photo2) It also  always surprised me that it is right next to our public housing estate ( Photo 3) . It is worth a visit before it is gone.

Recently, @slr_revolution had sent me @kasefiltersglobal’s 4-in-1 kit of clip-in ND filters to try out and I have to say I’m sold on them.
.
What impresses me is that are these filters can be mounted directly over the sensor, which bypasses the compatibility issues that traditional ND filters have. Additionally, they are much more compact and lightweight. 
.
Their innovative filter system also doubles down as a protective layer for your camera’s CMOS sensor. Whenever I am not using KASE’s ND filters, I have their UV filter mounted on my camera.
.
@slr_revolution is the sole distributor of @kasefiltersglobal’s products in Singapore and they have a great deal for you! From now till 15 Oct, use my  code “jethoon” to get 5% off any KASE filter you purchase.

Chilli crab, Hokkaido scallops, tiger prawns — Singaporeans are sure no strangers to seafood! But ever wonder where some of your favourite restaurants get their seafood from?

From Crystal Jade to The Ritz-Carlton, Hong Seafood has been supplying their frozen seafood to popular restaurant chains and luxury hotels here for more than three decades.

This humble family business started out only selling prawns, but now has over 30 types of seafood on its menu. Anyone hungry yet? 🤤

[Chinatown Precinct] - Past to present

Rediscovery is about looking for way to present a story. In this case, a story of past to present.

In the centre and background of the photo, it is the iconic public housing - Duxton that is built right in the heart of tanjong pagar. In the background, it is the  iconic “potato head”  pre-war shophouses with its beautiful and chic 5 foot walkway. This photo reminds us of Singapore’s progress from past to present. We should look forward to the near future when the pandemic is over and life goes back to normal again. Hope more people can continue to visit Singapore.

This isn't the most creative photo; they aren't the most innovative mooncakes. These are just simple, heartfelt photos that my son has taken, of my daughter and I working on the most traditional baked mooncakes. 

A full moon represents reunion for family, and these photos represent what I want most on Mid-Autum family. A simple wish of our family sitting, and celebrating this special day together.

【Ang Mo Kio #2 - Wanton Mee】
Feeling artsy? Then you really have to make a trip to the hawker centre at block 724. Beside the vibrantly-painted walkways and stone tables, check out the wall murals at the side of some of the iconic buildings in AMK-hood that have been around since the 80s.

Since we have covered the Singapore-style Wanton Mee two years ago, it's time we work on the next most popular style - Pontian Wanton Mee. This wanton mee chain is almost everywhere in Singapore now. This version of Pontian-style wanton mee comes with a savoury black sauce served with a fried dumpling. 

#dabaogram decided to give Pontian Wanton Mee a more refreshing look. We torched the BBQ pork, re-arranged the noodles, baked the leaves of the vegetables to give them a more crispy texture and topped our creation with some spring onions and flowers. Viola!

We would like to thank Pontian Wanton Mee for bringing these yummy bowls of noodles from across the Causeway. It means so much to us now especially when we are not able to travel, not even Johor Bahru. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‘dabaogram’ at home. 

Singapore, fried rice paradise? See ya next week!

Rubioideae is a subfamily of flowering plants in the Rubiaceae family and contains about 7600 species in 27 tribes.

1. Oldenlandia is a genus of flowering plants in this family. It is traditionally used in Chinese medicine.

2. Hedyotis (starviolet) is another. Many species of this genus such as Hedyotis biflora, H. corymbosa and H. diffusa are well known medicinal plants. 

The best I can figure is that these could be either genus, sort of cousins? 😅

新加坡剧团戏剧盒以“戏聚现场:参与式剧场的实践”重新想象如何逾越距离和社会接触💡

“戏聚现场：参与式剧场的实践”是一项由亚太区内各个参与社会的艺术工作者们齐聚一堂的虚拟聚会；同时也是大家在独处中进行独处中参与社会的一项艺术实践。以往，观众的聚集和存在都是重要元素，如今我们都被隔离，我们如何寻找参与社会其他的可能性？👥

一连7天的活动，3场体验式演出、6场工作坊、2场对话—— “戏聚现场”邀请大家一起前来探讨如何继续激发我们的同理心和想象力、克服距离、创造联系的方式、建立社群、以及互相合作的精神👍

Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on. 

Highlighting a few artworks

🅰 🆃🅰🅱🅻🅴 🆆🅷🅴🆁🅴 🅻🅸🆃🆃🅻🅴 🅿🅴🅾🅿🅻🅴 🅻🅸🆅🅴
The little people will jump onto your hand or object you place on the table. Check out the pan where you can cook an egg. 😁 This is just cute to the max!

🅻🅸🅶🅷🆃 🅱🅰🅻🅻 🅾🆁🅲🅷🅴🆂🆃🆁🅰
Push, bounce and roll the lighted balls to create your own orchestra! The kids couldn't stop running about to push the balls and watch them change colours. Too fun!

🆂🅺🅴🆃🅲🅷 🆃🅾🆆🅽
Watch your artwork ( buildings or vehicles) come to life on the big screen here. Just grab the paper and crayons provided and colour away. After scanning them, they appear on the screen and vehicles start to move around. It's amazing to see your creations come to life. 

Check out our IG TV for more! 

It was a well spent afternoon with family and we hope to go there and have another round of fun soon! 😁

post_caption:
A Living Space

Strolling along the streets of Kampong Gelam, one may find many shophouses providing all sorts of services such as hairstyling, food and drinks and souvenirs; there are also shophouses selling colourful Turkish lamps, mats, or aromatic perfumes and fragrances. What caught my eye on this particular trip, however, were the Turkish lamps that offered a dazzling array of colours -- it fitted perfectly in this district of vibrant walls and colourful shophouses.

For the employers and employees of the various shophouses, Kampong Gelam is not just a place for recreation. It's also a place of livelihood. It's a place where they spend most of their waking hours living. As seen here, this at times includes temporarily transforming these public spaces into their personal living space -- a space for prayer. It's a space to feel alive and to be alive.

For enlarged version, see InstaStory.

Old & New
Toa Payoh Lorong 6 Dragon Playground
(Singapore Heritage)

The dragon-shaped sand-based playground used to be a popular design for playgrounds in Ang Mo Kio and Toa Payoh.

After 1993, they were phased out due to safety concerns and it is believed that this Dragon Playground of Toa Payoh (located at Blk 28 Toa Payoh Lorong 6) is the only one of its kinds (sand-based) left in Singapore (The other two are laid with rubber mats).

The dragon playground was designed in 1979 by Housing and  Development Board’s (HDB) in-house designer Khor Ean Ghee (born 1935), who got his inspiration from the Oriental dragon commonly seen among the Chinese community in Singapore.

Beside the majestic dragon, there are two little plastic rides in the shapes of a seahorse and a pony for children to sit on.

The long body of the dragon is made of steel rails which form a passage for kids to get to the dragon head. Using the slide, kids can descend from the dragon head to the sandy ground.

The Toa Payoh dragon playground was picked by New York culture blog, Flavorwire.com, in 2013 as one of 15 amazing playgrounds from all over the world.

HDB Toa Payoh Apex (Background):

HDB Toa Payoh Apex is bounded by Lorong 6 Toa Payoh and Toa Payoh East, approximately 10 minutes (1.1km) walk away from Toa Payoh MRT Station. 

This development consist of 557 units of 3- and 4-room Standard Flats. All 4 blocks of flats come with three-quarter height windows in the living/ dining area and half-height windows in other rooms. Highest floor is 36 storey.

Just. can't. ignore. those. curves. snaking. 🤭

The initial destination was Kallang Riverside Park via PCN where available. It was a mistake! 😅 There were large sections where it was not continuous, and not only did I get lost and had to check with Google, I had to carry my bike up the overhead bridges which spanned the expressways! 💦 The sub 10kg bike made a HUGE difference! Once we got there, it seemed logical to carry on a little further to Marina Bay. 

It was very breezy and quiet at Kallang as well as Marina Bay and Merlion. It was obvious though from the very large bags of trash beside several bins that it was crowded earlier. It's a shame people can't pick up after themselves, or better yet, avoid disposables 😭

Decided to take the roads back, and made it back in half an hour, manual estimate 24 km/h average. A little bonus from Strava, I made it into the top 5 for 1 segment! 🤣 All because I wanted to get home to walk my dog and wasn't stopped by traffic lights!

As usual, Nerio and I were decked up like Xmas trees🌲
(Pics 4-6 on Samsung S20+ Pro mode, #Snapseed edit)

post_caption:
<364> 《走入时光隧道》

这是一条时光隧道。不信你试试看。

在时隔多年以后，我今早再次步入这一条从马林百列镇中心通往东海岸公园的地下人行通道。我人还没走出地道，便满满的青春回忆涌上心头。

还记得，你曾和朋友们结伴到东海岸，一起骑脚踏车、一起烤肉、一起唱歌、一起看海聊天、直到天明吗？还记得，那时候，谁和妳是如影随形的朋友吗？还记得，既期待自己也能碰上喜欢的人，又羡慕地看着谁和谁在一起了吗？这都是何其宝贵的青春回忆呀！

想回味的话，请进入这一条时光隧道吧！

<364> “Walking Into A Time Tunnel" 

This is a time tunnel. Try it, if you do not believe me.

After many years, I once again set foot on this underground walkway from Marine Parade town center to East Coast Park this morning. Before I got out of the tunnel, many memories from my youthful years were erupting. 

Do you remember yourself going to the East Coast Park with your friends together to ride bicycles, barbecue food, sing songs, watch the sea and chat ‘till dawn? Do you also remember the friend who was always sticking with you? And do you remember how you yearned to be with someone you like, while looking at your friends who had found someone they loved with envy? Those were the precious memories of youth!

If you would like to relive those memories, I suggest that you enter this time tunnel! 

<364> “Shíguāng suìdào”

Zhè shì yītiáo shíguāng suìdào. Bùxìn nǐ shì shìkàn.

Zài shí gé duōnián yǐhòu, wǒ jīn zǎo zàicì bù rù zhè yītiáo cóng mǎ lín bǎi liè zhèn zhōngxīn tōng wǎng dōng hǎi'àn gōngyuán dì dìxià rénxíng tōngdào. Wǒ rén hái méi zǒuchū dìdào, biàn mǎn mǎn de qīngchūn huíyì yǒng shàng xīntóu.

Hái jìdé, nǐ céng hé péngyǒumen jiébàn dào dōng hǎi'àn, yīqǐ qí jiǎotàchē, yīqǐ kǎoròu, yīqǐ chànggē, yīqǐ kàn hǎi liáotiān, zhídào tiānmíng ma? Hái jìdé, nà shíhòu, shéi hé nǎi shì rúyǐngsuíxíng de péngyǒu ma? Hái jìdé, jì qídài zìjǐ yě néng pèng shàng xǐhuān de rén, yòu xiànmù de kànzhe shéi hé shéi zài yīqǐle ma? Zhè dōu shì héqí bǎoguì de qīngchūn huíyì ya!

Xiǎng huíwèi dehuà, qǐng jìnrù zhè yītiáo shíguāng suìdào bà!

Bukit Brown Cemetery

Estimated to house 100,000 tombs in a vast land size of about 0.86 square kilometers, Bukit Brown Cemetery has been abandoned since its closure in 1973. It was opened in 1922 by the Municipal Council (Municipal Council oversaw the supplies of water, electricity, gas, maintenance of roads, lighting and other administrative things in Singapore before 1965).

The grandest and largest tomb site in Bukit Brown Cemetery lies on its tallest hill and covers an area of  600 square meters, roughly the size of ten, 3- bedroom HDB flats (public housing apartments).

Have always enjoyed eating chwee kueh but have not really had one that was memorable. Recently I kept seeing posts about an elderly uncle who sells chwee kueh at Taman Jurong Food Center. His chwee kuehs are very popular amongst those living around the area. Uncle actually makes the chwee kueh daily. Wanted to visit to support and also try out the famed chwee kuehs for myself. A good way to #supportlocal 😂 note that his shop doesn't exactly have a name but the sign says 水粿. Shop number #02-67!

Glad to say that the chwee kuehs were tasty! Enjoyed the smooth texture of the rice cakes that had a delicate chewy texture. The chye poh were for me both savoury yet sweet and surprisingly they were not too oily. Think the chilli which was on the sweeter side also went well with the kuehs. In all, it isn't something that will blow your mind but you can definitely taste the difference in quality as compared to other chwee kuehs. The contrasting savoury and sweetness in the chye poh gives it an edge over other versions too. 

Uncle manages the store by himself so waiting time could get long but it's worth the wait! His shop closes at 1.30pm daily so have to go early!

post_caption:
“The only surviving traditional Chinese mansion in Singapore, House of Tan Yeok Nee, was built in the 1880s and is an interesting Teochew-style residential building with an intricate roof with almost-straight ridges and wooden carvings. It’s just a small detour from Dhoby Ghaut and Fort Canning Hill! 

Teochew mooncakes come to my mind when I visit this Teochew private residence. Uniquely different from the other mooncakes, Teochew mooncakes are made with structurally layered, flaky puff pastry that signifies harmony and deep-fried to give it a golden-brown shade. Each mooncake is filled with lotus seed, mung bean, yam paste and salted duck egg yolk, such as this one from @mitzosg.”

Captured by @stormscape as part of #SingapoRediscovers – tell us if you’ve ever tried a Teochew mooncake in the comments below.

Sometimes happiness can be so simple ✨

I really miss taking campervan roadtrips and being on the road! Since it’s unlikely we’d get to travel this year, some creativity is needed to make this time count 🤔💭

We’ve been searching for ulu roads in SG with a scenic view where we can park the car and live a pretend “vanlife” even if just for a few hours. After checking out a few spots, it’s usually can park no view / got view can’t park / got view can park but super crowded and we’re starting to think it’s impossible... until we unexpectedly drove into this small park! It was exactly what we were looking for - quiet spot right by the waters of Seletar reservoir, overlooks the dam and wait for it... free parking! 😂🙌🏼

We popped open the boot, sat down and made tea. It turned out to be a simple, perfect kinda night.

Pero justo el viernes el Fullerton lanzó una oferta de 2x1(mucho más bonito que el Sands y también más caro de normal ), así que en el último momento reservamos y allí nos fuimos el domingo 😁

𝐄𝐱𝐩𝐥𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐋𝐢𝐭𝐭𝐥𝐞 𝐈𝐧𝐝𝐢𝐚: 𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐁𝐞𝐚𝐮𝐭𝐲 𝐢𝐧 𝐃𝐢𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐬𝐢𝐭𝐲

Took some time this week to visit the Little India precinct a.k.a. Tekka. As I strolled around, I bumped into this colorful house, which is known as the Former House of Tan Teng Niah. This colorful house is the last surviving Chinese Villa in the area, and the story inspires me a lot because it displayed how the small Chinese industries operated alongside the Indian cattle and rattan trade.

I then walked around the area a little bit more and never got bored of it. It always surprised me. For instance, I found a lot of beautiful murals such as the Cattleland 2, which shows several cows interacting with each other in different activities and created that sense of community.

"Pretty enjoyable exploration!", I must say. A place worth visit to everyone who wants to learn about what it means to have culture strongly amplified through the sense of diversity and belonging.

First timer at the hotspring. Heard its about 40 degrees at the foot dipping area, but I feel its more than that, as the hotspring source is already at 70 degrees. 

Most people dare not put their feet in entirely, because it really does feel like putting your foot in boiling water. I was hovering too initially, but got tired and decided to just plonk my feet in. Turned out it actually feels good. Sure does promote blood circulation because my feet became red like lobster after 30s of dipping. 

Take a container and some eggs along too to make some onsen eggs! 🥚🥚🥚

<353> “Probably one of the liveliest places in the heartland of Singapore”

This is a high-ceiling sheltered alley that is lined with a large diversity of small shops that provide every daily need and service you can imagine at the most affordable prices. 

Its most unique feature is the temporary stalls that are set up outside the shops where the sellers promote all sorts of interesting things of the season. 

The place is always bursting at seams in the weekends from morning to the evening. Lured by its local vibes, even on a weekday, there is no short of human traffic.

I would confidently say that it is probably one of the liveliest shopping arcades in the heartland of Singapore. If you drop by, let me show you around.

William

It’s the mooncake of course! Something we always look forward to every Mid-Autumn Festival 😆

I remember when I was kid, we would gather in front of the house enjoying the bright moonlight, steamed peanut was a must and sometimes we had nice moo cakes too. My father would tell some old Chinese folktales, I should have written them all, can’t remember many now. Wish could do that with my kids but... err... that would mean the HDB corridor? 😅

Anyway today was a fun day out at #ChinatownSG after mostly playing at home. It was also so good that we didn’t really have crowd of tourists, and hence we spent the afternoon fooling around. Indeed it was a good idea to have a little #SingapoRediscovers time at Chinatown today. I guess this is how we enjoyed this year’s#ChinatownMAF2020, a bit different from past years but still we had a lot of fun... and food, yeah.  That was a big Yum Cha, I’m still full until now!

Singapore’s oldest Hindu temple was built in 1827 by immigrants from the Nagapatnam and Cuddalore districts of South India. The Sri Mariamman Temple is dedicated to Goddess Mariamman, known for her power in curing epidemic illnesses and diseases

During the colonial times, it served as a refuge for new immigrants, hosted community activities and acted as the Registry of Marriages for Hindus when it was the only authorised venue to solemnise Hindu marriages

Trishaw Uncle (三轮车大叔) a tribute to all trishaw riders, for providing transport services rain or shine, from the time before cars, buses and trains back in the olden days.
In Singapore, children are taught to address elders as “Uncles” and “Aunties” as a form of respect. “Trishaw Uncle” is a term of endearment for the trishaw riders who formed the early backbone of Singapore’s labour force, using their manual strength to get people to places.

During my younger days I had my trishaw expedition through the colourful, quaint and bustling streets of Singapore, from Chinatown to Little India, experienced the nostalgic memories and dynamic aspirations of our country in a very different way.

Today is the 15th day of the 8 month in the Chinese calendar. It is the day set aside for family reunions, but also the time when the moon is at its most bright.  The Mid Autumn Festival or Moon Festival will have people gather to sample autumn harvests. In our case, most people here enjoy mooncakes, consisting of many tasty flavors 😋 Usually it is a crazy travelling moment all across Asia but I guess this year is quite a special year eh?!

Happy Mid Autumn Festival to all our friends out there. What is the best tasting mooncake you have had? Have you had one before?

Sembawang Hot Spring Park
Gambas Avenue, Singapore

In 1998, the Ministry of Defence (Mindef) acquired the land containing the spring for the expansion of the nearby Sembawang Air Base, leaving F&N with less than 4 hectares (10 acres) of land. Its water-bottling plant survived until the early 1990s however. In January 2002, locals' interest to the hot spring, which had caught the attention of Singaporeans after the surrounding land had been cleared to begin the RSAF air base extension. Sembawang community leaders gathered signatures to petition Mindef, which was going to fence off the area, to preserve & develop the hot spring for the general public. Mindef gave the green light to the appeals & opened a small side gate pavement for the public to access the spring.

During that same year, a series of scalding cases, including an incident in which a senior citizen diabetic lost six toes to gangrene after soaking in the hot spring, prompted the Singapore General Hospital to warn that people with nerve disorders or diseases affecting blood circulation should be cautious to hot mineral springs. As a result of some negative rumors and hearsay, and the RSAF redevelopment, public interest began to wane & the number of visitors dwindled.

With overseas travel off limits for a while to come, CNA journalists Matthew Mohan and Gaya Chandramohan set off on a marathon walk around Singapore to see how appealing their home really is. 
 
Click on the link in bio to read the story and follow the liveblog. And don't forget to check in on our Instagram Stories too!

Looking for a unique dining experience? Try underwater dining at Ocean Restaurant, a seafood restaurant that will allow you to soak in the graceful movements of the manta rays and sharks swimming by. Another fun place would be Sushi Airways, an airplane themed restaurant that serves high-quality sushi, with fresh fish flown in from Japan multiple times weekly! With the global situation keeping us grounded, this is another way to feel the nostalgia of travelling while enjoying a great meal!⁣
⁣
Don’t be fooled by the photos – Pollen restaurant is actually indoors, not outdoors. Located in the Flower Dome at Gardens by the Bay, this is the perfect place to treat yourself or a loved one.⁣

Had an awesome morning at @nestopia_sg at @sentosa_island today! The girls had a ball of a time climbing nets, crossing bridges and sliding down slides (one's pretty fast and steep, they say!). Being outdoors at 10am was rather hot though, especially with face masks on 😅 But they lasted for the hour we were booked for!
.
Honestly, I wasn't sure I'd visit Nestopia when I first heard about it as you have to pay entrance fees ($9-10/hr) - Singapore has loads of free outdoor playgrounds after all 😆. We decided to visit after redeeming the free NDP Sentosa tokens (go redeem yours if you haven't!) which covered entry for two kids (one adult can enter free with a kid). When we got there, I was pretty impressed by the playground structure. It looked about two stories high which made it really exciting for the kids. And there’s something about playing at a playground with the beach in the background - felt like we were on holiday somewhere! The kids enjoyed themselves so much they wanted to return another time - I said okay, if there is promo on the entrance fees 😋
.
It wasn't crowded the Tuesday school holiday morning we were there with only around 8 kids. Apparently late afternoon weekends are pretty popular though. There's a capacity limit of 15 kids now, so do call ahead to book a slot if you're planning to visit 😊
.
Are you enjoying your Sep holiday so far? 😉
.

"I will be embarking on a journey with @stb_sg this Mid-Autumn by pairing various mooncakes with different parts of Singapore! Join me as we discover stories behind our culture and heritage, and watch how our unique mooncakes ‘blend in’ around our city!

Singaporean pastry chef @janicewong2am is no stranger to us, known for her desserts that are in the form of edible art. Her collection of mooncakes this year are infused with our local flavours such as Cheng Tng Red Date Yam, Red Bean Tea, Peanut Pancake and Rose Bandung.

These pretty mooncakes reminded me of Singapore as a garden city.”

Captured by @stormscape for #SingapoRediscovers.

#beautiful #temple of the #earth #god sitting with a moat. It was raining heavily, but it is a picture of #tranquility in the raging rain. It feels like overseas, and I wish I have more time to walk about and explore rather than the 15 mins or so I visit the island every 10 years or so. 

The middle aged couple living there tending to the temple must be feeling quite isolated from life on the mainland. The uncle I spoke to says it needs getting used to. But then I was also thinking, you get a peaceful life and an island to yourselves, isnt that great? Maybe in freedom, there is also a responsibility (manning the temple), and maybe isolation and peaceful life isn't such a great thing?

To chase your Monday blues away, here’s a photo of our beautiful national flower, Papilionanthe Miss Joaquim, to brighten up your day!

You can see it, together with about 600 other species and hybrids, on display at the National Orchid Garden located in the Singapore Botanic Gardens. Make sure you have enough juice on your mobile phone because you will take lots of photos for sure!

Admiring the beautiful art pieces at this lantern festival at Chinatown with your family and love ones... We fall in love with people we can admire and who can bring the same level of commitment to building a life together enjoying every moment together.
中秋快乐！
Chinatown Mid-Autumn Festival 2020.
@chinatown_festivals
Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. The lanterns display will depict traditional Chinese motifs and characters such as Chang’e, Goddess of the Moon in Chinese mythology, it will also illustrate this year’s theme – “family”, as a core element in getting Singaporean unite together as one big family to overcome the challenges ahead and emerge stronger.
Date: 17 September – 16 October 2020
Time: 7pm – 12mn (Daily)
Venue: Along New Bridge Road, Eu Tong Sen Street and South Bridge Road

Have a RAWRSOME Monday! 🦖
#littlehayashisushi
#momandson
#firstborn
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
We were at @rwsentosa USS last Friday. I was surprised that Sushi had so much fun and was so brave in trying out the rides! I thought we were gonna be on the carousel for 10 times to make our $66 worth it. However, he surprised me when he requested to take the roller coaster at Jurassic World (the legs dangling one). I checked many times as we were queuing to make sure he know what were taking because I was super scared. Guess what? He loved it and I was the one screaming my lungs out. He requested to go again, and refused to get off the 2nd round 😅#thingsmomwoulddoforkids 
He came home and told everyone that he took the rollercoaster and he protected mama because mama was screaming. Such a sweet darling! 
I am just glad to have spent some quality time with him, even if it meant messy hair, sweaty face, getting blisters on my feet, having heat rash and running around to catch the meet n greet despite my burning achilles, it is ALL WORTH IT to see how much he enjoyed himself. ❤️
If you are heading down, do remember to purchase the tickets with @mastercard to receive a complimentary halloween special mask and a gudetama notebook! Head down at 12pm to meet n greet the characters and trick n treat with the Candy Ambassadors and have early access to the rides!🎃👻 I must say that they did a good job with the crowd control and safe distancing within the compound, because the queue was a maximum of 30min wait and we didn’t see crowds anywhere. Thank you safe distancing ambassadors for keeping us safe while we play. #thankful
Most importantly, don’t forget to bring an extra set of clothes and MASK for both you and your kids! You don’t want to wear a sweat soak mask for 5hrs... #notsponsored #justsharing #thanksforreading #happymonday

House of Tan Teng Niah

This vividly colorful house is located at Little India and was constructed in 1900 by a local businessman named Tan Teng Niah. It underwent a full restoration during the 1980s to what people see today. This vibrant and beautiful building has stood the test of time, representing hope and resilience. 

Conservational buildings, like the House of Tan Teng Niah, are being preserved to keep a balance between the modern and traditional structures. These buildings are valued because of their history and their significant impact to which I believe more people, not only locals but tourists too, should rediscover and learn more about. The intrinsic and unique design of these buildings will surely captivate your eyes.

@chinatown_festivals
Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. The lanterns display will depict traditional Chinese motifs and characters such as Chang’e, Goddess of the Moon in Chinese mythology, it will also illustrate this year’s theme – “family”, as a core element in getting Singaporean unite together as one big family to overcome the challenges ahead and emerge stronger.
Date: 17 September – 16 October 2020
Time: 7pm – 12mn (Daily)
Venue: Along New Bridge Road, Eu Tong Sen Street and South Bridge Road

3 Homegrown Halal Beauty Brands for Your Consideration

The 2020 consumer of the beauty insider is now more choice-conscious than ever, and beauty brands big and small are rushing to serve their needs. From Fenty with their groundbreaking foundations for nearly any skin type, to Lush’s focus on the environment and animal-free testing, there’s a product to suit almost everyone’s preference on the market now. It’s no wonder that the Halal cosmetics industry is worth USD$16.3 billion (SGD22.3 billion) in 2018, with some report suggesting its size may even reach over $50 billion (SGD$68.4 billion) by 2025. Local brands are rising to the occasion too. Tropika Club digs deep to find you 3 homegrown Halal beauty brands for your consideration, whether you’re Muslim, or not!

Me the local tourist, tired, exhausted, hungry. 

The whole plan of visiting Pearl’s Hill City Park is to walk myself tired so that I can have a good meal. 

And the meal has to be at @195pearlhillcafe ! 

A big THANK YOU to Benjamin for sharing your knowledge and helping me with the reservation for Dec. Although this was the first time I met him, but I trusted him with the food recommendations! 

If you are there, and have no reserved the pork satays, don’t worry, you can always go for the chicken satay, and THEY ARE REALLY GOOD! Oh... the pineapple satay sauce... man... old school taste... 

Had carbonara prepared by Chef L, and that small portion is actually a lot. 

Ben managed to get me some pork satay which some customers let go, and these pork satay is different from the traditional ones we have... 
I’m not going to share more, you have to try it yourself! 

Love the quiet environment which allows me to do some of my work. If it’s not of the rain, I would have stay a little longer. 

I’ll be back. 
.

LED Light Mask: The Latest Beauty Craze Around the World

Making use of light power to enhance your skin and also skin health might appear like very little greater than a science-fiction pipe dream. But that’s precisely what Team Tropika Club is seeking to find out. Points first, allow’s obtain clear on the essentials: LED light treatment itself is commonly supplied in dermatologist workplaces as a skin rejuvenator that functions in an extremely uncomplicated method. As well as even if you’ve been listening to much more about the treatment as of late, understand that it’s actually not new whatsoever. “Essentially we utilize these various light powers to treat different conditions, and it works by regulating or transforming cellular activity,” says board-certified skin specialist Melissa Levin, MD. “So it could feel like a ‘trend’ since you’re seeing it a lot more, yet it’s actually an actually old treatment that we understand a great deal around.”

#SingapoRediscovers journey sans the vouchers checking out the historical constitutional documents and oil paintings of Singapore.

I saw the treaty letter in 1819, the surrender document, the proclamation of merger with federation of Malaya, the draft letter to separate and our proclamation of independence. The latter gave me the damn chills.

At the Siapa Namu Kamu exhibition, especially love the National Language Class painting and how it defined the sign of the times when nationalism was strong and there was a collective desire among our parents and grandparents to forge a national identity. #nationalgallery #singapoliday #art #culture #museum #singaporediscovers #singapoliday

post_caption:
Rediscovering Joo Chiat/Katong and Kampong Gelam

📍Joo Chiat / Katong
•Former Queen's Theatre - one of the main entertainment places in Geylang from 1930 to 1982
•Mindanao Gum Heritage Tree (Rainbow Tree) - has distinctive peeling bark with multi-coloured streaks. Why are there so many colours? This is because the patches of outer bark are shed at different times, showing the bright-green inner bark which matures to give blue, purple, orange and then maroon tones.
•Archeological Dig for Fort Tanjong Katong - remnants of Fort Tanjong Katong which stood from 1879 to 1901, was one of the oldest military forts built by the former British colonial  government of Singapore

📍Kampong Gelam
•Masjid Sultan (Golden Mosque)- focal point for Singapore’s Muslim community. The onion-shaped dome base is decorated with glass bottle ends, donated by lower-income Muslims during its construction so that all Muslims, not just the rich, could contribute.
•Streetside Barber - the last of Singapore's streetside barber shop ($6.00 only! open everyday except Wed and Sun)

Isn't it amazing that there's a piece of history in almost all corners of Singapore? Behind the industrialization and development the country is going through, may the memories of yesteryears be kept alive for the next generations to see.
.

Another spot at #ToaPayoh Central that has transformed over the years.

The spot where the local @courtssg outlet occupied used to be the post office which in front of it stood a sculpture of a man lifting a woman, although I am quite sure the post office was not the first occupant of the old building.

The two housing blocks at the back of the picture used to be two of four accommodated the athletes competing in the 1973 SEAP Games.

Lastly, the two-storey building on the right of the picture used to house the local outlet of the now-defunct Emporium (英保良) departmental store.

⏩ If you like and follow this page after you chanced upon, thanks and it's all fated 🙂⏪

Mention Singapore and most people would immediately associate it with skyscrapers and high-rise flats, But what if we told you that you can still find a kampong (village) beyond the bustling city? Kampong Lorong Buangkok is mainland Singapore's last village that has withstood the test of time. The kampong is surrounded by HDB flats and is still home to 26 families today. Click the link in bio to find out how to get there and more!⁠

2020 has been an absolute rollercoaster of a year, as the world recovers from a depression — both literally and figuratively. This only makes festive occasions all the more precious, as we realise who the most important people in our lives are: family.

Being the only immediate kin I have, my mother has been the person I've spent the most time with over the last few years. This year has made that the case even more so, due to us being responsible people and staying home almost 24/7.

Taking the time to head out to Chinatown was a welcome break from the routine of staying home, made even more special by her agreeing to be photographed — trust me, this is especially rare.

As such, I'll be spending this Mid-Autumn Festival 2020 with the most important person in my life, as she rounds out her last few decades here with me.

I find myself in a bar at the end of Mondays all the time.

The Changi Jurassic Mile was opened last Sunday and we decided to check it out. It was pretty crowded on a weekday evening. If you are planning to cycle with the kids, do take note that you might need to get off and on the bicycle lots of time and you’ll need to look out for other cyclists, especially those who speeds along the narrow park connector. 

 Here’s a short clip of the 1km trail. More in IGstory. Enjoy! 🦕

Day 2 #BalloInSingapore 
I did not know we had such amazing hiking trails within Singapore till few of my friends(Shuchi Kapoor  Seema Balani) decided to explore the place . It was love at first sight when I looked at the pics and I decided that it was my next destination in Singapore to explore.
 MacRitchie reservoir is a place to enjoy tranquility if walking above a lush green foliage.I bumped into monkeys, monitor lizard and squirrels .
Macritchie can be termed Singaporean cousin of famous Cloud forest trail in Laos.
A must visit place says Ballo  either early in morning or evening ( before sunset) with your friends and family .

Five international dance troupes will be celebrating this Mid-Autumn Festival "together" by putting up an online Chinese dance performance on 30 September 2020 (Eve of the Mid-Autumn Festival). 

The concert will feature dances from Atlanta Chinese Dance Company (USA), 一般社団法人 中国舞踊サロン Chinese Dance Salon - CDS (Tokyo, Japan), 澳門英姿舞園 Macau Ieng Chi Dance Association (Macau SAR), 新加坡华族舞蹈剧场 Singapore Chinese Dance Theatre (Singapore), and Shadow Danceland 影子舞团 (Mauritius).

Do join us at our respective Facebook page on 30 September 2020 at SGT 8pm (GMT +8) to watch the “live” stream. Don’t miss it!

www.scdt.com.sg

post_caption:
Tee Seng Store is one of Singapore’s oldest provision stores. Located in a quiet private housing estate, this modest shop has been operated by Mr Ang Lu Heng since 1955.
.
Provision shops – known colloquially as mini-marts, mama shops, or zhap hueh diam (杂货店) – are witnesses to our memories, both personal and shared. Many of us often take these provision shops for granted, only remembering how important they are when we need an ice-cold drink, the occasional bottle of soya sauce, or that essential packet of coconut milk for our curries.
.
Many of us also grew up with the uncles and aunties who ran the provision shops – just like Mr Ang here. The octogenarian wakes up at 5am daily to practice qigong before opening his store at 8am like clockwork. Over the years, Mr Ang has built up a small but loyal following of customers, whose names and orders he knows by heart. This is the familiarity that modern supermarket chains and convenience stores cannot give. Because what the humble provision shop lacks in newfangled products, it more than makes up for in faithfulness and a wealth of memories.
.
Stepping into Tee Seng Store was like taking a trip down memory lane. Mr Ang once used a Milkmaid tin that dangled from the ceiling to store cash. Now, he uses a cash register. I was fortunate to have Mr Ang’s permission to take pictures of his store while he worked. These pictures are precious reminders of days gone by.
.
Rediscovering Singapore does not have to be anything grand. To me, it is about revisiting these living artefacts of Singapore’s past and getting reacquainted with these simple but deeply cherished memories of growing up.
.

You want to get started with night photography but not to spend that long 4 hours. 

I get it !

So I came up with a 2 hours workshop

What we’ll do... 

I’ll coach you the basic elements of night photography, providing you with tips and techniques of low light and long exposure photography. 

We will be working on camera settings to create different effects to capture fascinating images as the day changes from twilight hour into the night. 

What you’ll get...

At the end of the workshop, you will acquire the knowledge to capture light trails, to create the effect of light burst and silky waters, creating stunning colour tones to your night images as well as capturing modern and historical architecture illuminated with colourful lights that adorned the cityscape.

No filter required!

Just practical stuff from your in-camera settings.

Where we’ll be...

This workshop takes place at one of Singapore's most vibrant quays along the Singapore River, within a vicinity that is surrounded by historical and modern architecture. 

The location provides you with all the required subjects of interest to photograph in low light and to acquire the skills of night photography.

What others said....

Don’t just hear this from me. 

Swipe to your left to read what participant has to say about this workshop.

All that for $120 per person.

And that’s not the end of us...

I keep the communication channel open for all my workshops’ past and present participants. 

Participants still text or email me from time to time, checking in on unclear camera setups, asking for opinions and reviews of their work. 

Book your spot through info@carolinepang.com

post_caption:
Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷千秋
九月初🗓🙏🙏🙏

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

Commuting by public transport again recently.. Appreciating those ME time moments on my way back and forth daily..⁣
⁣
Do you realize art galore happening at almost every MRT station in Singapore?⁣
⁣
And this is one of them.. ⁣
At Newton station, the artist created a monochrome drawing of the area in year 2200. The 11m by 9m picture forms the backdrop to the station's escalators and commuters can marvel at the artist imagined city, comprising layers of stacked buildings with snaking highways.⁣
⁣
Don’t you love that crossing escalator with art at the background? To be honest it was very easy to take this photo with zero human traffic at escalator, just need to wait for the off-peak timing in between train arrival.⁣
⁣
Which one is your favourite MRT station in Singapore?

📍 Newton MRT (Downtown Line) ⁣

found at 尖沙咀港式炭烧烧腊 TST Roasted Food Pte Ltd at Food Scholar aircon foodcourt @ West Coast Plaza 2nd floor. Ample sheltered carpark lots during weekdays lunch time on a rainy day 🙂

Decent flavour and meat texture for this good portion meal at aircon foodcourt. Cucumber texture is pleasantly crunchy. Soft rice texture to compliment and absorb the fragrant duck sauce 👍💡
Affordable and value-for-money, I’ll be back again 👌😃 
This food stall also sells Whole Herbal Roasted Duck @ S$44, suitable for family / friends gathering potluck dish.

【Ang Mo Kio #4 - Ngoh Hiang】
With Singaporeans' love of crispy flavourful fried food items, no wonder Ngoh Hiang is such a popular dish here! You can find it in almost every hawker centre in Singapore. Tell us about YOUR favourite neighbourhood Ngoh Hiang stall!

Did you have a hard time figuring out how we piled up the vermicelli? Here is what we did: First, we stacked some fish cakes to make a tower and covered the entire structure with vermicelli. We then balanced the all-time-favourite crispy prawn cracker on the tower and gingerly arranged all the other ingredients on top. Reminds us of those elegant ladies' hats at the Kentucky Derby races! To add some greens to the dish, we added some leaves from our backyard. If you watched the video, you would see the pink sweet sauce make a special appearance towards the end.

We would like to thank S11 Coffee Shop Jin Long Wu Xiang stall near Cheng Sa Market for preparing and serving such wide variety of Ngoh Hiang items. This is an un-sponsored series in which we hope to raise awareness of our rich local hawker food culture and help local hawkers during this unprecedented period. Join us on this journey of rediscovery where we dabao and transform our local favourites into works of gastronomic art, one district at a time. Tag us in your post if you would try your own ‘dabaogram’ at home. 

We hope you’ve enjoyed our tour in Ang Mo Kio so far, take part in our IG Story poll to share with us which is your favourite dish! 

Next stop, Seng Kang! See you soon!

post_caption:
#SingapoRediscovers: 新加坡政府派钱让你去玩?! 😍

新加坡政府掏出3亿2000万元，推行“重新探索新加坡”消费券计划，补贴让本地人在国内旅游😲 那到底这是什么计划？小编划了以下重点让你一目了然：

1）18岁及以上的新加坡公民获100元旅游消费券
✔可购买景点门票、导览及支付酒店住宿

2）孩童和青年的门票有10元津贴
✔每人最多可购买6张儿童或青年优惠门票

💰派发方式：
👉所有消费卷将通过SingPass分发，每张面额为10元
👉可用于恢复营业的酒店、景点和导览行程
👉领取详情将在11月公布

⌛有效日期：
👉今年12月至明年6月底

✌可到哪儿玩？
👉国内已有214家酒店、40个景点和438个导览行程获旅游局批准，恢复营业。

详情可见以下网址：

🏨酒店
https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/home-pages/approved-hotels.html

🚣景点：
https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/home-pages/approved-attractions.html

😍导览行程：
https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/home-pages/approved-travel-agents-tour-operators-and-tourist-guides.html

This place used to be crowded with tourists and locals. Since the Covid19 pandemic, you see much fewer crowds, and thus opportunity for a cleaner shot without distracting elements. This is the best chance to re-discover the place again before the crowd returns ;)

22 on 22. Did you know that this large halo that appeared around the sun and seen by many in Singapore at around noon today (22 Sep) is what scientists call a “22-degree halo”? (Because the ring has a radius of approximately 22 degrees around the sun.) So yup, 22 on 22👽
.
What causes this phenomenon? Millions of tiny ice crystals in cirrus clouds that refract and reflect light in just the right orientation and position with respect to your eye for the halo to be visible.
.
Stay safe, and look up, people. You won’t find rainbows on the ground.
.
.
.
.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
龍南殿九皇大二帝爷圣诞 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

<359> “Have You Seen Any Crocodile?” 

Daunted by the inaccessibility of public transport and the fear of mosquito bites in a swampy forest, I had avoided visiting Sungei Buloh Wetland for a long time. 

Today, I was delighted to discover a new entrance to the wetland at Kranji Reservoir. And it was a pleasure to walk above the mudflat by crossing a suspension bridge and a coastal boardwalk. Thankfully, too, there were no mosquitoes today! Rather, there were butterflies and birds.

A passer-by asked me, looking disappointed, “I see many signboards cautioning about crocodiles. But I spotted none so far. Had you seen a crocodile?”

Bemused by his question, I shook my head and let out a laugh. 

William

Buddha Relic Tooth Temple

"Rediscover and appreciating one of the hidden beauty and gem of Singapore. Such a beautiful and magnificent structure"

This Tang-styled Chinese Buddhist temple is located in the historic district of Chinatown, Singapore. It has richly designed interiors and comprehensive exhibits on Buddhist art and history which tell stories of culture over thousands of years old. The building’s design was inspired by the Buddhist Mandala, a symbol of Buddhist culture that represents the universe.

Singapore as we all know is a place rich in culture with people still embracing the principles and beliefs passed to them through generations. Prayer is an integral part of the their culture - regardless of what religion you are in. Temples are found all over Singapore and their distinct beauty shines through despite being surrounded by modern buildings. It is a place of worship and where people spend time with their loved ones such as offering incense and attend meditations. Visiting these temples will help you to understand and experience the culture and beliefs of the people In Singapore.

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct] The Red House of Katong.

Rediscovery is about exploring angles and lighting of presenting the subjects. I was not very happy with shooting with the road divider( photo3)

I have visited this location a few times. Finally, I found the right lighting and angle (photo 1 and 2) to capture this iconic building. 

The Red House Bakery is a popular reference to the iconic confectionery shop, Katong Bakery & Confectionery. It was a popular breakfast place amongst Singaporeans living in the eastern part of Singapore, especially for its signature cakes and curry puffs. It was established in 1925 but closed on 23 March 2003 after the shophouse where it was occupying was deemed as unsafe. It has since reinvented itself. Currently, it houses a bakery cafe - Micro Bakery & Kitchen Red House

“Cantonese mooncakes are most commonly seen in Singapore. The golden brown pastry is filled with lotus paste and an optional salted duck egg, glazed with egg yolks before baking. Apart from lotus paste, the less common red date paste is also used as Cantonese mooncake filling. The red date paste gives it a dark red tone with slight fruity and citrus taste.

Chinatown is where many of us have gathered for Mid-Autumn Festival. While this year’s celebrations may be different, the community and family spirit of this occasion is very much alive. From the tradition of carrying lanterns, eating mooncakes together and solving Mid-Autumn riddles, I hope everyone is rediscovering Singapore and this festival in your own ways!”

🏮🌝花好月圆。Celebrating Mid-Autumn Festival at Gardens by the Bay. Even though celebrations are a lot muted this year due to the pandemic, it didn’t stop us and many others from heading to GBTB for the lantern light up that starts at 7pm every evening.

We were greeted by “Apricot Grove” featuring pink apricot flowers where the soft pink background makes for a welcoming entrance. Don’t forget to look up for the Colonnade of Lights  showcasing 1,500 beautiful paper lanterns painted by people from various walks of life. The kaleidoscope of colours from Illuminations of Joy was so mesmerising and the concept is inspired by traditional cellophane lanterns. Don’t miss the cute Prosperity Rats which are at the far end near Floral Fantasy! GBTB Mid-Autumn display is from now till 4 Oct. Are you planning to go too?
