A walk down memory lane. Traditional provision stores once central to the livelihoods of residents residing in villages, now serve primarily as a relic of our city’s past.

Looking for hidden photography spots in Singapore, while hoping to win attractive prizes at the same time? We’ve got you covered! Together with the Singapore Tourism Board, we’ve worked with @aikbengchia to put together an itinerary of 10 spots across 6 local precincts for you. Check out our LINK IN BIO to download the full itinerary to begin exploring these “Hidden Gems!”

You don’t have to limit yourselves to these locations though - any "hidden spots" within the 6 precincts are welcome.
 
From now until 4 October, you can submit your photo entries for the contest. To do so, visit at least 2 of the 6 precincts featured and share at least 2x original shots captured in your own style (we’ve included example photo spots in the itinerary, but your photos can be captured at other spots as well). These can be carousel-style posts or separate posts – the more the better! 
 
Do also ensure that you:
1. Follow both @stb_sg and @sg_photocommunity on Instagram.
2. Tag both accounts in your post and include the hashtags #SPCRediscovers and #SingapoRediscovers.
3. In the post caption, share what rediscovering Singapore means to you.
 
Winners will be chosen based on the most creative visual along with the best accompanying caption.
 
If your shots are chosen, you have a chance to win the following attractive prizes:
 
-1st Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Marina Bay Sands (worth over SGD $339)
-2nd Prize: 1 x One Night Stay at Mandarin Orchard Singapore (worth over SGD $280)
-3rd Prize: 2 x Tickets to Universal Studios Singapore (worth up to SGD $162)
-Consolation Prizes:
 * 4th, 5th, 6th, 7th prizes: #InstaWalk Bugis, Waterloo and Kampong Gelam Tribe Tours (worth $55 per ticket)
 * 8th, 9th and 10th prizes: Tickets to Trick Eye Museum Singapore (worth up to $25 per ticket)
 
We’re really looking forward to seeing your shots over the next three weeks, and hope you’re inspired to get out and explore!
 
Check out the link in our bio if you have any questions. You can find more info in the Terms & Conditions section under “How to Enter” and see some sample shots with more details on the itinerary as well.
 
Good luck! Contest ends 4 October 2020, 2359 hours (GMT+08:00).

“Ever seen a mooncake as large as this? Originating from the largest dialect group in Singapore, the Hokkien mooncake is also known as the Scholar Cake, distributed to those who sat for the Imperial examinations in ancient China.

Each Hokkien mooncake is made of candied winter melon, tangerine peel, melon and sesame seeds, sugar, and lard. I chose the Hokkien mooncake from the 89-year-old Tan Hock Seng Shop at Telok Ayer and was greeted by a warm and cheery old lady. She asked if I was getting it for my grandparents as youngsters these days generally do not know these old-school traditional confectioneries.

As a Hokkien-lang, I still remember my grandmother giving me a slice (because it’s really much bigger than the usual mooncakes) when I was young during Mid-Autumn Festival. This brings back lots of childhood memories, including old-school, heritage playgrounds such as the one shaped like a watermelon in Tampines. Traditions will be lost forever if we do not continue to preserve it and upkeep them.“

Captured by @stormscape for #SingapoRediscovers. Comment below and share with us your childhood Mid-Autumn memories.

Find out more in our Instagram Stories.

牛车水 Murders is a new #gametour where participants are thrown into a scenario to solve puzzles. The scene is Chinatown where a serial killer is on the loose and the whole nation is gripped with fear. Participants are roped in to find the killer by solving a series of puzzles around Chinatown

Played in teams of 2 – 5 persons, participants determine the route they take, and the choice of items to pick. Narrated throughout by our tourist guide/gamemaster, the guide will dive into a character throughout. This character has strong ties in Chinatown having lived there for 48 years and through the guide, he/she shares their affiliation through the people the guide knew and grew up with. Characters include Samsui woman Auntie Geok, moneylender friend Raj, provision shop owner Ah Kee and others

Every Friday, Saturday and Sunday 1000 – 1200hrs Suitable for age 7 and up. Book your challenge now #linkinbio

[Joo Chiat/Katong Precinct]  Ancient South Indian Temple architectural with a respect for harmonious coexistence re-discovered

Rediscovery is about relooking and appreciate the coexistence of interesting elements in an environment

I learned about Sri Senpaga only recently and decided to re-discover this amazing temple built with ancient South Indian temple architectural style that flourished in the 7th-century Chola dynasty. This temple was established in the 1850s by Ceylonese Tamils from Sri Lanka which explains the differences  from the usual Hindu temple that I have seen.

 Two things captured my attention. Firstly, it is the  21-metre tall, five-tiered structure at the main entrance that looks amazing with the glow from the morning sun. The intrigued details are very impressive. 
Secondly, it was the signage that says “All are welcome”. You need to read the signage in detail to be impressed by how welcoming they are regardless of different race and religion. That signage as well as the temple represents what is unique about Singapore - Our harmonious  coexistence of different races and religions into what is Singapore.

Hope to visit this temple more
